<FIRST>r a AM-Boggs-Attack     06-12 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boggs-Attack,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Threatened Red Sox Slugger Gets 25 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who held a knife to the throat of
Boston Red Sox third baseman Wade Boggs outside a bar was sentenced
Monday to 25 years in prison.
   George Young Jr., 23, pleaded no contest to two charges of
aggravated battery and one count of burglary in the Dec. 28
incident, which left Boggs with a slight cut on his neck. A
no-contest plea is not an admission of guilt but can be used as such
for the purpose of sentencing.
   Under sentencing guidelines, Young faced three years in prison.
   But because he had been out of prison less than three months
before the December attacks, Assistant State Attorney Ralph Grabel
asked acting Circuit Judge J. Edward Philman to use state law to go
well above the recommended sentence.
   Philman said his sentence was based more on the violence of the
crime than the stature of Boggs, an All-Star third baseman and one
of baseball's top hitters.
   ``The fact that he had been released so recently on a violent
crime and then went out and committed another even more violent
crime, I determined him to be a danger to society,'' Philman said
after the sentencing.
   Young fell well within the the requirements for an extended
sentence since he had been released in September from prison on a
1985 conviction of aggravated battery with a firearm and a later
escape charge, Grabel said.
   Philman sentenced Young to 15 years on the aggravated battery of
Boggs and another 10 years in prison for the assault on Stephen
Minardi, a passenger in Boggs' jeep who attempted to help the
athlete.
   The judge ordered Young to serve an additional five years on
probation for a burglary charge related to entering Bogg's jeep
during the assault.
   According to police reports of the incident, Boggs was inside his
vehicle showing his friends a handgun when Young and another man
began talking to Boggs.
   The men left, but a short time later pulled up in a vehicle and
parked in front of Boggs' Jeep, blocking him. When a passenger in
Boggs' vehicle got out to talk to the men, Young brandished a knife.
   Police say Young got into Boggs' vehicle, holding the knife to
the baseball player's throat while threatening to kill him.
</TEXT>
