<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonBriefs 1stld-writethru a0435 06-12 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington Briefs, 1st ld-writethru, a0435,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead graf of 2nd item to eliminate extraneous word</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One quarter of U.S. households were the target
of a violent crime or theft last year, a figure similar to the three
previous years, according to the Justice Department.
   ``In 1988, 27 percent of households with incomes of $25,000 or
more, 29 percent of black households and 30 percent of urban
households were touched by crime,'' the report found.
   The report, based on the National Crime Survey, covered 92.9
million households and found that 22.8 million experienced a theft
or burglary or had a member who was raped, robbed or assaulted.
   The study also found that members of about 141,000 households
were raped, 872,000 were robbed and 3.7 million were assaulted, and
it said a total of 7.19 million households, or one in 13, were
targeted by crimes of ``high concern,'' including rape, robbery,
assault by a stranger or a burglar.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hurricane Hotline Starts Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Hurricane Hotline'' will resume this
year, according to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
   The hotline is a special telephone service providing regular
updates of the progress of named tropical storms and hurricanes. It
operates only when such a storm is active.
   Last year the hotline received more than 100,000 calls during
Hurricane Gilbert, and the year bfore 700,000 calls were recorded
when hurricanes Gloria and Elena threatened, officials said.
   The hotline number is 1-900-410-NOAA and calls cost 50 cents for
the first minute and 45 cents for each additional minute.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>VA Awards Contract for New Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Veterans Affairs has given US
Sprint and Science Applications International Corp. an $84 million
contract to build a data network linking VA offices and medical
facilities nationwide.
   San Diego-based SAIC is the prime contractor and will provide
computer software and management systems for the ``integrated data
communications utility,'' while US Sprint will provide network,
office and transmission equipment, according to an announcement.
   The new system will serve 377 geographic locations, including the
172 VA medical centers, when it is fully installed in about two
years. It will replace the VA's data transmission systems and its
benefits delivery system, which serve about 80 million veterans,
dependents and survivors of deceased veterans.
