<FIRST>r a PM-Iowa-Powder     06-12 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa-Powder,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Changes Powder Storage Practices After Iowa Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy will stop storing gunpowder for its
Iowa-class battleships aboard unventilated barges following the
fatal explosion on the USS Iowa, according to a published report.
   The change comes despite the Navy's belief that gunpowder was not
at fault for the fatal blast.
   Construction of additional magazines at the Yorktown Naval
Weapons Station will eliminate the need to store munitions aboard
barges on the York River, Navy officials told The Virginian-Pilot
and The Ledger-Star of Norfolk.
   When the battleship Wisconsin heads for maintenance and repairs
this summer, its powder charges _ 110-pound bags _ will not be
stored aboard uncooled, unventilated barges as the Iowa's were, the
newspaper reported in Sunday editions.
   When the Iowa went in for similar overhaul last summer, its
powder was stored aboard uncooled barges at the Yorktown station
during the hottest part of the season.
   In April, 47 sailors aboard the Iowa were killed when powder
exploded in the No. 2 gun turret during open seas gunnery practice.
Before the explosion, the No. 1 turret had a misfire when the five
bags of powder used to propel the gun's projectile wouldn't ignite.
   Navy officials have said they do not believe the storage of the
powder was to blame and are investigating the possibility of
sabotage. Nevertheless, the charges aboard the Iowa have been
removed and replaced with powder that was stored in
temperature-controlled underground bunkers.
   Navy officials did not monitor either the temperatures or
humidity aboard the barges, though the newspaper reported that the
station's safety officer had complained the munitions needed to be
moved.
   ``Permitting these charges to be stored in the barge for this
period of time indicates the lack of importance that is placed on
compliance with the safety requirements'' set forth in the Navy's
manual on munition storage, a memo from the unidentified safety
officer said in September 1988.
   Those powder charges were later returned to the Iowa when it came
back from its scheduled shipyard visit.
   Munitions experts and the Navy manual say that prolonged exposure
to high temperatures and humidity can lead to deterioration of the
powder charges, making them either inert or extremely volatile.
   The internal report estimates the temperature inside the
aluminum-sided barges were 25 degrees higher than the outside air
temperature. Using that estimate, the newspaper calculated from
National Weather Service readings for the area that the temperature
inside the barges could have exceeded 110 degrees on 66 days during
the time the powder was in storage.
   Thomas Black, administrative officer at the Yorktown station,
said the Wisconsin's powder would not be stored at the station, the
largest of the Navy's six weapon stations.
   Black said additional magazines are being built at the weapons
station to accommodate more munitions. According to the Pentagon,
Yorktown is the only one of the Navy's munitions stations that uses
barges for temporary powder storage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
