<FIRST>r a PM-HellsAngels     06-12 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hells Angels,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Bikers Attend Funeral For Hells Angels Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hells Angels leader Michael ``Irish''
O'Farrell received the club's funeral honors as hundreds of bikers
wearing jackets emblazoned with the winged skull escorted his body
to a cemetery.
   O'Farrell, believed by law enforcement to be second in the club's
hierarchy only to the its spriritual leader, Ralph ``Sonny'' Barger
Jr., died during a bloody bar brawl on Tuesday.
   ``You couldn't ask for a more dedicated or more faithful guy to
his friends and to the Hells Angels,'' a club member known only as
Cisco said at the funeral service.
   ``I ain't going to say goodbye. Goodbyes are for the movies. So
long, buddy,'' he said in a choked voice.
   Both O'Farrell, who celebrated his 40th birthday four days before
his death, and Barger faced sentencing on federal explosives
convictions. O'Farrell was stabbed once each in the neck and chest
and five times in the back as well as being shot four times from
behind, the Alameda County coroner's office said.
   About 1,000 people filed into a funeral home in East Oakland to
pay final respects Saturday to O'Farrell, who acted as president of
the club's Oakland chapter in the early 1980s while Barger recovered
from a throat operation for cancer.
   After visiting the closed casket, decorated with flowers and
pictures of him on his motorcycle, mourners walked into an adjoining
room to offer condolences to Barger. Wreaths from motorcycle clubs
throughout the West adorned the chapel.
   Mourners, including O'Farrell's wife, Teddy, his son, and about
250 bikers, accompanied his body to Evergreen Cemetery. There,
bikers buried O'Farrell after placing ribbons and banners from the
flowers on the casket.
   Investigators don't have a motive for O'Farrell's killing and
don't believe he was killed by a rival gang.
   But Alameda County Sheriff's Lt. Dean Hess said last week drugs
were involved. Powdered methamphetamine, better known as speed, was
found on the San Leandro bar's patio, where the killing occurred.
   Barger and O'Farrell, both of Oakland, were convicted in October
for what prosecutors said was a revenge attack for the slaying of a
Hells Angel who was shot outside a bar in Jefferson County, Ky., in
August 1986. A Louisville Outlaw motorcycle club member had pleaded
guilty to reckless homicide in Webb's death.
   California Attorney General John Van de Kamp's 1985 report on
organized crime described motorcycle gangs like the Hells Angels as
controlling most of the manufacture and distribution of
methamphetamine through a large-scale clandestine operation of
laboratories and distribution networks.
   Law enforcement experts say the Angels switched from biking,
carousing and bar-busting to organized crime in the mid-1960s.
   Van de Kamp said the Hells Angels, known for riding
Harley-Davidson motorcycles, have 60 chapters worldwide, 13 in
California. The group was founded in the Southern California steel
town of Fontana about 1950.
</TEXT>
