<DOCNO> AP890612-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 0515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-12 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises To Highest Level in Tokyo Since August 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar today rose nearly five yen to a 22-month
high against the Japanese currency, sending prices down on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange, dealers said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 241.97 points, or 0.72
percent, finishing at 33,398.01. The index had lost 78.31 points on
Friday.
   The dollar closed at 148.40 yen, up 4.90 yen from Friday's
143.50-yen close. Today's close was the highest since the dollar
finished at 148.55 yen on Aug. 18, 1987.
   After opening at 147.60 yen, the currency fluctuated between
147.35 yen and 148.45 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's sharpest jump in almost two years
resulted mainly from uncertainties over developments in China and a
sharper-than-expected rise in the U.S. wholesale price index
announced on Friday in Washington.
   The U.S. Labor Department reported that the nation's wholesale
prices surged 0.9 percent in May. The rise had been expected to be
nearer the moderate climbs of 0.4 percent in both March and April.
   ``The Chinese situation and the wholesale price index did have an
impact on the trading, prompting dollar-buying, but most investors
were jumping on the bandwagon,'' said Sanwa Bank's Hirokazu Yoshida.
   Minori Takeuchi, a dealer with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said
market sentiment here was totally inclined toward dollar-buying.
   ``Japanese investors would have bought even if the wholesale
index had been lower. At present, just about anything seems to have
the potential to be a dollar-buying incentive for Japanese
investors,'' she said.
   Traders said the Bank of Japan intermittently sold dollars in
efforts to check the U.S. currency's rise, but the amount was
unknown. The central bank does not comment on its foreign exchange
operations.
   Meanwhile, Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama said Japan will take
measures in cooperation with other Group of Seven major monetary
nations to cope with the ``speculative'' foreign exchange markets,
Kyodo News Service reported today.
   Kyodo also quoted an unidentified Bank of Japan source as saying
the current dollar-buying was highly speculative.
   On the stock market, dealers blamed the decline in the market's
main barometer on the yen's sharp drop.
   Nomura Securities analyst Masahiro Umemori said the index fell in
early trading, as a majority of investors moved to the sidelines,
and stayed low throughout the day.
   ``The yen's decline, more than four yen just over the weekend,
did have a great impact on market players,'' he said. ``It was only
natural that most investors totally lost motivation to buy stocks
today.''
   ``The problem is that the market is taking the dollar's rise for
granted,'' Umemori said. ``Anything can be a dollar-buying
incentive, and whenever the dollar-yen rate becomes unstable, it
discourages stock investors.''
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 350 million shares,
the smallest this year, dealers said.
   Market players sold varieties of issues including steel,
construction and shipbuilding.
</TEXT>
