<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-12 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fatima, one name, is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beware of bridges and cemeteries
in Oakland County: Snoopy pyschics say the environs make it easier
to eavesdrop on your psyches.
   The Glen Eden Cemetery in Novi, in southeastern Michigan, is a
center rich in psychic power, said psychic-astrologer Robert
Thibodeau. Another is the Roseland Park Cemetery in Berkley.
   ``What you have in cemeteries is a combination of nature forces
and historical events that took place,'' said Thibodeau, a bookshop
owner.
   Other spots are Lake Cranbrook in Bloomfield Hills and at a
bridge at Bloomer State Park in Rochester.
   ``I have found that in the middle of that bridge there is an
incredible amount of force and energy,'' said Sue Fine, who sells
psychic crystals.
   It isn't clear why the vibes are so strong in Oakland County.
   ``I think it's something to do with the water,'' said Fatima, a
psychic from Harper Woods.
   ``It's easier to read people'' in Bloomfield Hills, she said.
``The readings just flow from them. For some reason, they want to be
read.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRYTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of engineering students has
envisioned the automotive future, and it looks a giant cheese wedge
on three wheels that seats one and gets 1,278 miles per gallon of
gasoline.
   ``Big Richard,'' designed by 11 engineering students at
California State University, Northridge, was the winner of Sunday's
sixth annual West Coast Supermileage Competition.
   The dark red three-wheeler driven by student Hiep Nguyen led a
field of 12 vehicles from eight California colleges and universities
in four laps around a 1}-mile test track.
   ``The SLO,'' a whale-shaped vehicle entered by eight students
from California Polytechnic State University in San Luis Obispo,
finished second with 951 mpg.
   A four-student team from California State University, Sacramento,
which fielded the champion designs in the past two years, came in
third with 888 mpg by ``The Stinger.''
   Gas mileage, not speed, determined the winner, said Ben Winkler
of the California State Automobile Association, which sponsored the
event with the Society of Automotive Engineers.
   A CSU Sacramento team set the U.S. record in 1987 with 1,971 mpg.
</TEXT>
