<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-12 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged in hectic trading in Europe today
on a wave of dollar-buying that started Friday.
   Gold prices fell on the dollar's climb and on continued
profit-taking in bullion.
   ``It looks like the dollar has found a solid base,'' said Ernst
Pullmann, chief trader at Deutsche Girozentrale-Deutsche Kommunale
Bank in Frankfurt.
   ``At the moment there are hardly any dollar sellers,'' he said.
   Some traders attributed the dollar's strength to Friday's news of
a surprisingly large 0.9 percent increase in U.S. producer prices in
May. That fueled expectations that U.S. interest rates would remain
high.
   Other traders said the dollar continued to be supported by
investors in the Far East who were converting assets into
dollar-denominated investments because of the turmoil in China.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar soared nearly 5 yen to a 22-month high against the
Japanese currency. The dollar closed at 148.40 yen, up 4.90 yen from
Friday.
   Later, in London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 149.05 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday:
   _2.0305 West German marks, up from 2.0025
   _1.7645 Swiss francs, up from 1.7402
   _6.8815 French francs, up from 6.7810
   _2.2918 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2510
   _1,469 Italian lire, up from 1,450.50
   _1.2025 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1999
   In London, the dollar jumped against the British pound. It cost
$1.5305 dollars to buy one pound, compared with $1.5545 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $357.40 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $363.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $358.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $358.50 compared with $368.05 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.47 to close at a bid $359.03.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.15 a troy ounce,
down from Friday's $5.27.
</TEXT>
