<FIRST>r i PM-China-ForeignPress 1stLd-Writethru   06-12 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Foreign Press, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0458,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Journalist Expelled By China Not Allowed Contact with Consulate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 4th, `In Beijing...' to UPDATE with BBC crew
detained; Picks up 5th graf, `They are...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British journalist expelled from China said
today that the officials who seized him while he was covering a
demonstration in Shanghai took his film and refused to let him
contact the British Consulate.
   Peter Newport of Independent Television News was the first
journalist expelled from China since the student-led campaign for
greater freedom began in mid-April. He was ordered out on Saturday
and flew to Hong Kong.
   After he was expelled, Shanghai authorities sent a letter to
diplomatic missions telling them to instruct journalists that they
cannot cover news in the city without Foreign Ministry permission.
   In Beijing, a British Broadcasting Co. television reporter today
said he and his crew were detained Sunday while filming. Brian
Barron said the identity cards and passports of members of the crew
were confiscated and they were told they should not leave China
without official authorization.
   Foreign reporters in Beijing must have local government approval
to report from all areas under martial law, meaning all of central
Beijing.
   They are also banned from interviewing people on activities that
violate martial law decrees, taking pictures of troops and receiving
materials prohibited under martial law.
   In an telephone interview, Newport said he was seized while
videotaping a sit-in by about 50 students in front of Shanghai's
public security building on Saturday. He was told he could not
report on a tourist visa.
   Newport told the security officials who seized him that he would
not answer questions until allowed contact with the consulate but,
``I was never allowed to contact the British Consulate.''
   He said he was filming the sit-in when officers ``just grabbed me
by the arms and pulled me past the police lines and the gateway of
the public security building. ... I got away from them but they came
after me and dragged me back.''
   The officers took his passport and asked that he erase his film.
When he did not comply, a technician was summoned. The officers
watched the tape erased, and they kept it.
   Newport said he was then taken to another building where a half
dozen officers questioned him for 75 minutes.
   He said officers videotaped and wrote down the conversation and
had Newport sing the written record of the conversation.
   ``They basically said I was going to be treated leniently because
I had admitted what I had done and I apologized but that I was to be
expelled from China,'' he said.
   Newport said reporting in China has become dangerous for all
involved, pointing to the case of ABC News.
   The U.S. network said Sunday that Chinese authorities intercepted
raw footage of an ABC interview with a man in Beijing, broadcast the
tape on national television and then used it to arrest him for
``rumor-mongering.''
   Chinese television on Saturday broadcast footage of the man
telling ABC that 20,000 people were killed in the June 3-4 assault
that crushed the pro-democracy uprising in Beijing. His arrest was
announced on national television on Sunday.
   The government has said nearly 300 people were killed, most of
them soldiers attacked by ``ruffians.'' Chinese witnesses and
Western intelligence sources have said as many as 3,000 were killed,
most of them civilians, when troops fired on unarmed protesters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
