<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 0728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RuralTales     06-12 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rural Tales,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Writers Focus On Stories Of Midwestern History And Culture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLAIR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The young writers came from the city, the
stories from the country, and the modest magazine bridged the gap
between the two cultures.
   There were stories about butchering hogs, one-room schoolhouses,
barn-raising, canning with grandma, and an old man's memories.
   Now, after a three-year break, ``Tales from the General Store''
is back in publication, and its founder hopes both its readers and
its writers benefit.
   ``For students, I see it as a way to learn to write in a hands-on
way,'' said editor Ray Elliott, an Urbana high school teacher. ``It
also provides a valuable service by preserving the history and
culture of the rural Midwest.''
   ``Tales'' is printed in the format of a small tabloid newspaper.
   It is distributed as an insert to the Casey Reporter, the
Marshall Independent, the Robinson Daily News, the Daily Record in
Lawrenceville, the Martinsville Planet, the Oakland-Hindsboro
Prairie Sun and the Robinson Constitution.
   Elliott also hopes to mail it to the 1,000 subscribers in 35
states who took Tales when it was published between 1981 and 1986.
Four issues a year will cost $5. Individual and corporate
contributions will be another source of income for the magazine, he
said.
   Elliott began Tales in 1981 while teaching at Oak Lawn Community
High School in suburban Chicago, when he took seven students to stay
at his father's property near Bellair, about 200 miles south of
Chicago.
   ``We just camped near the woods _ no water or electricity,'' he
recalled. ``We had to take two of them back to the train in
Effingham the second day. It was just too primitive.''
   The others stayed on, interviewing and photographing people in
the area for the first edition of Tales.
   ``They'd use a tape-recorder and use a lot of people's exact
words,'' said Elliott. ``Then, they'd weave in a description of the
scene - the sights, the sounds and the smells.''
   Elliott's non-profit corporation also bought the old Bellair
general store. They ate there, worked there and brought in local
people to demonstrate things like chair caning and relate memories
of the area.
   ``A lot of old people die without telling all the stories from
their lives and they are lost forever,'' said Laurie Goering, who
first wrote for Tales in 1983. ``This is a nice way to preserve
them.''
   Goering, who now writes for the Chicago Tribune, once did a story
about a man who made alcohol from old candy that had been discarded
by stores. She says that Elliott is good at working with young
people because ``he teaches them that writing is fun.''
   But eventually, donations to Tales dried up. Elliott also left
his teaching job, so he lost his source of student writers.
   Tales ended in 1986 after its 10th issue.
   Now, with new students and new donations, Elliott hopes Tales
will broaden its coverage.
   ``We'll focus on the Midwest _ anything of historical
significance or cultural interest,'' he said.
   The new issue features memories of ``The Tin Lizzie,'' the first
horseless carriage, in poem form; the struggles of
Champaign-Urbana's first newspaper publishers, who battled unhappy
advertisers, unhappy readers and each other; the efforts of the
small town of Oakland to survive and thrive; and an essay by a
recent high school graduate on the death of her little sister.
   ``The sky was dark the day she was buried,'' Cynthia Cox wrote.
``I had to sit in the front of the limousine with the driver because
I was the one who was able to climb in by myself. My face was as
dark as the day and appeared blank.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0046 </DOCNO>
