<FIRST>r a PM-BalloonCrash     06-12 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Balloon Crash,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed When Hot Air Balloon Hits TV Tower Wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA GRIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GARNER, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hot-air balloon flying in tricky winds that
led another balloon owner to cancel two flights ran into a
television tower guy wire and fell ``like a sack of bricks,''
killing all three people aboard.
   The balloon fell 1,100 to 1,500 feet to the ground at 7:15 a.m.
Sunday, officials said.
   ``We didn't say anything to each other when we saw the balloon
flying so low,'' said Orlando Haley, 25, of Smithfield, who
witnessed the crash along with his brother, Dennis. ``We both knew
it was going to hit the tower.''
   The balloon ``dropped like a sack of bricks to the ground,'' said
Dennis Haley, 27. The brothers were the first to reach the crash
site.
   The victims, who were dead at the scene, were identified as the
pilot, Dan D. Johnson, 45, of Raleigh; Joseph James Tanahey, 32, of
Cary; and his wife, Margaret Angel Tanahey, whose age was not
available.
   Deputy D.C. Davenport said witnesses told him that when the
balloon hit the wires, ``it just tore the whole top out of that
balloon and it dropped straight down. It came down quick.''
   Ronald E. Brady, the co-owner of Aerial Ascensions, another
charter balloon company in Raleigh, said bad wind led his company to
cancel two flights Sunday morning.
   ``You develop a sixth sense, and I guess that's what we relied on
today,'' said Brady. ``It told us that something wasn't right and we
couldn't put our finger on it, so we didn't fly.''
   The National Weather Service at Raleigh-Durham International
Airport in Morrisville recorded surface winds of 8 mph at the time
of the accident.
   Brady said that's fine for launching a balloon, but he was
concerned about a low-level wind shear _ an abrupt change in wind
speed or direction _ detected in the 300- to 400-foot range.
``Because of that, we decided not to fly,'' he said.
   The tower whose wire was hit is owned by Durham Life Broadcasting
Co. for WPTF-TV and is one of three in the field where the crash
occurred. Guy wires on television towers can extend a quarter-mile
from the tower, officials said.
   Federal Aviation Administration officials are investigating the
crash, officials said.
</TEXT>
