<FIRST>r a PM-Hearns-Shooting 1stLd-Writethru a0491 06-12 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hearns-Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0491,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brother of Boxer Thomas Hearns Arrested in Weekend Shooting of Girlfriend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to recast. A longer version moved on sports
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGELA AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The younger brother of boxer Thomas
Hearns has been arrested in the weekend shooting death of his
girlfriend at a home the boxer owns, the brother's attorney
confirmed.
   Henry Hearns, 22, was held on a preliminary charge of murder and
was scheduled to be arraigned this afternoon, his attorney, Neil
Fink, said late Sunday. The arraignment comes just hours before
Thomas Hearns' scheduled title fight with Sugar Ray Leonard in Las
Vegas.
   Tony Barile of Shelby Township identified the victim as his
sister, Nancy, 20, and said she was Henry Hearns' girlfriend, The
Detroit News reported in today's editions.
   Police and Oakland County Prosecutor Richard Thompson refused
Sunday to identify the victim or confirm that Henry Hearns was a
suspect. Under Michigan law, a suspect's name is not released until
a formal warrant is signed by a judge, Thompson said.
   The suspect was arrested early Sunday, about 2{ hours after
witnesses reported the shooting, said officer Gary Conat, a
department spokesman.
   The victim's body was found in a bedroom of a home owned by
Thomas Hearns. She had been shot once in the head, and a handgun was
recovered at the scene, police Lt. Lloyd Collins said.
   Conat said the shooting stemmed from a ``domestic situation,''
but refused to elaborate. Police did not immediately know to whom
the handgun was registered, he said.
   Thomas Hearns remained in Las Vegas, where he was to meet Leonard
in a scheduled 12-round fight for Leonard's World Boxing Council
super middleweight title at Caesars Palace. Leonard is heavily
favored to win.
   Hearns is so consumed with avenging a 1981 loss to Leonard he has
little time to worry about the shooting, promoter Bob Arum said
Sunday from Las Vegas.
   Arum said the home where the shooting occurred was one of four
owned by Hearns and not the fighter's actual residence.
   Jackie Kallen, Hearns' publicist, said the fighter was in
seclusion, adding that was normal for the day before a fight.
Another publicist, John Totaro, said it was doubtful Hearns would
comment on the shooting before the fight.
  
