<FIRST>u i PM-Indochina-Environment 1stLd-Writethru   06-12 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indochina-Environment, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0417,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia Face Decimated Forests, Wildlife</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 10th graf, `Japanese loggers...' to CORRECT grammar. Pickup
11th pvs, `Indochinese officials...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VINH PHU, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the scarred, denuded hills northwest
of Hanoi, Vietnam is waging another war, one scientists say may
prove as crucial to its survival as those against the French and
Americans.
   Over large tracts of Vinh Phu, experimental efforts are under way
to regenerate forests that once covered most of the hilly province
and to persuade farmers to mix cash crops with trees that bind and
fertilize the soil.
   The lessons learned may help attain a national objective:
increase tree cover in the next few decades from the current 20
percent to 50 percent. Vo Quy, the country's leading
conservationist, says while the plan may be over-ambitious, not
succeeding could spell disaster.
   According to Quy, a biologist who helped develop Vietnam strategy
for national conservation, forces threatening the underpinnings of
Vietnam are at work.
   About 40 percent of the country is being raked by erosion, with
water rushing off denuded hills and carrying away tons of vital
topsoil. Agricultural land is already scarce, and Vietnam's
population, now 60 million, is growing at 2.4 percent a year.
   ``This task of restoring our environment is the biggest and most
important challenge facing Vietnam today,'' Quy said upon accepting
an award last year from the Switzerland-based World Wildlife Fund.
   Forced for decades to worry about falling bombs and empty rice
bowls, the Vietnamese and their neighbors in Cambodia and Laos
largely ignored the mounting ecological mayhem around them.
   Vast forests became firewood, and the land was turned into rice
paddies; wildlife was slaughtered by foraging armies and hungry
civilians. In Vietnam, the United States unleashed a new form of
warfare: chemical defoliation to deny communist guerrillas vital
forest sanctuaries.
   The wars have ended in all but Cambodia, but peace and a recent
opening to the outside world pose new dangers. Eager for rapid
economic growth but unable to pay for it, the three countries find
that among their most saleable commodities are the remaining forests.
   Japanese loggers _ widely criticized for despoiling Southeast
Asia's tropical forests _ have already gained a foothold in
Cambodia. Thailand, which banned domestic logging this year after
ravaging its own forests, is hungry for its neighbors' timber.
   Indochinese officials say controls will be placed to prevent
exploitation by outsiders, but their statements sound optimistic in
light of experiences elsewhere in the Third World.
   Western environmentalists contend that Japanese and Thai loggers
will try to buy off anyone who tries to stop them from cutting down
the forests.
   ``We are destroying our environmental balance,'' said Chea Kong
of Cambodia's Agricultural Ministry, estimating forest cover has
shrunk from 73 to 50 percent in his country over the past decade.
   Eradication of ``flooded forests'' adjacent Cambodia's Tonle Sap
lake has wiped out many fish breeding grounds and, in part, accounts
for the dramatic drop in catch in recent years.
   In an unprecedented speech last month, Prime Minister Kaysone
Phomvihane of Laos said deforestation had reached a ``dangerous
level'' and called for a ban on logging for export. He blamed
drought and floods on the forest felling, which he described as a
``crime against the next generation.''
   In all three countries, the large herds of wild animals
remembered by older residents have vanished. Tiger, elephant, gaur
and gibbon are among the endangered species; the Sumatran rhinoceros
and tapir are extinct.
   Vietnam probably faces the greatest problems. Since World War II,
when about half the country was under tree cover, the forests have
dwindled steadily. According to the Vietnamese, about 4.9 million
acres of forest were destroyed by herbicides and other U.S. military
actions.
   But since the war ended in 1975, even more woodland has been
destroyed by human encroachment.
   Some of Vietnam's countermeasures appear impressive, given the
shattered economy and little foreign aid for conservation.
   Quy said more than half a billion trees are being planted each
year with every student in the country obliged to take part. About
90 parks and conservation areas have been established, and a search
has begun to capture and breed the kouprey, an endangered species of
wild cattle that has become a symbol to conservationists in
Southeast Asia.
   But across Indochina, the ax and the gun are hard to stop.
Tribespeople in Laos strip entire mountainsides through their
migratory slash-and-burn farming, a tactic that wreaks environmental
havoc worldwide.
   ``It was easier to mobilize and sacrifice during the war,'' said
To Thinh, a district chief in Vinh Phu. ``It is harder to mobilize
people to save the environment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 0954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Sudan     06-12 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudanese Government, Rebels Agree on Peace Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sudanese government and a rebel
group that has been fighting for autonomy for six years agreed
conditionally today on a constitutional conference in September to
end their civil war.
   In a joint statement, the sides set Sept. 18 for the start of the
conference but said it would have to be preceded by full
implementation of a pending peace agreement.
   That agreement was reached in November between the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army and the Democratic Unionist Party, a major
player in Sudan's coalition government.
   The pact caused a schism in the governing coalition and Prime
Minister Sadek Mahdi was forced to reshuffle his government earlier
this year under pressure from the army and professional groups.
   Although Mahdi has signaled his acceptance of the November peace
plan, Sudan's Parliament still has not formally endorsed it.
   The government and the rebel army said they would meet again in
Ethiopia's capital on July 4 to discuss ways to implement the
November accord and pave the way for the September conference.
   The joint statement was issued at the end of a two-day,
closed-door meeting between the sides, the first in the 6-year-old
war.
   No site was given for the constitutional conference, but the
statement said all Sudanese political parties would be invited to
participate.
   It appeared doubtful, however, that the militant National Islamic
Party would agree to take part in such a conference because it is
firmly opposed to a peace agreement with the Sudan People's
Liberation Army.
   The Islamic Party, also a dominant partner in the former
government, left Mahdi's coalition after he indicated acceptance of
November's tentative peace accord.
   One of the sticking points to formal endorsement of the peace
proposal was a provision in the agreement calling for abrogation of
Sudan's defense pacts with Egypt and Libya. But on Sunday, the
government in Khartoum unexpectedly announced it had canceled those
pacts.
   In the joint statement, the sides ``agreed that the steps taken
by the governments of Sudan and Egypt to abrogate the joint defense
pact by mutual consent are positive and what remains is its
ratification by the Constituent Assembly.''
   But government and rebel delegations expressed differing views on
the Sudanese-Libyan defense protocol, with the insurgents
questioning whether Sudan could end it unilaterally without Libya's
consent.
   Lam Akol, the Sudan People's Liberation Army's director of
external affairs, noted that Libya has made no mention of the pact's
abrogation and said ``it is not clear if one side alone can cancel
it.''
   The organization considers the mutual defense agreements an
infringement on Sudanese sovereignity. Under a 1976 joint defense
treaty with Egypt, the countries are to aid each other in case of a
foreign attack. The agreement is one-sided in reality because of the
poor condition of the Sudanese army.
   Libya and Sudan signed a military cooperation pact in 1985, but
that too is one-sided, with Sudan receiving military aid and
equipment but contributing very little in return.
   Other points of the November peace initiative which remain to be
worked out are cancelation of Islamic law, which are opposed by the
rebels; lifting of a state of emergency; and the declaration of a
permanent truce.
   The guerrilla organization launched its rebellion in early 1983,
demanding greater autonomy and economic reforms in the three
southern provinces of Bahr Ghazal, Upper Nile and Equatoria,
populated mainly by Christians and animists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1010EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     06-12 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt Offers to Mediate Between PLO and Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HERZLIYA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens today
rejected Egypt's offer to serve as a mediator with the PLO to help
end the 18-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied
territories.
   The offer came in a message to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir from
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. It was delivered in a private
meeting by the visiting Egyptian minister of state for foreign
affairs, Butros Ghali.
   Ghali is the only leading Egyptian official to visit Israel since
the start of the Palestinian uprising.
   ``I'm ready to be a good and active postman,'' Ghali told about
30 prominent Palestinians at a breakfast meeting in Herzliya.
   After 90 minutes of talks with Ghali in Jerusalem, Arens
responded that there was no need for a middleman and no desire for
talks with the PLO. Israel refuses to negotiate with the PLO,
considering it a terrorist organization.
   ``There is no need for mediation,'' Arens said. ``I think the
Egyptians understand that we are convinced...that the peace process
needs to be advanced through direct negotiations and not through
mediation.''
   A senior Israeli official who requested anonymity said Shamir
told Mubarak's envoy he would welcome Egyptian efforts to persuade
Palestinians to accept Israel's plan for holding elections in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip. The PLO has rejected Shamir's plan, under
which Palestinians would elect non-PLO representatives to negotiate
limited autonomy for the occupied territories.
   ``Any positive influence Egypt could exert on the Palestinians
here would be beneficial,'' the official quoted Shamir as saying.
But he added the PLO was not a partner and, ``We don't need
mediation with them.''
   Asked about differences between the Egyptian and Israeli stance
toward the Palestine Liberation Organization, Arens said that Israel
sees the PLO as ``the major obstacle to progress for peace in the
area.''
   ``It is our position that anything which enhances the image of
the PLO is not a positive development in the peace process,'' Arens
said.
   Egypt is the only Arab country that maintains diplomatic ties
with Israel.
   Ghali also suggested Egypt's Embassy in Tel Aviv play a mediating
role between Palestinians and the PLO if such a move was requested
by Arabs in the occupied land, said Radwan Abu Ayash, head of the
Arab Journalists Association.
   Several prominent Palestinians did not attend the meeting. Some
said they received threats from radical PLO faction, while others
boycotted the session because it was held in Israel instead of in
Arab east Jerusalem.
   Also today, the Israeli daily Haaretz reported the army will
extend the maximum period under which Arabs can be jailed without
trial from six months to a year. Currently, 1,508 Palestinians are
being held without trial in Israeli detention centers and 5,000
Arabs have been held since the uprising began.
   The so-called administrative detention has been strongly
criticized by the United States as a violation of the right to due
process before the law.
</TEXT>
