<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Extradition     06-12 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Extradition,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Won't Block Extradition of Californian to Hong Kong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to block the
extradition to Hong Kong of a California man accused of falsifying
accounts while chairman of a bank in the British crown colony.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that extraditing
the former bank official will violate his rights and could subject
him to additional prosecution when Hong Kong is returned to Chinese
control in 1997.
   Lawyers for Oen Yin Choy said the current unrest in China and the
prospect of civil war there underscore the urgency of his plight.
   Oen, 70, is an Indonesian citizen now living in an undisclosed
location south of San Francisco. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals last October turned down his bid to avoid extradition.
   The appeals court rejected arguments that forcing Oen to return
to Hong Kong would violate a treaty between the United States and
Britain.
   The treaty bars anyone who is extradited from being turned over
to a third nation. It also prohibits the extradited individual from
being charged with any offense other than those for which he or she
has been extradited.
   Under a 1985 agreement between Great Britain and China, control
of Hong Kong will revert to China on July 1, 1997, when a 99-year
British lease expires.
   The 9th Circuit court said, ``Even if Oen becomes subject to
Chinese authority ... upon ... termination of the British lease of
Hong Kong, he will not have been extradited to China.''
   Oen also said the Chinese, in violation of the U.S.-British
treaty, could charge him with additional offenses based on his
alleged conduct as former chairman of the Union Bank of Hong Kong.
   But the appeals court said the treaty ``does not purport to
include commitments by successor governments or third states.''
   U.S. prosecutors contend that Oen embezzled $26.7 million that
was deposited in the Union Bank from 1975 to 1984. The prosecutors
said the money was supposed to be placed in accounts outside of Hong
Kong to produce tax benefits for the investors.
   Instead, the prosecutors charged, the money was used for other
bank purposes. Oen approved fictitious loans in 1984 to raise money
to repay some of the investors, according to the prosecutors.
   Oen, noting that Hong Kong officials have accused him of false
accounting, denied he embezzled the money.
   He also said his due-process rights were violated by the
extradition proceeding conducted by U.S. officials.
   Oen said translations from Chinese to English of witness
statements in his case are unreliable. He also said he was
unlawfully denied the right to cross-examine the government's
witnesses.
   The case is Oen vs. Robinson, 88-1481.
</TEXT>
