<HEAD>Alligators Stolen From Zoo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two alligators reported missing from the
local zoo were apparently stolen, and the thieves had better keep
watch on their snapping jaws, authorities said today.
   ``They just don't get up in pairs and stroll out,'' said police
officer Judd Lezotte.
   The 4-foot American alligators, who live in a new outdoor pen,
were last seen at about midnight Saturday by a watchman. They were
discovered missing about eight hours later.
   ``They were in there all week and seemed very happy there,'' said
Gregg Cancho, acting director of Beardsley Zoological Gardens. The
alligators, which are native to the Southeast, would have had to
climb a 4{-foot-high wall to get out, an unlikely feat, Dancho said.
   ``One other possibility would have been for them to go out the
keeper's entrance, but they'd have to hop a 3-foot wall, walk around
and jump another 3-foot wall,'' Dancho said.
   He said the animals are dangerous and capable of biting off
fingers. The pair was near death three years ago when a local
resident, who had apparently brought them up from the South, donated
them to the zoo.
