<HEAD>Two Chinese Diplomats Seek Political Asylum in United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th pvs, `I was...' to UPDATE with Chinese
official in Australia asking to stay. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `In San...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration authorities must decide whether
to grant political asylum to Chinese diplomats who said they were
defecting during an emotional vigil honoring pro-democracy students
slain in Beijing, the FBI said.
   The Consulate of the People's Republic of China would not confirm
the two men had defected, but FBI agents said the pair requested
asylum and were under federal protection Sunday.
   Agents referred the matter to the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, which decides asylum requests.
   A spokesman for David Ilchert, regional INS director, said Sunday
that the two had yet to file an asylum request, but he would provide
no other information.
   White House spokesman Bob Hall said in a telephone interview from
Washington that the Bush administration had no official statement
yet on the defections.
   At a Sunday rally organized by Chinese exchange students in
Oakland's Chinatown, some of the 300 demonstrators said they were
touched by the diplomats' actions.
   ``I was really moved when they said they are on our side,'' said
Yu Maochun, an exchange student from the University of California at
Berkeley. ``I am a Chinese national and I know how brave their
action is.''
   Elsewhere, Australia's Department of Foreign Affairs announced
today that a Chinese diplomat has requested permission to stay in
Australia and his application was being considered by the government.
   A spokesman for the department, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, refused to disclose whether the official was based in the
Chinese Embassy in Canberra or one of China's consulates in
Melbourne or Sydney. It was not clear whether the officials was
seeking political asylum or refugee status.
   The Special Broadcasting Service Television News said the
official was one of China's 10 vice-consuls in the Sydney consulate.
   In San Francisco's Chinatown, posters began appearing in shop
windows Sunday printed with the words, ``The Unkillable Dream,'' and
reading in Chinese, ``Spread the torch of the fire of the student
movement all over,'' said David Chien, of the San Francisco-based
Chinese Alliance for Democracy.
   The posters depicting the goddess of democracy statue that stood
in Tiananmen Square before the crackdown were distributed by
students at Berkeley, Chien said.
   ``In my 43 years of life I've never seen Chinese so united and
being so vocal. We are being encouraged by the students who already
went to the front lines and sacrificed their lives,'' said Chien,
whose group is one of a coalition of San Francisco area Chinese
associations who have joined to assist the democracy movement in
China.
   Hundreds of protesters wept Saturday night as the diplomats made
a surprise public plea for political asylum at a candlelight vigil
outside City Hall.
   They told the stunned rally of 5,000 that they decided to defect
after Beijing leaders launched a propaganda campaign claiming no
citizens had died in the clash.
   The Chinese government has said nearly 300 people were killed
last week in Tianamen Square but that most were soldiers attacked by
``ruffians.'' Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources
have said as many as 3,000 may have died when troops fired on crowds
of citizens.
   ``We are supposed to tell you that no one was injured or killed.
Why? Because we are diplomats. But we won't fake it here. Before we
are diplomats, we are Chinese and we are human beings,'' said one of
the diplomats.
   Lee Man-kar, an editor at San Francisco's Chinese Times, on
Sunday identified the two from their business cards as Zhou Li-ming,
26, vice consul for cultural affairs, and Zhang Li-man, 25, acting
consul for overseas affairs. He said both had been in the United
States for 2{ years and were unmarried.
   Humphrey Wou, a member of the Chinese Christian Mission, one of
the sponsors of Saturday's rally, said he saw several San Francisco
police officers crying after the men spoke.
   He said the diplomats told him they had walked to the rally after
finishing dinner at the consulate, about a half-mile away.
   Along the way, they stopped at a public telephone and called the
FBI, and agents escorted them from the rally afterward.
</TEXT>
