<HEAD>Chicago Student, Baby Return Safely From China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The husband of a woman who was detained with her
baby in China for five days called her safe return to the United
States ``the end of a nightmare.''
   Yu Cheng, 30, savored her first full day back with her husband,
Sanyuan Li, Sunday and appeared at a rally of about 200 people at
Chicago's Chinatown.
   Ms. Cheng was detained for five days last week after arriving in
Beijing to join pro-democracy demonstrators. She was delivering
money raised by Chinese students in the United States to the student
leaders in China.
   She said she was well treated, but very concerned for her safety
and that of her 18-month-old son, Payton Li, who is a U.S. citizen.
Ms. Cheng and her husband are Chinese nationals.
   ``For the fight for freedom and democracy in China it's going to
be a very, very long struggle,'' said Ms. Cheng, a doctoral
candidate in education at the University of Chicago. She said
authorities questioned her about her involvement in the movement.
   Ms. Cheng, her husband and child all wore black swatches pinned
to their sleeves to symbolize mourning for the students who have
died in the 7-week uprising in China.
   ``I'm so happy,'' Sanyuan Li said of the return of his wife and
child. ``This is the end of a nightmare.''
   Also Sunday, 17 students from Northern Illinois University and 15
professors from Illinois State University returned safely from China.
   ``Demonstrations are still strong outside of Beijing,'' said
Thomas Heaney, director of NIU's Lindeman Center in Chicago. ``We
saw students demonstrating in every single city we were in.''
