<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     06-12 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Reportedly Attack Strategic Airport, Destroy Government Arsenal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels attacked an airport in northern
Afghanistan, killing 300 government soldiers during a raid in which
a large ammunition dump blew up, the guerrilla news service said
today.
   The Moslem guerrillas _ known as the mujahedeen, or Islamic
``holy warriors'' _ launched the attack in early June on the airport
at Mazar-i-Sharif, the insurgents' Afghan News Agency said.
   The city is the capital of northern Balkh province and a major
military base of Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government.
   During the fighting, 7,400 tons of ammunition stored in a depot
exploded, destroying weaponry, vehicles and 170 tanks, the agency
said. It said it was unclear if the arsenal was exploded by the
rebels or if it was sabotaged to keep weapons out of guerrilla hands.
   About 300 government troops were killed in the blast and
subsequent fighting, the agency reported.
   It was not possible to independently confirm the guerrilla report.
   Battlefield claims by each side are difficult to verify, and
casualty counts frequently are released several days after clashes.
   Mazar-i-Sharif, 35 miles south of the Soviet border, is the major
military supply hub for Kabul, the Afghan capital.
   Guerrilla and Western diplomatic sources say the communist
government has prepared the city as a fallback position in the event
Kabul is taken by the rebels, who are backed primarily by Pakistan
and the United States.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, leader of the fundamentalist Hezb-i-Islami
rebel group, told civilians Sunday to evacuate the southeastern city
of Kandahar, Afghanistan's second-largest, before an imminent
guerrilla attack.
   Communist government forces still hold the country's major cities
following the withdrawal earlier this year of Soviet troops helping
the Marxist government. But the guerrilla fighters have control of
most of the countryside.
   A commander in Hekmatyar's group issued a similar warning to
Kabul citizens in May, but the offensive has yet to materialize.
   Guerrilla sources who demanded anonymity said rebel leaders plan
to focus their firepower mainly on eastern Afghan cities near the
Pakistan border.
   Capture of a major eastern city would provide a capital for the
guerrillas' government-in-exile and provide them a staging base for
their ultimate objective, Kabul.
   But Jalalabad, the guerrillas' first target just 40 miles from
the Pakistan frontier, remains in government hands despite three
months of rebel attacks.
   The rebels want to rid the country of Marxists and establish an
independent, Islamic republic of Afghanistan. They have rejected
repeated peace overtures from the Kabul government.
   Pakistan, which shelters more than 3 million Afghan war refugees,
and the United States have announced they will continue supporting
the guerrillas but with an eye to pursuing a political solution of
the war.
   Hard-line guerrilla leaders such as Hekmatyar along with and
hawks in Islamabad and Washington advocate fighting on for a
military victory.
</TEXT>
