<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Waste     06-12 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Waste,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Companies Involved in Treating Hazardous Waste Lose Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies involved in treating hazardous waste
today lost a Supreme Court appeal aimed at forcing the government to
adopt tougher environmental rules.
   The court, without comment, refused to let the firms sue for
stricter standards that could increase their business volume or give
them a competitive advantage over other waste-treatment companies.
   The justices, instead, let stand a ruling that denies the
companies legal standing to sue in such cases.
   The case prompted an unusual alliance between business and
environmental groups.
   The appeal by the Hazardous Waste Treatment Council, representing
leading treatment firms and makers of advanced technology treatment
equipment, was supported by such prominent environmental groups as
the Environmental Defense Fund, the National Wildlife Federation and
the Natural Resources Defense Council.
   The environmental groups, noting their own limited finances and
technical capabilities, said they welcome legal standing for
industry groups wishing to fight, for whatever motive, for a cleaner
environment.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled against the
waste-treatment companies last October.
   The appeals court said the companies generally may not challenge
as too lax the rules adopted by the federal Environmental Protection
Agency for the treatment, storage and disposal of hazardous waste.
   For example, the companies sought stricter deadlines and
standards for cement kilns used to burn liquid hazardous wastes.
   The Hazardous Waste Treatment Council said lax EPA regulations
reduce the market for high-tech control devices that council members
make and use. The council also said the rules permit the use of
waste treatment facilities inadequate to protect the environment.
   The appeals court said the council may not invoke federal
environmental law to enlist the government's support for rules that
would enhance company profits.
   Also, the appeals court said, ``A firm has no common law
interest, much less a constitutional one, in having government drive
business its way or in having government force competitors' services
to be of the same quality (and cost) as its own.''
   The appeals court also said permitting companies to sue in such
cases could have unintended consequences. For example, requiring
more advanced recycling techniques, ironically, could hurt the
environment by prompting users to substitute more harmful fuels, the
appeals court said.
   It said the only time the waste-treatment companies may sue for
stricter rules is to protect themselves as consumers _ when they
purchase recycled oil for their own use, for example.
   The case is Hazardous Waste Treatment Council vs. Environmental
Protection Agency, 88-1532.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
