<FIRST>r w PM-Water     06-12 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Decision Expanding Indian Water Rights at Fort Mohave
Reservation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An evenly divided Supreme Court today upheld a
federal government decision that effectively expanded Indian water
rights at the Fort Mohave Reservation in Arizona and California.
   By a 4-4 vote, the justices automatically affirmed a federal
appeals court ruling that threw out challenges by officials from
both states.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall did not participate in the case for
unannounced reasons. Announcement of the 4-4 vote came in a
one-sentence opinion.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in 1987 ruled that the U.S.
Department of the Interior correctly added 3,500 acres to the
reservation, an action that had the effect of increasing the
reservation's share of water from the Colorado River.
   Joining the two state governments in challenging that ruling were
the Metropolitan Water District of Southern California and the
Coachella Valley Water District in California.
   Both water districts are run by public corporations that store
and deliver water to other public agencies for municipal and
residential use.
   The state and water district officials said the adjustment of the
reservation's boundaries illegally deprived them of their fair share
of Colorado River water.
   They said the amount of water at stake is enough to serve about
500,000 people for a year.
   The 9th Circuit court ruled that the federal government is immune
from being sued in federal courts in this case.
   ``To allow this suit would permit third parties to interfere with
the government's discharge of its responsibilities to Indian tribes
in respect to the lands it holds in trust for them,'' the appeals
court had ruled.
   The case is California vs. U.S., 87-1165.
</TEXT>
