<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Disability     06-12 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Disability,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Makes It Easier to Recover Lawyers Fees in Social Security
Cases. Elmer is correct first name for Alabama Woman.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today made it easier to
recover lawyers' fees for people who win disputes with the
government over Social Security benefits.
   By a 5-4 vote, the court said the government must reimburse legal
fees incurred during administrative proceedings that a federal court
has ordered the Department of Health and Human Services to conduct.
   The decision is a victory for Elmer Hudson, an Alabama woman who
won disability benefits in a dispute with the government.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, in her opinion for the court, said
requiring the award of legal fees in such cases is in keeping with a
federal law _ the Equal Access to Justice Act _ giving lawyers an
incentive to represent the needy.
   The law demands reimbursement of legal fees for more than just
court proceedings, she said.
   ``We find it difficult to ascribe to Congress an intent to throw
the Social Security claimant a lifeline that it knew was a foot
short,'' said O'Connor.
   She was joined by Justices William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall,
Harry A. Blackmun and John Paul Stevens.
   Dissenting were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices
Byron R. White, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   White, in an opinion joined by the other dissenters, said the
court misread the law.
   ``Our duty is to apply statutes as they were enacted by Congress,
not to take it upon ourselves to overcome the political realities
that blocked what we might consider to be good legislation,'' he
said.
   The case began when Mrs. Hudson filed a Social Secuirty
disability claim in September 1981. She said a variety of physical
and emotional ailments prevented her from continuing to work as a
maid and janitor.
   An administrative law judge of the Health and Human Services
agency denied her claim, ruling that none of Mrs. Hudson's ailments
was so severe as to render her disabled.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overruled the decision in
1985. The appeals court said Mrs. Hudson's impairments must be
considered in combination and sent the case back to the Health and
Human Services agency.
   An administrative law judge then determined she was disabled
since May 1981 and granted her benefits.
   The 11th Circuit court last year said the government now must
reimburse Mrs. Hudson for attorneys' fees she incurred during the
second round of administrative proceedings.
   The former Reagan administration, before it left office in
January, asked the Supreme Court to reverse the appeals court ruling.
   Justice Department lawyers argued that the administrative
proceedings ordered by the 11th Circuit court were not adversarial
in the way that court proceedings are and therefore said legal fees
should not be recoverable.
   The case is Sullivan vs. Hudson, 88-616.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-MissingPlane 1stLd-Writethru a0501 06-12 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Plane, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0501,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Launched for Missing Hawaii Tour Plane With 11 Aboard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with location of Coast Guard search today, details,
police finding nothing in ground search, similar plane crash in 1987. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane with 11 people aboard
disappeared on what was to have been an hourlong tour of the
Hawaiian Islands, and searchers used helicopters and boats to look
for the plane, the Coast Guard said today.
   The U.S. Coast Guard Cutter Point Harris searched overnight
through the channel separating Hawaii Island and Maui Island for the
Scenic Air Tour Hawaii plane that disappeared Sunday afternoon.
   The Coast Guard was concentrating its search for the plane off
the northeast coast of Hawaii Island, the last confirmed location of
the airplane, said Coast Guard spokesman Petty Officer Robert
Bennett.
   Bennett said the Coast Guard received information from Federal
Aviation Administration radar tapes confirming the twin-engine
Beechcraft had left Hilo International Airport on the east side of
Hawaii Island and headed up the island's northeast coast.
   The last communication with the pilot was when he radioed an FAA
ground station that he had taken off from Hilo for Maui's Kahului
Airport, said the FAA's George Harvey.
   The plane was to have toured Hawaii Island, including erupting
Kilauea Volcano, before flying on to Maui, said David Tom, a Scenic
Air Tours Hawaii reservationist in Honolulu.
   Tom, who declined to identify the pilot, said the 10 passengers
aboard the plane had set out earlier Sunday from Honolulu on Oahu
Island. He said they were probably tourists.
   Search efforts Sunday included a Coast Guard C-130 search and
rescue plane and a helicopter, two helicopters provided by the Maui
Fire Department and four Scenic Air Tour Hawaii planes, said Bennett.
   Civil Air Patrol planes and a Coast Guard helicopter were to join
the search when it resumed this morning, Bennett said.
   Hawaii police were also asked to check a section of the island
the pilot was known to fly over during tours, Bennett said. Hilo
police Sgt. Prentiss Morino said ground searches Sunday turned up
nothing and police were to resume looking later today.
   Air strips on the neighboring island also were checked in case
the pilot made a landing without informing the FAA, Harvey said.
   No rains were reported on the two islands Sunday, which had party
sunny skies with low scattered clouds and 15 to 20 mph winds, the
National Weather Service office said. Alenuihaha Channel, which the
plane would have had to cross to get to Maui Island, had 5- to
6-foot seas, it said.
   In December 1987, a twin-engine Panorama Air Tours plane with
eight people aboard disappeared on flight from Honolulu to Molokai
Island. No trace of the plane or those aboard was found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
