<FIRST>u i PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0446 06-12 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Presses Case for Noriega Departure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 17 grafs new with report of meeting; picks up at pvs 10th
graf, Nonetheless, Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle underscored U.S.
insistence that Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega step down
soon and urged Guatemalan leader to promote that goal, Bush
administration officials said today.
   Guatemalan government officials told Quayle in a meeting Sunday
night about a new Organization of American States plan to pressure
Noriega from power. But administration sources said U.S. officials
are worried that the military chief may try to hang on while a
national reconciliation effort in Panama is under way.
   Quayle met with Guatemalan Foreign Minister Mario Palencia on the
eve of Palencia's departure today for Panama as part of an OAS team
that is seeking to negotiate a solution to the Panamanian quagmire.
   Palencia told Quayle, ``There was a new plan, a new formula, that
was being applied, in the thus far unsuccessful effort to remove
Noriega,'' who has been indicted by U.S. grand juries on
drug-trafficking charges, said an official traveling with Quayle.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, declined to
give specifics of that plan other than to say it would provide for
deposing Noriega and installing a democratically elected government.
   One official told reporters that Quayle was interested in the
proposal but was insistent on the U.S. position that Noriega must
step down at once and preferably leave Panama. That means Noriega
would not be allowed to remain while his country's politicians
engaged in reconciliation dialogue.
   Quayle reiterated that point this morning to a group of
Guatemalan political and community leaders, saying: ``Our bottom
line is that Noriega must leave, not only from power, but also it is
our position that he should leave the country.''
   The vice president also discussed with the Guatemalans further
steps that might be taken regarding Panama should the OAS effort
fail. Part of the purpose of his three-day, four-nation trip to
Central America is to sound out U.S. allies on initiatives they
might take to further the anti-Noriega effort.
   The possibility was discussed that Noriega might go to a country
that does not have extradition agreements with the United States and
thus avoid having to face drug indictment charges in Florida, one
official said.
   But he added that ``we don't have anything in writing'' from any
countries offering to take Noriega.
   In his meeting Sunday night, Quayle also asked Guatemala's
defense chief, Hector Alejandro Gramajo, to relay to Panamanian
military forces President Bush's position that it is Noriega the
United States opposes, not the Panamanian Defense Force he heads.
   Bush has urged the Panamanian military as well as the country's
citizens to rise up and oust Noriega.
   Quayle later met with Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo
   Flying here Sunday, Quayle told reporters aboard Air Force Two
that he will tell Contra field commanders that they should consider
dropping their fight against leftist-ruled Nicaragua and returning
home peacefully.
   ``We are clearly on a diplomatic and political course,'' with
regard to Nicaragua, he said. ``I will lay out the option to them
about the possibility of returning to Nicaragua,'' as envisioned in
Bush's $49 million package of non-lethal aid to the U.S.-backed
Contras.
   Bush and Congress agreed that the U.S. money can be used for
repatriation of the Contras while the presidents of the five Central
American countries negotiate toward free elections in Nicaragua next
February.
   Quayle was skeptical that Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega will
fulfill his promise to hold fair elections.
   Nonetheless, Quayle said, he will talk with the Contras about the
possibility that they might want to return and take part in the
Nicaraguan political process. He meets the Contras on Tuesday in
Honduras.
   The 11,000-member Contra army is camped in Honduras near the
Nicaraguan border, but Quayle will meet with the commanders, and
possibly their military leader, Enrique Bermudez, in the capital of
Tegucigalpa.
   Quayle said his reservations about Ortega shouldn't be taken by
the Contras as a signal to hold on for the possibility of renewed
U.S. military aid.
   The Democratic-controlled Congress has blocked more military aid
and that isn't likely to change, he agreed.
   Speaking of the possibility of the Contras returning home, Quayle
said, ``I'm certainly going to lay that out as an option. And if
they feel comfortable, they should be encouraged to go back.''
   But he added, `I don't think it would be proper for me to say
this is your only option.''
   The vice president said Nicaragua's leadership doesn't appear to
be moving toward free elections.
   Of the Contra commanders, Quayle said, `I don't have to tell them
what Danny Ortega's track record is.''
   U.S. officials say they have evidence that Nicaragua is still
supplying weapons to leftist rebels in El Salvador, in violation of
regional peace agreement signed by Ortega.
   Quayle said the focus of his trip, in addition to discussing the
Panama question, will be to spotlight regional democracy and to
``get involved on a substantive basis'' with the presidents before
they and Ortega meet again in July for more work on their peace plan.
   Regarding the latter mission, Quayle said he intended to discuss
U.S. objections to the all-powerful electoral commission formed by
the Sandinistas to oversee the elections. The administration claims
the membership is stacked in favor of the Sandinistas, putting
opposition candidates at a disadvantage.
</TEXT>
