<DOCNO> AP890612-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BarnBurner     06-12 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barn Burner,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arsonist Torches 22 Barns In Two Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMER, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers in McNairy County have taken to
camping in their barns to catch an arsonist who has set fire to 22
barns in two years.
   ``It's got everybody baffled,'' said Sheriff Robert Lee. ``It's
just hard to catch an arsonist. You've got no idea ... why they're
doing it.''
   Investigators say the arsonist strikes late Sunday or early
Monday and burns up to three barns at a time. The firebug doesn't
use an accelerant such as gasoline, just the materials at hand. The
last fire was May 22.
   All but one of the barns were destroyed.
   ``It looks like the person is trying to burn people out,'' said
Grady White, whose Stantonville barn burned in 1988. ``People try to
watch their barns as close as they can. But they're pretty smart
about it, whoever they are.''
   Authorities say they have some suspects, but no arrests have been
made despite hundreds of hours of investigation.
   The arsonist is believed to live in the rural county, about 80
miles from Memphis.
   The Forestry Department and the Farm Bureau are offering up to
$7,000 for information on the crimes, Robert Frost, assistant
commissioner of fire prevention for the Department of Commerce and
Insurance, said last week.
   Neighborhood watch groups have been formed over the last six
months, and some farmers camp out in their barns Sunday nights.
Investigators have also conducted stakeouts and set up roadblocks,
but no one has spotted the firebug.
   ``The only thing people can do is watch their own property,''
Fire Chief Jimmy Dickey said. ``A lot of them are talking about
neighborhood watch groups, and I said as long as you keep yourself
clear of it, it's OK.
   ``I just don't want to see anyone get hurt.''
   Racine Meek, who lost a tractor and other equipment in a blaze
near Adamsville, blames arson investigators for the lack of an
arrest.
   ``I don't have much confidence in the arson people here,'' Meek
said.
</TEXT>
