<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-PleaBargain     06-12 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Plea Bargain,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Bolsters Judges' Power to Impose Harhser Penalties on Some
Defendants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today bolstered the power of
judges to impose harsher penalties on criminal defendants who back
out of plea-bargained agreements that called for lighter sentences.
   The justices, by an 8-1 vote, apparently reinstated the life
sentence of an Alabama man convicted of burglary.
   Before standing trial in 1986, James Lewis Smith had pleaded
guilty to the burglary charge and had been sentenced to 30 years in
prison for it.
   Smith was indicted in Montgomery, Ala., on charges of rape,
burglary and sodomy _ all arising from the same incident.
   In a plea-bargain agreement, he pleaded guilty to rape and
burglary and the sodomy charge was dropped. Smith was sentenced to
30 years on each conviction, with the sentences to run concurrently.
   He then sought to withdraw his guilty plea, and a state appeals
court allowed him to do so. It ruled that Smith had not been
informed that he would be sentenced as a repeat offender, and would
be subject to stiffer penalties than he expected.
   Smith then stood trial and was convicted of all three crimes. The
same state judge who had accepted his guilty plea sentenced Smith to
separate life terms for sodomy and burglary, but set aside the
sentence for Smith's rape conviction.
   The Alabama Supreme Court last year threw out Smith's life
sentence on the burglary conviction, ruling that it represented
judicial vindictiveness.
   The state court's ruling, however, did not affect Smith's life
sentence for the sodomy conviction.
   Alabama Attorney General Don Siegelman then asked the nation's
highest court to draw a distinction between cases in which
defendants withdraw guilty pleas and those in which they are
resentenced after successfully appealing convictions or sentences.
   In a pair of 1969 decisions, the court limited judges' power to
impose more stringent sentences for defendants in both circumstances.
   But today's decision reversed one of the 1969 rulings to create
the distinction Siegelman had sought.
   ``There is no basis for a presumption of vindictiveness where a
second sentence imposed after a trial is heavier than a first
sentence imposed after a guilty plea,'' Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist wrote for the court.
   He said Smith is free to pursue with the Alabama Supreme Court
his contention that there is evidence to support a finding of actual
vindictiveness by the sentencing judge in his case.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall was the sole dissenter.
   The case is Alabama vs. Smith, 88-333.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
