<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-USMilitary     06-12 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-US Military,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Superpower Accord Reduces Chance Of Military Conflicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union today signed
an agreement to prevent military incidents such as accidental
intrusions by enemy warplanes from causing major conflicts between
the superpowers.
   The accord was signed at a Defense Ministry ceremony by the
Soviet armed forces chief of staff, Gen. Mikhail A. Moiseyev, and
Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the U.S. joint chiefs of
staff.
   Crowe today began an official 11-day visit to the Soviet Union.
   The 19-page accord came after nine months of negotiations between
top U.S. and Soviet officials. It goes into effect Jan. 1.
   The agreement, intentionally limited in scope, does not touch
upon some areas where military incidents have occurred, such as the
shooting death of a U.S. Army major in East Germany in 1985 and the
bumping of two U.S. Navy ships by Soviet vessels in the Black Sea
last year. It also does not touch upon incidents involving civilian
aircraft.
   The accord does cover the accidental straying of military units
into the other country's territory and the hazardous use of
laser-range finders.
   It also covers hampering military operations in a tense area,
such as the Persian Gulf during the Iran-Iraq War, and interfering
with command and communications networks.
   The agreement spells out radio frequencies and code phrases for
contacting military aircraft, ships, or ground units that stray into
foreign territory, according to U.S. Air Force Maj. Gen. George L.
Butler. He led the U.S. negotiating team for the agreement.
</TEXT>
