<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS correspondent Harry Reasoner has become a
college graduate, receiving his bachelor's degree along with other
University of Minnesota students.
   Reasoner, co-editor of ``60 Minutes,'' also addressed 950
graduates at Sunday's commencement, drawing loud applause when he
referred to his ``classmates.''
   Reasoner attended the university from 1940 to 1942 and again in
1950, but his career prevented him from completing the requirements
until recently.
   He received the needed credits by submitting about a half-dozen
classes worth of independent study to Minnesota's School of
Journalism. His grades were not disclosed.
   In an address titled ``Can We Survive This Century?'' Reasoner
said survival will depend on the strength of the middle class.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cybill Shepherd says it's her duty to be an
outspoken feminist.
   ``I've read that some younger women don't see the need to
identify themselves as a feminist,'' the actress said in the July
issue of Glamour. ``Personally, I feel I owe something to the women
who came before me, who sacrificed to get us where we are today.''
   Ms. Shepherd said she became a feminist in 1970 but wasn't active
until four years ago, when she joined Gloria Steinem's group Voters
for Choice. Her first demonstration was an abortion-rights rally in
Washington in April.
   ``My belief that abortion is a constitutional right has gotten
even stronger, particularly because I have daughters,'' said Ms.
Shepherd.
   She has two daughters, 9-year-old Clementine Ford and 1{-year-old
Ariel Shepherd-Oppenheim, as well as Ariel's twin brother, Zack.
   ``Whenever you go out and march about an issue like this, you
take a risk. You're exposed. Some fanatic might shoot you,'' she
said.
   ``But in my heart, I realized that I would be willing to die for
this issue, to prevent the deaths that would result if abortion were
made illegal again.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Couples who live together before marriage to
determine if they are compatible could probably learn more about
each other if they borrowed a 3-year-old for a while, Dr. Joyce
Brother says.
   The psychologist, columnist and author made the observation
during a weekend appearance for Celebration of Women week at the
University of Southern Colorado.
   On the subject of opposites attracting, Brothers said one of the
hardest parts of marriage is to learn how to forgive a spouse for
the very trait that attracted you to that person in the first place.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folk singer and activist Joan Baez invited
a banned singer on stage during a concert in Czechoslovakia this
weekend, but the microphones went dead as he began his song, an
activist news agency said.
   Baez was charged with breach of contract by concert organizers
after her performance, during which she also dedicated songs to an
imprisoned political activist and to independent Czech groups, the
report said Sunday.
   The report was issued by the independent East European news
agency VIA, run by activists in Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Poland and
the Soviet Union.
   Before her performance as part of an officially sponsored folk
festival in the Slovak capital of Bratislava, Baez met with nine
Czech activists, including banned playwright Vaclav Havel, who was
released last month midway through an eight-month jail sentence that
drew unprecedented protest at home and abroad.
   When Baez invited singer Ivan Hoffman, who is banned from
performing in Bratislava, on stage, the microphones were turned off,
the report said.
   The microphones were again switched off when Baez invited other
Czech performers on stage to sing the folk song ``Donna, Donna,''
but the audience of 2,500 people joined in the song, VIA said.
  
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning poet Gwendolyn Brooks
received an affectionate tribute from colleagues as well as an award
from the National Endowment for the Arts for her lifelong
contribution to American letters.
   Many of the 72-year-old writer's works have been marked with
bitterness and anger, but Sunday's award ceremony at the Chicago
Poetry Festival was warm and friendly.
   ``I've been in shock since ... they told me about the award,''
Ms. Brooks, Illinois' poet laureate, told the 200 poets and
well-wishers in attendance.
   The $40,000 award was given to Ms. Brooks for ``extraordinary
contributions to American literature over a lifetime of creative
work.'' Writers Hortense Calisher and Eudora Welty also received the
award Sunday.
   In 1950 Ms. Brooks became the first black to win a Pulitzer
Prize, for ``Annie Allen,'' her second collection of poems.
</TEXT>
