<FIRST>u i PM-Iran 2ndLd-Writethru a0570 06-12 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0570,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Speaker Re-Elected In Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 13h graf, `Rafsanjani thanked...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT
Khamenei to Khomeini. Pickup 14th, ``He also...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani of
Iran, whose political position has strengthened since Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's death, was re-elected today to another one-year
term, Iran's news agency said.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
said that 230 out of 241 deputies attending a special session of the
Majlis, the Iranian parliament, voted for Rafsanjani.
   One deputy voted against and there were 10 abstentions, IRNA said.
   Rafsanjani, 55, who also is the armed forces commander-in-chief,
has served as speaker for the past eight years.
   His armed forces post was reconfirmed last week by President Ali
Khamenei, who was selected to succeed Khomeini as Iran's leader.
   Khomeini died June 3 of a heart attack suffered 11 days after he
underwent surgery to stop intestinal bleeding.
   Rafsanjani, a political ally of Khamenei, is the only declared
candidate in the Aug. 18 presidential election. Under the
constitution, Khamenei cannot run for a third four-year term.
   Constitutional reforms expected to give the president increased
executive power at the expense of the prime minister's post are to
be approved in a referendum being held on the same day as the
presidential election.
   The reforms are intended to end disputes among competing power
centers in the hierarchy and speed up the decision-making process.
   Rafsanjani is considered the leader of a faction that favors
restoring ties with the West and boosting private enterprise in
order to rebuild the country's economy after the eight-year war with
Iraq.
   That faction is locked in a dispute with hardliners in the
regime, among them Prime Minister Hussein Musavi, who want to
maintain Iran's self-imposed isolation and advocate self-reliance.
   Before his death, Khomeini reinforced the radicals by calling for
a revival of revolutionary fervor and the assassination of British
author Salman Rushdie for allegedly blaspheming Islam in his novel
``The Satanic Verses.''
   Rafsanjani thanked the Assembly of Experts, a body of
parliamentarians and theologians, for their swift selection of a new
leader the day after Khomeini's death. ``The people welcomed this
right choice and the enemies mourntheir empty dreams shattered,'' he
said, referring to predictions that Iran would be plunged into
political turmoil immediately after Khomeini died.
   He also called on parliament to work toward achieving Khomeini's
aims.
   ``As in the past, the Majlis must follow the leadership and,
while serving the people, carry out the principles of Islam,''
Rafsanjani said.
</TEXT>
