<HEAD>President Declares Flood Disasters in Ohio, Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today declared the states of
Ohio and Alaska eligible for disaster aid because of flooding caused
by heavy rains last month.
   The major disaster declarations clear the way for residents and
business owners in the affected areas to qualify for federal help.
   The Ohio disaster stemmed from heavy rains and flooding that
began May 23. The areas eligible for relief are the counties of
Butler, Cuyahoga, Geauga, Greene, Lake, Lorain, Mercer, re a
5.9-magnitude quake struck Oct. 1, 1987, and a 5.3 aftershock Oct. 4
caused $358 million in damage, eight deaths and 200 injuries.
However, today's quakes were not aftershocks to those quakes, said
Diane Barnhart, a spokeswoman for the Caltech.
   The shaker was reported felt as far east as Banning, 85 miles
east of downtown Los Angeles.
   ``It was like a ride at Magic Mountain where it just shakes and
shakes,'' said Joseph Libby in Torrance, about 15 miles south of
downtown. ``Some things fell of shelves, like books, but I can't see
any real damage.''
   The tremor shook City Hall violently for 12 to 15 seconds,
knocking plaster and ceiling fixtures down. Many employees were
evacuated from the Civic Center complex downtown. Other downtown
buildings also had cracked plaster.
   In the Silver Lake area near downtown, resident Cal Werner
reported feeling a sharp jolt. He said his dog ran barking down the
hall and ``he never barks at anything.''
   Los Angeles City fire tra seismograph.
   Some experts say the actual amount of energy released may be 30
times greater.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6
severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of
tremendous damage.
   The San Francisco earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the
Richter scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the Richter
scale.
