<FIRST>u a PM-Scotus-Discrimination-Reax     06-12 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Discrimination-Reax,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer For White Firemen Says Court Takes Step To End Employment
Bias</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus-Discrimination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for white firemen challenging
a racially tailored hiring plan in the Birmingham Fire Department
said today's U.S. Supreme Court ruling clears the way for white
firefighters to have their day in court.
   But an attorney for black firemen said the judicial system would
have to ignore history to rule against affirmative action in
Alabama's largest city.
   Ray Fitzpatrick, an attorney for the International Association of
Firefighters Local 17, representing white firemen, said the ruling
in the reverse discrimination case is a step toward ending
``race-based quota promotions'' that harm white firefighters in
Birmingham.
   City Fire Chief Neal Gallant declined comment. Neither Birmingham
City Attorney Jim Baker nor Mayor Richard Arrington could not be
reached immediately by telephone for comment.
   The court's decision, on a 5-4 vote, held that an affirmative
action plan agreed to by city officials and approved in court may be
attacked later by workers who took no part in the case leading to
the original agreement.
   New York attorney Robert Joffe, who represents black firefighters
in the case, said the decision is ``just another, unfortunately, in
a too long line of recent cases in which the Supreme Court has put
up road blocks in the way of affirmative action plaintiffs.''
   He said the Birmingham case would be a good test of an
affirmative action policy.
   ``You would have to ignore several hundred years of United States
history to find there wasn't sufficient record'' to warrant
affirmative action in Birmingham, he said.
   But Fitzpatrick said the Supreme Court decision means the city
``may no longer bind its unconsenting non-minority employees to an
agreement which those employees had no part in making.''
   ``Birmingham has engaged in race-based quota promotions and
claims it is protected by a consent decree to which the non-minority
employees were not a party,'' he said. ``We have simply tried to
obtain a day in court to contest the legality of the racial quotas
that Birmingham has been following.''
   Fitzpatrick added that the city ``has never been willing to
engage in any meaningful discussions with the white employees.''
   The Birmingham case began in 1974 when city officials and the
Jefferson County Personnel Board were sued by the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People and blacks
charging racial bias in the city fire department. Eventually both
sides reached agreement on a plan for the hiring and promotion of
minorities.
   The Birmingham Firefighters Association opposed the plan, but its
objections were rejected by a federal judge who issued consent
decrees in 1981 approving the agreement. Seven white firefighters
then challenged the promotion plan, saying less-qualified blacks
were being promoted ahead of them.
   Initially, a federal judge ruled that the white firefighters must
abide by the consent decree. But a federal appeals court in 1987
reinstated the suit, and the Supreme Court today agreed and cleared
the way for the white firefighters' case to be heard.
</TEXT>
