<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Seniority     06-12 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Seniority,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Limits Deadlines for Some Sex Bias Suits in Illinois Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today limited the deadlines
for filing some lawsuits that accuse employers of illegal sex bias.
   In a 5-3 ruling, the court threw out a suit by three women who
said a change in the seniority system at an AT&amp;T plant in Illinois
discriminated against them.
   The court said the women waited too long to sue.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the court, said the women had
300 days to sue from the time the seniority system change was
adopted _ not 300 days from the time they were affected personally
by the new seniority rules.
   Scalia said the shorter time period for suing applies to cases in
which an employer is accused of unintentional bias _ adopting rules
that on their face do not discriminate on the basis of sex.
   ``Allowing a facially neutral system to be challenged ... many
years after its adoption would disrupt'' the legitimate interests of
other workers who benefitted by the new rules, Scalia said.
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Thurgood Marshall said the
ruling shields acts of intentional discrimination.
   He said employees who are victims of bias must sue within 300
days of a change in the employer's system ``even if the employee ...
could not reasonably have expected to be demoted or otherwise
concretely harmed by the new system at the time of its adoption and,
indeed, even if the employee was not working in the affected
division of the company at the time of the system's adoption.''
   Such a severe interpretation of deadlines for suing violates
Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act outlawing discrimination
based on race or sex, he said.
   Justices Willima J. Brennan and Harry A. Blackmun joined
Marshall's dissent.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor did not take part in the ruling.
   The case involves Patricia A. Lorance, Janice M. King and Carol
S. Bueschen, employees in AT&amp;T's Montgomery Works in Aurora, Ill.
   They were demoted in 1982 because of a restructured seniority
system.
   Under the change, seniority for the skilled job of tester no
longer was determined on the basis of how long a worker was at the
plant but rather how long the employee worked as a tester.
   The change was incorporated into a contract between AT&amp;T
Technologies and Local 1942 of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers.
   The three women said the change was designed to limit the job
rights of female workers who had been promoted recently into
traditionally male jobs.
   They filed charges with the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission in April 1983 _ within the 300-day time limit prescribed
by law if that period started with the date the revamped seniority
rules caused their demotions.
   But a federal magistrate in 1986 ruled the three waited too long
because they had not filed their complaint within 300 days of when
the new system was adopted in 1979.
   The magistrate's ruling was upheld by a federal trial judge, the
7th U.S. Cirucit Court of Appeals and today by the Supreme Court.
   The case is Lorance vs. AT&amp;T, 87-1428.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
