<FIRST>u a PM-WiscObscenityLaw     06-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wisc Obscenity Law,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Bars Enforcement Of Wisconsin Obscenity Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge granted a preliminary injunction
today that bars the state from enforcing its year-old obscenity law,
saying it is unconstitutionally vague and unfairly exempts libraries
and schools.
   Under the ruling by U.S. District Judge J.P. Stadtmueller, the
state may appeal to the federal Appeals Court or ask for a trial. If
the state does neither, the preliminary injunction would become
permanent and the law would have to be scrapped.
   Two Milwaukee stores, Denmark Book store and Paradise Video
Store, in addition to Pure Pleasure II Bookstore in Oshkosh, filed
suit in federal court against the state, calling the obscenity
statute unconstitutional.
   Since the law was passed last spring, no one has been criminally
prosecuted. The law, which was intended to halt commercial traffic
in hard-core pornography, calls for jail terms of up to five years
and fines of up to $10,000 for pornography wholesalers.
   Under the statute, material is obscene if it lacks serious
literary, artistic, political, educational or scientific value.
   Attorney General Donald J. Hanaway said today that he had not
seen the decision and would not comment yet.
   Stephen M. Glynn, the attorney representing the stores, called
the decision well-reasoned and said were very pleased by it.
   But a sponsor of the legislation, Sen. Joseph Andrea, said he was
disappointed by Stadtmueller's decision.
   Sponsors, he said, ``were very careful when we put this (the law)
together to address the constitutional concerns,'' Andrea said.
   In his decision, Stadtmueller said the statute was
unconstitutionally vague. The judge said it was difficult to
determine whether the law was violated by depicting sexually
explicit conduct, by describing sexually explicit conduct or both.
   In addition, Stadtmueller said the state violated the equal
protection clause of the Constitution by exempting libraries,
schools and universities from prosecution under the statute.
   The law allows a school library to commercially distribute
obscene materials without the threat of prosecution, but does not
allow an adult bookstore to do the same, the judge said.
   The judge also found unconstitutional the law's distinction
between contract printers and bookstore clerks. Under the statute,
the printers would not be threatened with prosecution, but the store
clerks would.
   Stadtmueller did rule in favor of the state, however, when he
said that the Legislature intended to include videotapes, as well as
film, under the statute.
</TEXT>
