<FIRST>r w AM-TaxBreaks     06-12 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Breaks,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Opposes Putting Special Features on This Year's Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, served notice on colleagues Monday that he will
oppose addition of special tax breaks for selected individuals or
businesses to any legislation written by the panel this year.
   ``As chairman, I have opposed and will continue to oppose any tax
amendments that unfairly benefit certain taxpayers while not
benefiting other similarly situated taxpayers,'' Bentsen, D-Texas,
said in a letter.
   ``Moreover, I have been forthcoming with information available to
me about the beneficiaries of tax legislation, and I plan to
continue that practice,'' he added.
   It has been almost routine practice for several years for members
of the Finance and House Ways and Means committees to attach
amendments benefiting one or two individuals or businesses to
general tax bills. The beneficiaries were seldom named in the
legislation.
   The practice was all but abandoned in 1988, apparently because of
the public outcry that followed inclusion of large numbers of
special breaks in the massive 1986 tax overhaul.
   Bentsen's committee is likely to write several tax bills this
year. On Tuesday, the panel will consider expanding tax credits for
child-care expenses and rewriting a 1986 provision requiring
employers to conduct complex tests to prove that their
health-insurance plans do not discriminate against lower-paid
workers.
</TEXT>
