<FIRST>u a PM-SwindallTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0582 06-12 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swindall Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0582,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Drops One Count Against Former Rep. Pat Swindall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add that judge refused to throw out other nine
counts. SUBS 8-9th grafs, bgng `This morning...', with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with judge disallowing Frank testimony. Picks up last graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today dismissed one of the 10
perjury counts against former Rep. Pat Swindall as the defense phase
of his trial got under way.
   U.S. District Judge Richard C. Freeman said there was confusion
over what period of time was being discussed when Swindall testified
to a federal grand jury about his knowledge of a mortgage company.
He rejected defense motions to throw out the other nine counts as
well.
   Swindall, a Republican, was defeated in his bid for a third term
in the U.S. House last November, not long after he was indicted. He
represented a district in suburban Atlanta.
   He is charged with lying to a federal grand jury in February 1988
regarding his 1987 negotiations with an undercover agent posing as a
money launderer and with Swindall associate Charles LeChasney, later
convicted of money laundering. Many of the negotiations were taped
and played for the jury during the prosecution phase of the trial.
   The original charges cited 37 statements to the grand jury that
prosecutors said were false, grouping the statements into 10 perjury
charges. On Friday, Freeman ruled that five of the 37 statements
were irrelevant to the case, but he let all 10 counts stand until
this morning.
   The count dismissed today involved Swindall's knowledge of who
was to own the Gulf Coast Mortgage Co. that was created during
Swindall's negotiations for a $850,000 housing loan.
   The prosecution rested its case last week. The trial began last
month.
   Also today, Freeman cut short the testimony of Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass., and said he would instruct the jury to disregard Frank's
comments in the hour he spent on the witness stand.
   The judge said the testimony of Frank, called by the defense to
describe the workings of Congress, might infringe on the
constitutional protection given to members of Congress for
performance of their duties.
   Frank had testified that Swindall was not a member of the
subcommittee that handled the money-laundering act of 1986 and that
most congressmen do not have time to learn specifics of all
legislation before Congress.
   At least two other congressmen, Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C., and
Rep. J. Alex McMillan, R-N.C., also had been subpoenaed to testify
for the defense. But they had filed a motion seeking to have their
subpoenaes thrown out.
   Swindall himself is expected to take the stand, possibly as early
as this week. If convicted, he could faces up to five years in
prison on each count of perjury.
</TEXT>
