<DOCNO> AP890612-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages     06-12 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Denies Western Hostages Moved to Tehran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's Foreign Ministry on Monday denied
that Westerners held hostage in Lebanon had been moved to Tehran.
   Iran has no information on the whereabouts of the Westerners
missing in Lebanon, the official Islamic Republic News Agency said,
quoting an unidentified Foreign Ministry spokesman.
   The reports were rumors circulated by the international media,
according to the agency, which was monitored in Nicosia.
   The Observer, a London newspaper, reported this week that six
Western hostages _ five Americans and one Briton _ were moved to
Iran to ensure their safety. The newspaper, quoting unidentified
sources in Beirut, Damascus and Tehran, did not identify the
Americans but said the Briton was journalist John McCarthy.
   The Observer said McCarthy and two of the Americans were
disguised as injured Lebanese, transferred to the Syrian capital on
May 24 and flown to Tehran. The newspaper said three other Americans
were moved to Iran on May 29.
   It said Iran's interior minister, Ali Akbar Mohtashami, decided
to move the hostages after fighting intensified between Christian
and Syrian forces in and around Beirut.
   Most of the 18 Western hostages in Lebanon are believed held by
pro-Iranian Shiite extremist factions. Held longest is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press,
who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Previous reports that hostages had been moved to Iran also could
not be confirmed.
</TEXT>
