<FIRST>r a AM-CancerPrizes     06-12 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cancer Prizes,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Scientists Share Cancer Prizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key discoveries in the effects of radiation, the
genetics of cancer and substances that regulate development of blood
cells have earned cancer prizes for five researchers.
   The three General Motors Cancer Research Foundation Prizes, each
worth $130,000, will be presented Wednesday in Washington.
   Mortimer Elkind of Colorado State University in Fort Collins will
receive a prize for his studies of the biological effects of
radiation.
   His work made it possible for tens of thousands of cancer
patients a year to receive radiation therapy safely and effectively,
the foundation said.
   The research is being used to define permissible levels of
radiation exposure from medical X-rays, nuclear plants, radon and
other sources, the foundation said.
   A second prize will be shared by Peter Nowell of the University
of Pennsylvania School of Medicine in Philadelphia and Janet Rowley
of the University of Chicago. Their work dealt with chromosomes,
thread-like bodies that carry genes.
   Nowell was a co-discoverer of the first consistent chromosome
abnormality in cancer, which led to research linking more than 100
such defects to cancer, the foundation said.
   Rowley revealed that the abnormality occurred when the ends of
two particular chromosomes switched places.
   The third prize will be shared by Donald Metcalf of the Walter
and Eliza Hall Institute of Medical Research in Victoria, Australia,
and Leo Sachs of the Weizmann Institute of Science in Rehovot,
Israel.
   They independently discovered substances called colony
stimulating factors, which regulate growth, maturation and
production of blood cells, the foundation said. The substances are
used to increase production of disease-fighting cells in patients at
high risk of infection, such as cancer patients on chemotherapy.
</TEXT>
