<FIRST>u w PM-US-China 2ndLd-Writethru a0571 06-12 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0571,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Indicates It Will Not Hand Over Dissident Fang</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs with U.S.-Chinese talks; picks up at pvs 3rd graf,
``When a''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has
opened talks with China's ambassador here in an effort to resolve
the case of two dissidents being sheltered in the U.S. Embassy in
Beijing, it was disclosed today.
   Baker called Ambassador Han Xu to his office on Saturday and the
envoy was summoned back on Sunday for another talk with Robert
Kimmitt, the undersecretary for political affairs, State Department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said today.
   The conversations dealt with Fang Lizhi, an astrophysicist, and
his wife, Li Shuxian, an assistant professor at Beijing University.
They were accused of counter-revolutionary activities and warrants
for their arrest were issued Sunday.
   `We`re trying to resolve it,'' said a senior official who
declined to be identified.
   Ms. Tutwiler, meanwhile, challenged Chinese assertions that
hundreds of protesting students were not slain by army troops on
June 3.
   ``The whole world has seen what happened in Tiananmen Square,''
she said. ``Large numbers of peaceful demonstrators were killed by
army units. We condemn the use of live fire against unarmed
civilians, which is what happened in Tiananmen Square.''
   The spokeswoman said the demonstrators were seeking basic human
rights. ``Labeling such people counter-revolutionaries and hooligans
will do nothing to alter the reality of what happened in Tiananmen
Square on June 3,'' she said.
   Earlier today, the Bush administration indicated it would not
permit the Chinese to arrest the two dissidents who took refuge in
the embassy.
   ``When a person presents himself to one of our embassies and says
he is imminent danger and we have reason to give it credence
sometimes we grant refuge,'' a U.S. official said. ``And when we do
that, I ask you `What does it mean?'''
   The administration, in dealing with the crackdown on dissidents
and other pro-democracy forces, is trying not to inflame the
situation by denouncing Chinese authorities.
   But the statement by the U.S. official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, indicated that any attempt to arrest Fang and Li would be
resisted.
   The charges against the two dissidents could amount to
accusations of treason and, amid the turmoil in China, carry the
threat of a death sentence.
   The Beijing government warned that leaders of independent groups
who refuse to surrender will be arrested ``and dealt with severely.''
   Meanwhile, U.S.-Chinese relations have turned sour. President
Bush has suspended military sales to Beijing and all Americans
except diplomats were urged to leave the country.
   James Lilley, the U.S. ambassador to China, said today ``the
jury's still out'' on how the situation will unfold.
   ``Right now we have the semblance of order and control,'' he said
on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.'' ``Certainly Beijing is an
orderly city right now. But I think that we have to wait and see.''
   Lilley declined to discuss the Fang situation, saying ``it's too
sensitive... If you get up and start posturing, it lessens the
chance of getting something done.''
   In a separate interview with NBC-TV's ``Today'' program, Lilley
said he hoped the dispute over Fang and Li was ``not volatile at
all.''
   ``We hope that it's settled and it's out of the way fairly
soon,'' he said.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, said when asked
about Fang: ``It's our judgment it's not helpful in any way to
comment.'' He added that the administration was ``considering this
situation.''
   A reporter called out a question about Fang to President Bush at
the start of a meeting with congressional leaders.
   The lawmakers took that as their cue to break out into a hearty
chorus of ``Happy Birthday, Mr. President'' for Bush, who turned 65
today. Bush laughed and reporters were quickly escorted out of the
room.
</TEXT>
