<FIRST>u i AM-China-Press Bjt   06-12 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Press, Bjt,0874</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Reporters Face Growing Controls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign reporters covering China's crackdown on
pro-democracy protesters no longer have bullets whizzing past their
heads, but some said Monday their job has become harder in the
growing climate of fear.
   Television crews have had their film or equipment confiscated and
been forced to write ``self-criticisms.'' Other reporters have been
stopped by police from talking to people on the street or have had
notebooks taken. A British reporter was expelled from Shanghai.
   The Australian Embassy expressed grave concern Monday over the
safety of its country's journalists, saying, ``From what we've seen
the last few days we can't seriously expect the police or troops to
be fussy about who they shoot.''
   Sources also are drying up. Chinese said they fear talking to
reporters even in private as the number of reported arrests in
connection with seven weeks of pro-democracy protests neared 1,000.
   ``You have to be so careful,'' said Jan Wong of the Toronto Globe
and Mail. ``I don't want to ask people (on the street) their names
... for their protection.''
   TV crews that already were taking precautions when shooting
photographs to avoid detection by security officials said a new
damper was put on their work by the government use of an ABC
videotape to track down a Chinese man.
   China Central Television apparently intercepted the unedited
video as ABC sent it by satellite to New York. It showed a
42-year-old worker claiming that 20,000 people were killed when the
army fired on student protesters and supporters June 3-4.
   CCTV broadcast the interview and urged viewers to find the man.
Two women reported him within hours and he was arrested.
   ABC said it was ``deeply distressed'' over the use of its tape
and began covering the faces of students it interviewed.
   Mike Chinoy, Beijing bureau chief of the Cable News Network, said
some CNN footage also has been used on Chinese TV, although no
arrests have been reported as a result.
   ``Even the people I know with the most extensive contacts among
the Chinese are not talking to them because they don't want to get
them in trouble,'' Chinoy said. ``I'm depressed _ profoundly. I
think it's going to change living and working in China.''
   No news organizations said they were pulling reporters out of
China because of the difficulties, but CNN's Vito Maggiolo said some
of the 25 staff now in Beijing might leave by week's end.
   ``The story has gone behind the scenes and underground to a great
extent,'' he said. ``There's much less to see.''
   Chinoy said, ``The irony is that after a period in which it had
gotten easier and the government had become tolerant of a huge range
of reporting ... All of a sudden it's reverted to a decade ago.
We've been forced to cover China the way China watchers did when it
was a closed society, reading (the official) Xinhua (News Agency),
talking to diplomats and each other.''
   Under the martial law imposed in Beijing May 20, reporters are
barred from conducting interviews on the streets, on campuses, at
factories and other sites without official permission. Photographing
and making audio tapes also are forbidden. Most reporters have
ignored the restrictions.
   Many news organizations have sent reporters to Shanghai despite
official warning they need permission to work there.
   On Saturday, China expelled a reporter for Britain's Independent
Television News who was photographing student protesters outside
Shanghai police headquarters. He was questioned and put on a plane
to Hong Kong.
   More expulsions were expected. China expelled two reporters after
the last major student demonstrations, in 1986-87.
   Several camera crews for the BBC have been detained by police for
photographing on the street, and in one case were forced at gunpoint
to kneel on the ground. In the most recent incident, reporter Brian
Barron said he and his crew had their passports confiscated Sunday,
were told to write self-criticisms and ordered not to leave China
without permission.
   Another Western TV network that asked not to be identified said a
crew was detained and released only after writing self-criticisms.
In most cases, such self-criticisms have consisted of accounts of
what the reporters were doing, with some apologies for
inconveniencing officials.
   Adi Ignatius of the Wall Street Journal said he scuffled Saturday
with plainclothes security who tried to detain him at the Beijing
Normal University campus. He said he broke free of the men, who did
not identify themselves, and got in his car. They kicked the car
door and broke the mirror as he drove away.
   The only foreign news organization to be criticized publicly is
the Voice of America. The official media has castigated it daily
since Friday for alleged distortions. VOA frequencies have been
jammed for weeks.
   ``We've been criticized in the past by the media and officials,''
said VOA Beijing bureau chief Alan Pessin. ``This is unprecedented
in length and scope. They're engaged in an extensive effort to
rewrite the history of the past 10 days. Their tirades against VOA
are only a part of that.''
</TEXT>
