<FIRST>u a PM-Planes-Collision 1stLd-Writethru a0587 06-12 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Planes-Collision, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0587,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planes Collide; One Crashes and At Least One Person Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6-8th grafs, bgng `Lattrell declined....', to UPDATE with
FAA confirming identity of surviving pilot. Picks up penultimate graf,
`Portland International...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUBBARDSTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private plane crashed into a wooded
area near here this morning after striking the wing of another plane
that landed safely, officials said. At least one person was killed.
   Federal Aviation Administration spokeswoman Gail Lattrell said
the pilot of a Cessna 210 bound from Teterborough, N.J., to
Portland, Maine, radioed Boston air traffic controllers about 9:20
a.m. The Cessna managed to land at Portland.
   ``He reported that he struck another aircraft with his left wing
near Gardner,'' she said.
   The FAA spokeswoman said it was not immediately clear how many
people were aboard the plane whose wreckage was discovered near
Hubbardston, but said state police and federal officials were at the
scene.
   ``The wreckage was found. The pilot died,'' she said. ``But we
don't know if there were any other passengers or the extent of
damage to the plane.''
   Lattrell identified the pilot who managed to make his Maine
destination safely as Sheldon Gould, a New York businessman.
   She said passenger Paul Schief, of Brentwood, N.Y., was also
uninjured in the accident, which left the single-engine plane with
minor damage to its left wing.
   ``An airplane at my altitude where it shouldn't have been just
came right at me, and I just swerved and managed to save the
airplane by having the tip of the wing caught and nothing else,''
Gould said this morning in an interview with television station WCSH
in Portland.
   Portland International Jetport emergency crews gathered as air
traffic controllers guided the hobbled plane to a safe landing about
10 a.m.
   ``We picked him up down around Kennebunk, and we worked him into
Portland,'' Wayne Owen said at the Portland airport. ``His left wing
was damaged, and that's about all I can say.''
</TEXT>
