<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildHealth     06-12 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Health,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Policies Seen If Tax Credit Becomes Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health insurance companies will develop new
policies to cover children of low-income Americans if a proposal to
offer parents a tax credit of up to $500 to help pay for the
premiums becomes law, an industry official predicted Monday.
   Mary Nell Lehnhard, vice president of the Blue Cross and Blue
Shield Association, told the Senate Finance Committee there were an
estimated 11 million children in the United States with no health
insurance in 1985 _ about three-fourths of them in familes with
annual incomes of $20,000 or less.
   She said a survey of the association's 75 health plans nationwide
suggested that roughly half of the small employers who provide some
health insurance coverage for their workers do not pay anything
toward coverage for their dependents.
   In supporting a tax credit proposal by Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, Ms. Lehnhard said the Medicaid health program for the poor
``frequently forces parents to choose between going to work in a
low-paying job _ with unaffordable health benefits for themselves
and-or their dependents _ or remaining on Medicaid to assure that
their children have access to health care services.''
   Adopting the Finance Committee chairman's plan, she said, would
give families increased ability to purchase coverage for their
children under employer-sponsored health plans and also allow more
low-income families to buy policies if there is no health plan where
they work.
   ``We believe that private health insurance markets will respond
to these incentives by making available low-cost products with the
objective of reaching children,'' said Ms. Lehnhard.
   As an example, she cited a Blue Shield of California program
introduced last summer that establishes special rates for children
in two age categories _ 1 to 4 years old and 5 to 18.
   She said a typical policy covering a child 5 to 18 would cost the
parent $250 a year. For a child 1 to 4, the cost would be $320.
   The Bentsen bill, to be acted on by the panel Tuesday, also would
extend an existing child care tax credit to lower income workers by
making them eligible for a cash refund if they did not have to pay
enough federal income tax to take advantage of the benefit the way
it is now structured.
   Willis B. Goldbeck, president of the Washington Business Group on
Health, said the major employers his organization represents
supports both the child care and health care tax credits in the
Bentsen bill.
   He said the programs are intended for ``people most in need.''
   ``They are the ones trying hardest to maintain the American work
ethic rather than falling prey to the cycle of poverty that we all
know is far more expensive to society than the cost of your proposed
tax credit,'' he told Bentsen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
