<FIRST>r w AM-Cambodia-Aid     06-12 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-Aid,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solarz Asks More Military Aid for Cambodian Resistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military aid to non-communist factions in
Cambodia should be increased from the $7 million now planned to as
much as $30 million to help prevent the return to power of the Khmer
Rouge, Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., said Monday.
   ``Providing military assistance to non-communist resistance
forces will strengthen the ability of Cambodians wishing to resist
the Khmer Rouge'' after occupying Vietnamese forces are withdrawn in
September, Solarz told a Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee.
   ``These are Cambodian forces who are willing to put their lives
on the line in order to prevent a repetition of the Khmer Rouge
holocaust,'' Solarz said. ``Don't we have a moral obligation to help
them out?''
   Solarz said he believes the $7 million in military aid sought by
the Bush administration is too little to do the job of strengthening
anti-communist forces.
   ``I would favor giving them more,'' Solarz said. ``This is not a
light or peripheral issue. This is a matter of preventing another
holocaust. For starters, I would provide somewhere between $20
million to $30 million.''
   Robert M. Kimmitt, undersecretary of state for political affairs,
said the administration believes that strengthening the
non-communist resistance, including Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
Cambodia's former ruler, will help achieve a peaceful political
solution and prevent the return of the Khmer Rouge.
   But other witnesses said they feared that military aid might fall
into the hands of the Khmer Rouge and lead to the restoration of a
regime blamed for killing hundreds of thousands of Cambodians.
   ``I am deeply skeptical of the wisdom of such a policy,'' said
Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., the subcommittee chairman. ``I reject
the notion that the best means of dealing with the volatile and
potentially violent situation in Southeast Asia is to inject
military aid.''
   ``Providing military aid would add a potentially explosive
element of instability into the process,'' Cranston said.
   Richard Holbrooke, who was assistant secretary of state for Asian
affairs in the Carter administration, said he also believes that
arming the non-communist forces would be a mistake.
   ``I believe we are headed toward a situation where the Khmer
Rouge will be invited to participate in a coalition government in
Cambodia,'' he said.
   And he said he feared that ``a limited amount of military aid to
an incompetent military force leads us to a later dilemma: Do we
increase that aid or do we continue it at all?''
   But Solarz said that because of the desire to prevent a
repetition of the the killings of the past, ``we are dealing with
one of the transcendental moral issues of our time.''
   He said by providing arms to Sihanouk and the non-communist
resistance, the United States would simultaneously strengthen their
position at the negotiating table.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
