<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1533EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Reagan     06-12 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Has Accepted Knighthood, Burke's Peerage Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan has been offered an
honorary knighthood and has accepted the highest royal honor Britain
bestows on Americans, Burke's Peerage said Monday.
   Reagan, who is in London on his first visit since leaving the
White House in January, will be the guest of Queen Elizabeth II at a
Buckingham Palace lunch Wednesday, but nobody would say whether she
would give him an award.
   Harold Brooks-Baker, publishing director of Burke's Peerage,
which chronicles the British aristocracy, said: ``We understand it
has been offered and will be accepted either this trip or his next
trip, which is expected to be next spring.''
   Asked whether it was likely to be announced this week, he said:
``I think it's very likely, but we don't know.''
   Buckingham Palace and Reagan's press spokesman, Mark Weinberg,
referred all queries to the Foreign Office, where a spokesman said:
``I simply do not know whether the queen is going to give President
Reagan a knighthood.''
   British honors such as knighthoods are awarded by the queen,
although most are made on the recommendation of Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher. Buckingham Palace said awards to foreign
officials must be recommended by the Foreign Office.
   Brooks-Baker said Reagan was offered a knighthood ``because
because of his special contribution to the British government under
Mrs. Thatcher. He helped Mrs. Thatcher in the Falklands War and in
many different ways.''
   The United States provided naval intelligence, communications
facilities and political support to Britain during its 1982 war
against Argentina over the Falkland Islands in the south Atlantic.
   Several members of Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative Party have urged
that Reagan be given a high British honor.
   Lawmaker Harry Greenway said such an honor would be ``not only in
recognition of his unique special relationship with Britain but also
to mark his massive contribution to world peace.''
   If Reagan receives an honorary knighthood, he would be the 57th
American to receive the award, joining his former secretary of
defense, Caspar Weinberger, who was made a knight in 1988; fellow
actors Douglas Fairbanks Jr. and Sidney Poitier; President Dwight D.
Eisenhower; and philanthropists Paul Mellon and John Paul Getty II.
   An honorary knighthood wouldn't mean Reagan could call himself
Sir Ronald. That accolade is reserved for the queen's own subjects,
although Brooks-Baker insists there is nothing in U.S. law
preventing Reagan or any other American from using a British title.
   Reagan will deliver a lecture Tuesday on the problems and
challenges confronting the English-speaking world. Afterward, he and
his wife, Nancy, will be guests at a dinner given by Mrs. Thatcher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
