<FIRST>r a AM-SwindallTrial     06-12 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall Trial,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses One Of 10 Perjury Counts Against Swindall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Monday dismissed one of 10 perjury counts
against former Rep. Pat Swindall as the defense began its case.
   U.S. District Judge Richard C. Freeman called the count ``just
too confusing for a jury trial.''
   The judge also threw out more than half an hour of testimony
Monday by a defense witness, Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., who
discussed the knowledge that congressmen do and do not have
regarding the details of legislation.
   Swindall was indicted on charges of lying to a federal grand jury
in 1988 about negotiating a loan in 1987 from an agent posing as a
money launderer. Prosecutors said Swindall lied in denying he was
told some of the money might have come from drug trafficking.
   The dismissed charge said Swindall lied when he testified that he
knew little about Gulf Coast Mortgage Corp., the company created by
a Swindall associate to funnel the $850,000 loan to Swindall from
the agent.
   Swindall, if convicted, faces up to five years in prison on each
of the remaining nine counts.
   The defense opened its case Monday by calling Frank, one of at
least three members of Congress subpoenaed by the defense.
   Frank explained that members of Congress have little knowledge of
the nuts-and-bolts of the hundreds of bills Congress considers each
year, unless their specific subcommittees are involved.
   The prosecution has argued that Swindall, a former member of the
House Banking and Judiciary committees, should have been especially
aware of money-laundering laws.
   Frank said ``no human being'' could know the details of ``more
than 20 percent'' of the bills before Congress.
   Frank, a member of the Banking Committee, testified that Swindall
was not a member of the subcommittee that handled the
money-laundering act passed in 1986.
   But he said ``a well-informed member would know we were including
in the drug bill efforts to stop (criminals) from laundering money
and ... getting cute.''
   Freeman said he would order the jury to disregard Frank's
testimony because it could ``open the Pandora's Box'' of matters
protected by the Constitution's clause guarding the ``speech and
debate'' activities of Congress.
</TEXT>
