<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-China     06-12 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Criticizes China and Deng On Human Rights, Holds Talks On Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday challenged
Chinese assertions that its troops did not fire on pro-democracy
students massed in Tiananmen Square. ``The whole world has seen what
happened,'' said spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   Seizing the offensive, the department also chastized senior
leader Deng Xiaoping even as the United States pressed efforts to
find a diplomatic solution for two dissidents sheltered in the U.S.
Embassy in Beijing and threatened with arrest.
   ``We're trying to resolve it,'' a senior U.S. official said of
the case of Fang Lizhi, an astrophysicist critical of the Chinese
government, and his wife, Li Shuxian, an assistant professor at
Beijing University.
   They were accused of counter-revolutionary activities and
warrants for their arrest were issued on Sunday.
   Stepping into the dispute, Secretary of State James A. Baker III
called Han Xu, the Chinese ambassador, to his office Saturday. The
envoy was summoned back Sunday for a talk with Robert Kimmitt, the
undersecretary of state for political affairs, Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Reading a statement that reversed days of a deliberately
low-keyed U.S. approach to the tumult in China, the spokeswoman
declared:
   ``The whole world has seen what happened in Tiananmen Square.
Large numbers of peaceful demonstrators were killed by army units.
We condemn the use of live fire against unarmed civilians, which is
what happened in Tiananmen Square.''
   The spokeswoman said the demonstrators were seeking basic human
rights. ``Labeling such people counter-revolutionaries and hooligans
will do nothing to alter the reality of what happened in Tiananmen
Square on June 3,'' she said.
   The Chinese government has said that about 300 people were killed
in the assault and that most were soldiers. Other estimates place
the death toll as high as 3,000.
   Ms. Tutwiler also had sharp words for Deng Xiaoping, China's
senior leader, who emerged from more than three weeks of seclusion
Friday to praise the army's suppression of pro-democracy forces.
   The performance cast doubt on Deng's reputation as a cautious but
ardent advocate of reforming the Marxist system. Ms. Tutwiler said
if Deng ``was responsible for the brutal attack on Tiananmen Square,
then he has acted to undercut the very reform process he has sought
to foster.''
   Baker and Kimmitt, a close aide, were believed in their meetings
with Ambassador Han to be exploring ways to arrange safe passage
from China for Fang, the country's best known dissident, and his
wife. But U.S. officials, concerned about the couple's welfare,
declined to discuss the case.
   Earlier, a U.S. official who spoke on the condition of anonymity
indicated the United States would not permit Chinese authorities to
arrest the two dissidents.
   ``When a person presents himself to one of our embassies and says
he is imminent danger and we have reason to give it credence
sometimes we grant refuge,'' a U.S. official said. ``And when we do
that, I ask you, `What does it mean?'''
   The charges against the dissidents could amount to accusations of
treason and, amid the turmoil in China, carry the threat of a death
sentence.
   The Beijing government has warned that leaders of independent
groups who refuse to surrender would be arrested ``and dealt with
severely.''
   Meanwhile, the department reported that Chinese police and other
security forces had surrounded the U.S. Embassy in an obvious effort
to keep other dissidents from taking refuge there.
   James Lilley, the U.S. ambassador to China, declined to discuss
the Fang situation in an interview on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America.
   ``It's too sensitive,'' he said. ``If you get up and start
posturing, it lessens the chance of getting something done.''
   In a separate interview with NBC-TV's ``Today'' program, Lilley
said he hoped the dispute over Fang and Li was ``out of the way
fairly soon.''
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said when asked
about Fang, ``It's our judgment it's not helpful in any way to
comment.''
   By the latest estimate, one U.S. official said, about 1,100
Americans are still in China. All who wanted to leave are gone or
are on their way out, Ms. Tutwiler said. Over the weekend 159
Americans joined the exodus.
</TEXT>
