<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Ecology     06-12 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Ecology,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Proposes Cooperation on Ecology</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
on Monday proposed ecological cooperation with West Germany that
would include exchanges of technology and emergency assistance in
case of an environmental disaster.
   Speaking at a dinner given by West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl,
Gorbachev said the ``scientific-technical and economic possibilities
of the U.S.S.R. and West Germany would have a huge meaning'' in
Europe's effort to combat pollution.
   Any agreement would more directly benefit the Soviet Union's new
ecology program than the well-established West German effort.
   The Soviets' environmental protection agency was created only
last year and still lacks the finances and many of the powers it
needs to crack down on polluters.
   Soviet officials said last month they were finishing a
comprehensive environmental protection package but they were still
working out technical options for factories to reduce effluence.
   Gorbachev suggested the Soviets and West Germany could conduct
research to develop joint ventures to build pollution control
equipment, process wastes, exchange information between regions and
cities in the two countries, agree on a program of urgent aid in
case of accidents and develop working groups to help form an
all-Europe environmental policy.
   Gorbachev praised the efforts of French President Francois
Mitterrand, and West Germany's opposition Social Democrats and
Greens parties to work out international environmental agreements.
He did not mention Kohl's Christian Democratic Union, which has been
slower to formulate environmental protection policies.
   Thousands of Soviet citizens have participated in demonstrations
protesting decades of rushed industrial production that ignored
environmental consequences.
   Soviet officials have said 50 million people live in cities where
air pollution sometimes exceeds acceptable limits by 10 times and
the country's main waterways are dying because of the dumping of
industrial wastes.
   Environmental activists say overuse of pesticides and chemical
fertilizers are poisoning the food Soviets eat.
   Gorbachev and other government leaders were criticized repeatedly
on the ecology issue by parliamentarians during the Congress of
People's Deputies session that ended Friday.
   Germans are concerned about Soviet environmental policies,
especially after the April 1986 Chernobyl nuclear power-plant
disaster. The explosion and fire at the Chernobyl plant in the
northern Ukraine killed at least 31 people and released a cloud of
radiation that spread around the world.
</TEXT>
