<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1652EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Bomb     06-12 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Bomb,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes at Rail Station, Killing 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A time bomb believed to have been planted
by Sikh militants exploded at the main railroad station Monday,
killing eight people and injuring 53 others, police said.
   The bomb exploded in the station's crowded entrance hall where
hundreds of people were waiting for trains or to buy tickets, police
said.
   No group claimed responsibility for the bombing, police said, but
the blast came a week after authorities announced a city-wide alert
against possible terrorist strikes by Sikh extremists around the
fifth anniversary of a bloody army raid on the Sikh Golden Temple in
Amritsar on June 6, 1984.
   The bomb killed seven people at the scene; 54 others were
hospitalized, including a 2{-year-old girl who died from her
injuries, according to police officials speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The girl and her parents were from Karachi, Pakistan, and the
family was waiting to board a train for eastern Calcutta, the
officials said. Her parents were not injured, they said.
   ``We suspect it was the work of the Babbar Khalsa,'' said Police
Commisssioner V.N. Singh. The Babbar Khalsa is one of the
underground militias fighting for an independent Sikh nation in the
northern state of Punjab.
   ``We did suspect this kind of thing,'' Singh said. ``There was
some information from intelligence agencies. There was an alert. But
our arrangements cannot be fool-proof.''
   Singh said whoever planted the bomb could have boarded a train
after dropping the device in the hall.
   Press Trust of India quoted a witness, Pawan Kumar, as saying he
saw a man with a mustache ask someone to look after his briefcase
and a wooden crate while he went to drink water. A few minutes later
the bomb exploded in the same spot, the news agency quoted Kumar as
saying.
   Sandals, sunglasses, and food was strewn across the entrance hall
floor. Blood splattered the hall's 60-foot-high ceiling and a
100-square-foot section of the floor.
   ``It was like hell,'' said Ramesh Kumar, who was in the hall but
escaped injury. ``I thought I was seeing a bad bloody movie.''
   The city's 32,000-member police force was placed on alert. Road
blocks were set up on major roads and vehicles were checked.
   Police made announcements at crowded markets and the capital's
main bus station warning people to stay away from suspicious objects
or unclaimed luggage.
   Sikh militants have been fighting for an independent homeland
since 1982, claiming discrimination by the country's Hindu majority.
They have been blamed in at least 850 killings in Punjab state this
year and for sporadic attacks in the capital in previous years.
   The 1984 raid on the Sikh Golden Temple was aimed at flushing out
armed militants entrenched in the shrine and left at least 1,200
people dead, many of them Sikhs. Less than five months later, Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi was assassinated by Sikh bodyguards in
retaliation.
   The last major Sikh attack in New Delhi occurred on June 20,
1988, when Sikh militants hurled a homemade grenade into a crowded
vegetable market. Four people were killed and more than 40 wounded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Anderson-Guns 2ndLd-Writethru a0657 06-12 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anderson-Guns, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0657,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fellow Journalists Criticize Anderson `Stunt'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs `Keenan Block ...' with 1 graf to CORRECT
spelling to Kenan, sted Keenan, and ADD NewsHour to title of MacNeil-Lehrer.
Picks up 6th graf pvs `It's a ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columnist Jack Anderson, who pulled out a gun
during an interview with Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole to
illustrate what he termed lax security, was criticized Monday by
fellow journalists who called his ploy ``a cheap shot.''
   Capitol police say they may file criminal charges against
Anderson in connection with the May 24 incident, and the committee
that hands out media credentials is considering revoking Anderson's
privileges.
   ``I think it was a cheap shot,'' Bob Franken of Cable News
Network said about the incident, calling it a ``trivialization'' of
journalism.
   ``The police here do a good job. They have an impossible task,''
Franken said. ``We have some horrendous issues to try to comprehend
here. This was Jack Anderson making a quick buck.''
   Kenan Block, a producer for MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour, said in an
interview that he did a similar story on airport security when he
was reporting for a local station.
   ``It's a cheap shot,'' he said. ``It's kind of a cliche. I
thought Anderson would do a more sophisticated story.''
   Al Freeman of Mutual Broadcasting called Anderson's technique ``a
stunt.''
   Freeman said someone such as Anderson, a nationally syndicated
columnist, is known and might have an easier time getting into the
Capitol without as thorough a check as lesser-known individuals.
   Anderson said in a telephone interview Monday that he did not
carry the gun into the building himself because he realized there
was a possibility he would be recongized and therefore not checked
as carefully as a person not known to security officers.
   He said the accomplice who carried the weapon was with the
Anderson party but ``went in far enough ahead of me I don't think
that person would have been associated with me.'' The accomplice was
not named.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, and Dole,
R-Kan., have threatened to require more time-consuming searches of
the media if the credentials committee doesn't ``deter any future
repetition of this act.''
   Jeffrey Birnbaum, chairman of the five-member panel that oversees
assigning credentials to about 2,000 reporters, said the group would
hold a hearing. No date has been set.
   ``We could do nothing, reprimand him or take away his
credentials,'' Birnbaum said. ``For us, the issue is narrow: Did he
abuse his position as a reporter?''
   Capitol Police Officer Dan Nichols said Anderson could be charged
with possession of a gun inside the Capitol, a felony punishable by
a $5,000 fine, five years in jail or both. Lesser charges also are
being considered, he said.
   ``I think it's sad that once again they would go after the
journalist who exposes a problem instead of correcting the
problem,'' Anderson said in the telephone interview.
   ``I have been told by journalists that their (the authorities')
way of correcting the problem is to double and triple and quadruple
security on journalists. It seems they are punishing all because one
exposed a faulty security system.''
   Anderson addd that the ``publicity probably does me good, but I
would rather avoid it.''
   The incident occurred during taping for his syndicated television
show on which the topic was terrorism.
   Anderson was interviewing Dole in a private office when he pulled
the Austrian-made, part plastic gun out of his pocket, said Dole
spokesman Walt Riker.
   ``Dole was surprised as anyone would be,'' Riker said. ``But the
senator had just made the point that the building is not fail-safe
and that's why we have to be ever vigilant.''
   Nichols said officers have not changed procedures since the
incident.
   ``All visitors have their packages checked and pass through metal
detectors,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
