<FIRST>u p AM-GOPPrimary Bjt   06-12 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GOP Primary, Bjt,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Republicans Vie Tuesday To Oppose Wilder for Virginia Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Republicans scrambled from the
mountains to the coast on the eve of a primary Tuesday to decide who
will oppose Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder in his bid to become the
nation's first elected black governor.
   Former U.S. Sen. Paul S. Trible Jr., former Attorney General J.
Marshall Coleman and U.S. Rep. Stanford E. Parris looked for a
last-minute edge in the tight race in Virginia's first GOP
gubernatorial primary in 40 years.
   Meanwhile, Wilder and his running mates opened a get-acquainted
tour of the state just two days after winning the Democratic
nomination.
   Trible, 42, had led all polls until last week. But two surveys
published as Coleman turned 47 on Thursday put him about even with
Trible. Parris, 59, was was close enough to the leaders to fall
within the polls' sampling errors.
   A poll released last week showed each of the three GOP contenders
leading Wilder, but only slightly. Wilder is nurturing his image as
an underdog, a tactic which helped parlay him into the lieutenant
governorship in 1985.
   The nation has not had a black governor since Reconstruction and
has never actually elected one. Lt. Gov. Pinckney Pinchback of
Louisiana became acting governor in 1872-73 after Gov. Henry
Warmouth was removed from office.
   Because voter rolls do not designate party, all of the state's
2.6 million registered voters are eligible to cast ballots in
Tuesday's primary, but few are predicting a big turnout of
Republicans, much less Democrats.
   Susan Fitz-Hugh, secretary of the Board of Elections, predicted
that turnout could be as low as 250,000, or less than 10 percent.
   But Parris and a top Trible aide, Judy Peachee, said they
expected as many as 350,000 to vote.
   Wilder has played down the racial aspect of the contest, as have
the GOP contenders. Political experts have said Wilder has at least
an even chance of winning in Virginia, which is 82 percent white.
   Wilder was elected in 1985 on the same ticket as Gov. Gerald L.
Baliles, who is barred by the state constitution from seeking a
second consecutive term.
   The three GOP candidates have raised almost $10 million for the
primary, which Republican leaders chose instead of a convention in a
bid to recapture the Executive Mansion that has been the home of
Democrats since 1982.
   Trible, speaking Monday during the busy lunch hour in Richmond's
downtown financial district, continued to press an electability
message. He said a Coleman or Parris win in the primary would give
the Nov. 7 election to Wilder.
   Parris, meantime, said the forecast for rain probably would work
to his advantage, since bad weather tends to hurt turnout in rural
areas where he is weakest. ``We think we're peaking at exactly the
right time,'' he said.
   Coleman was endorsed Monday by the Washington Times, which cited
his ``more aggressive and specific advocacy of reforms in welfare,
education and criminal justice.''
   Wilder, 58, was nominated for governor Saturday at a harmonious
state Democratic convention.
   Asked which Republican he would prefer to face, Wilder said he
would take on any of them and that he would not encourage his
supporters to vote in the GOP primary.
   Wilder, a grandson of slaves who grew up in segregated Richmond
and attended Howard University Law School in Washington on a state
stipend because he could not go to Virginia's all-white law schools,
has portrayed himself as a social moderate and fiscal conservative.
   The Wilder nomination ``is giving Virginians an opportunity to
put the era of racial discrimination behind them,'' said Tom Morris,
a University of Richmond political scientist.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
