<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     06-12 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Identity Cards Issued, Army Weighs New Measures Against Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Egypt, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EREZ CHECKPOINT, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Arabs
lined up Monday to collect army-issued computerized identity cards
despite a call by underground Palestinian leaders to fight their
distribution.
   Some Palestinians claimed soldiers coerced them to accept the new
cards and others said they would be denied jobs without them.
   Residents of the Israeli-occupied Gaza Strip are barred from
entering Israel without the cards that are designed to increase
control of their movements. Government officials said the system may
be expanded to also cover the occupied West Bank.
   The daily Haaretz newspaper reported Monday that the army plans
to extend from six months to one year the maximum period imprisoned
Arab can be held without trial. The change is part of a legal
crackdown on the Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the
occupied lands, the paper said.
   An army spokesman refused to comment on the report.
   There are now 1,508 Arabs being held under Israel's
``administrative detention'' procedures, according to official
reports. The United States and international human rights groups
condemn the practice as a violation of due process of the law.
   Army gunfire wounded six Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip on Monday, including two 14-year-old boys, Arab hospital
officials said.
   At least 516 Palestinians have been killed and more than 10,000
wounded since the uprising began in December 1987. Twenty-two
Israelis also have been slain in the violence.
   At a military base at this crossing into the Gaza Strip,
Palestinians sat in long rows in a building, waiting to get the new
identity cards.
   The red, green and white plastic cards are being issued only to
Gaza men over the age of 16 who have paid all their taxes and do not
have criminal records, the army said.
   Col. Ami Levy, who is directing the distribution, said cards will
be denied to Palestinians who have served more than five months of
administrative detention.
   He estimated that 2,000 Arabs would be denied cards.
   ``It's an honesty card,'' said Levy. ``Everyone who has one is
regarded as cleared by the administration to work and visit in
Israel.''
   In a leaflet distributed Sunday, the clandestine leadership of
the Palestinian uprising accused Israeli authorities of ``renewing
their Nazi and fascist activities'' with the cards and said the
effort would be opposed.
   The army began issuing the cards last week, Levy said. Arabs must
pay 20 shekels ($11) for each card.
   The cards are critical for the estimated 50,000 Gazans who work
in Israel.
   Atef, a Palestinian in his 30s who would give only that name,
said soldiers forced him to come to the base, but he acknowledged he
needed the card to work in Israel.
</TEXT>
