<FIRST>r a AM-CustodyBattle     06-12 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Custody Battle,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polygamy Shouldn't Bar Utah Couple From Adoption, High Court Told</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First name Sharane in 2nd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple's practice of polygamy is no
reason to bar them from adopting six motherless children, a lawyer
told Utah's Supreme Court on Monday.
   The judge should have considered Vaughn and Sharane Fischer's
other qualifications as parents and the interests of the children,
who have lived with them two years, said attorney David Nuffer,
representing the Fischers.
   But Timothy Anderson, representing relatives who oppose the
adoption, called plural marriage ``anathema to society.''
   Oral arguments before the state's highest court took place in a
courtroom overflowing with friends and relatives.
   The Fischers sought to adopt the children, ages 5 to 19, after
the 1987 cancer death of their mother, Brenda Thornton, who married
Fischer, 54, three months before her death and assigned custody to
his family with consent from the children's biological father.
   Circuit Judge Dean E. Conder ruled in December that while the
Department of Social Services found the couple capable, their
polygamist lifestyle disqualified them. The judge stayed his
decision pending an appeal.
   The children remain in the polygamist town of Hildale near the
Arizona border with the Fischers, who share their home with plural
wife Katarina Stubbs and 15 children.
   ``The question of what is best for the children is central to the
issue,'' Nuffer said. Further, he said, Ms. Thornton's marriage to
Fischer was based on ``her specific desire and purpose ... to bring
her children into the family.''
   Anderson countered that polygamy was ended for good reason in the
19th century because it ran counter to society's commitment to
monogamy.
   The Mormon Church dropped polygamy as a tenet of its faith in
1890 in exchange for statehood and it is proscribed in the Utah
Constitution.
   However, an estimated 20,000 to 30,000 Mormons still practice
plural marriage at risk of excommuncation.
   The law against polygamy has not been actively enforced for more
than three decades.
   Anderson said said the case hinges not on the Fischers' right to
their fundamentalist Mormon beliefs but on the state's
responsibility to protect children from being taught illegal
practices.
   Ms. Thornton's stepsister, Pat Johanson of Washington, claims
that transfer of the children to the Fischers was signed under
pressure from the fundamentalists and that Ms. Thornton really
wanted her to take the children.
   Ms. Johanson said her stepsister confided her true wishes in the
weeks before her death but feared being excommunicated.
   Ms. Johanson's sister, Janet Johanson of Salem, Ore., is seeking
to adopt the children.
</TEXT>
