<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-12 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms Rumble From Texas To Ohio Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms were scattered from Texas and the southern Plains
into the Ohio Valley on Monday, unleashing at least one tornado in
Kentucky, and thunderstorms also developed in Minnesota, Colorado
and Florida.
   An upper air disturbance moving across warm, humid, very unstable
air triggered strong thunderstorms across the lower Mississippi
Valley. Wind gusted to 60 mph at Charleston, Ark., and wind downed
trees and power lines at Lamar, Ark.
   Strong thunderstorms also developed over the lower Ohio Valley. A
tornado touched down near Simpsonville, Ky., but there were no
reports of injury or damage, state police said. High wind elsewhere
in Kentucky toppled trees at Calhoun and near Reynolds Station, the
National Weather Service said.
   Thunderstorms across southern Oklahoma dropped hail near Taylor.
Almost the entire state was under a flash flood watch Monday night
because the ground was already saturated after more than a week of
rain.
   ``Most of the rivers in the state are running at close to bank
full,'' said Ken Huckabee, a weather service forecaster in Norman.
   Since June 1, Oklahoma City has had 8.85 inches of rain. Similar
or higher figures have been reported around the state, which
normally has less than half that amount for the entire month of June.
   Central and eastern Texas had thunderstorms with locally heavy
rain.
   Heavier rain during the six hours up to 1 p.m. CDT included 1.42
inches at Fort Worth, Texas; 1.18 at West Plains, Mo., and 1.00 at
Dallas.
   Farther north, thunderstorms developed over Minnesota along a
cold front that stretched from the upper Mississippi Valley to
southern Colorado, which also had scattered thunderstorms.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms were scattered across the Florida
Peninsula and showers were scattered from the upper Great Lakes to
the upper Ohio Valley.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 48
degrees at Grand Marais, Minn., to 99 at Palm Springs, Calif.
Monday's low in the 48 contiguous states was 33 degrees at West
Yellowstone, Mont., and Yellowstone National Park, Wyo.
   For Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from much of
the northern and middle Atlantic Coast across the Appalachians, the
Great Lakes, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and the lower
Mississippi Valley into the southern Plains. Scattered showers were
expected across the upper Mississippi Valley and the Dakotas.
Scattered thunderstorms were forecast across Florida, and central
and eastern Colorado.
   Highs in the upper 50s or 60s were predicted from much of the
northern and central Plains across the upper Mississippi Valley and
the upper Great Lakes to much of New England; in the 60s and 70s
along the Pacific Coast; in the 90s from the southern Atlantic Coast
and Florida across the Gulf Coast region, the southern half of
Texas, inland California and much of Nevada; above 100 over the
desert Southwest, inland valleys of southern California and sections
of south-central and southwestern Texas; and in the 70s and 80s over
the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
