<FIRST>r w AM-CleanAirReax 1stLd-Writethru   06-12 0955</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0681,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praised for Offering Plan; Some See Tough Bargaining Ahead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 3-6 bgng: ``Canadian Prime,'' with Canadian reaction
^With AM-Clean Air, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush won strong praise Monday for his
legislative proposal to reduce air pollution but lawmakers and
special-interest groups said tough bargaining remains over cutting
motor vehicle emissions and controlling airborne toxic chemicals.
   General support from industry, environmental organizations and
lawmakers on all sides of the issue centered on Bush's willingness
to put a strong proposal on the table after eight years of inaction
by the Reagan administration.
   But when pressed for their detailed views, these organizations
and lawmakers differed over crucial technical points that eventually
will decide whether a decade-long congressional logjam over clean
air can be broken.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said in an Ottawa
statement that he Bush proposal was the most positive move by the
United States in a decade of Canadian complaints and requests for
action.
   Canada which blames half its acid rain on pullution flowing in
from the United States.
   Environment Minister Lucien Bouchard said at a news conference,
``I am advised the controls ... would satisfy Canada's request for a
50 percent reduction in acid rain reaching this country.'' He said
Canada still hopes for a treaty to make the new controls harder to
weaken.
   The most negative comments came from coal interests.
   Richard L. Lawson, president of the National Coal Association,
accused Bush of trying ``to accomplish too much, too soon,'' called
some provisions ``unnecessary, unduly harsh and economically
onerous'' and warned that ``electric rate payers will likely pay
more for electricity.''
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., who represents a coal-producing
state, said Bush's plan to cut acid rain unfairly penalizes the
high-sulfur coal areas, abandons the promise of clean-coal
technology and endangers the nation's energy future.
   ``The proposal, by leading to massive switching from high-sulfur
to low-sulfur coal, will serve as a disincentive to the use of
clean-coal technologies,'' Byrd said.
   But more typical were comments by an auto industry spokesman, Tim
MacCarthy, who said Bush ``has really shown leadership,'' and Rep.
Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
environment subcommittee, who applauded ``the president's commitment
to deal effectively with ... urban air pollution, acid rain, and air
toxics.''
   ``This is a long journey beginning with a single step,'' said
Rep. Edward R. Madigan of Illinois, ranking Republican on Waxman's
subcommittee. Jerry Jasinowski, executive vice president of the
National Association of Manufacturers, pronounced the organization
``pleased that the president recognizes the value of allowing
businesswide flexibility.''
   A crucial message of support came from House Energy and Commerce
Chairman John D. Dingell, D-Mich., known for his protection of the
auto industry's interests on clean air.
   ``The broad outlines appear reasonable, effective and consistent
with the need to promote economic growth and job opportunities,'' he
said.
   Demonstrating how the harmony breaks down when specifics are
discussed, Waxman said Bush wasn't tough enough on reduction of
motor vehicle emissions, adding: ``Without tough new controls on
cars, trucks and buses, we simply won't get clean air.''
   MacCarthy, director of federal liaison of the Motor Vehicle
Manufacturers Assocation, said ``We don't support tailpipe emissions
standards.''
   However, MacCarthy, in a statement that could increase chances of
eventual approval of clean air legislation, said, ``There are never
100 percent victories in this town (Washington).'' He added ``there
is a very good likelihood there will be some tightening of tailpipe
standards.''
   David Hawkins, of the Natural Resources Defense Council, an
environmental group, said Bush left unclear whether he would require
use of the best possible technology to reduce the largely
unregulated release of airborne toxic chemicals.
   David Gardiner, of the Sierra Club, called the air toxics part of
the bill ``the weakest'' portion. He added that the standard that
would be imposed on industry ``will not make a dent'' in the problem.
   But Gardiner, legislative director of the Sierra Club, said that
overall, Bush ``laid out a set of objectives that are worthy and
will definitely break the logjam. The reason there was no action the
last eight years was the failure of Reagan to put a proposal on the
table.''
   He called Bush's acid rain proposal a strong one but said he's
skeptical about a provision to allow large utilities to trade or
sell credits for sulfur dioxide reductions if they exceed the
minimum reduction requirements.
   ``In theory it should work,'' Gardiner said, but added that in
practice, the trades or sales could result in an imbalance, where
there are major reductions in one region and few in another.
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., chief sponsor of clean air legislation
in the Senate, said, ``The rhetoric is good, but it's a bit vague in
the urban smog provisions.''
   He praised an ``attitude change'' in the White House because Bush
``is committed to a bill, which was not the case'' during Ronald
Reagan's presidency. ``But the actual language is going to tell
where the president is. All interests are much more inclined to
compromise,'' Baucus said.
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, last year's
chief clean air legislative sponsor, called Bush's statement ``a
significant departure from the negative environmental policy of the
Reagan administration, which opposed every clean-air bill considered
by Congress for the past eight years.''
   He said the government ``must be prepared to deal fairly and
humanely'' with the job loss that the proposal is likely to produce.
   Mitchell said he is concerned that the president did not say how
the proposed reductions would be made, adding, ``the history of the
Clean Air Act demonstrates clearly that merely setting forth goals
is not sufficient to achieve them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
