<FIRST>r w AM-Orr-Singapore     06-12 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Orr-Singapore,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nominee Says He Will Urge Attention to Southeast Asia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Robert D. Orr of Indiana said
Monday that if confirmed as U.S. ambassador to Singapore he hopes to
persuade businesses all over the United States to ``investigate the
markets of Southeast Asia'' for export possibilities.
   ``If there is any country in the world where U.S. businesses have
a level playing field on which to compete, it is Singapore,'' Orr
told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. ``The Singaporean
economy is one of the most open and barrier free in the world.''
   Specifically, Orr said he will help U.S. companies in ``more
aggressive export sales efforts'' aimed at replacing Japan as the
largest single source of Singapore's imports.
   ``Most of Singapore's exports from the United States are capital
equipment and electronic components,'' Orr said. ``My goal will be
to broaden the product mix while expanding U.S. exports.''
   Orr said he will deal with complaints about Singapore's
restrictions on press freedom, especially on U.S.-owned
publications, with careful diplomacy.
   ``It is necessary to continue to carry the message,'' he said.
``I would hope it would finally result is somewhat more openness.''
