<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Egypt 1stLd-Writethru a0634 06-12 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Egypt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0634,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt Seeks Expanded Peacemaking Role</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout ADDING Arafat-Mubarak favorable comment on
U.S. position, UPDATING with PLO supporter's peace plan. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt sought an expanded peacemaking role Monday
by offering its services as an ``active postman'' between Israel and
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   In Cairo, President Hosni Mubarak met with PLO chief Yasser
Arafat, who indicated hope remained for Israel's plan to start peace
negotiations with elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``We have not rejected the idea of elections but we have specific
questions on the subject,'' Arafat said. ``Can there be democracy
without freedom? Can there be democracy without self-determination?''
   Mubarak told journalists in Cairo there is a new ``seriousness''
in the U.S. position on the Palestinian issue that could point
toward a settlement.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens rejected the offer by Egypt, with
which Israel signed a peace treaty in 1979, to be middleman for
indirect negotiations. He said Israel does not want to enhance the
status of the PLO, which it still considers a terrorist organization.
   ``There is no room for mediation,'' Arens said after a 90-minute
meeting with Butros Ghali, Mubarak's minister of state for foreign
affairs, the most senior Egyptian official to visit Israel since a
Palestinian uprising began 18 months ago in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   Arens expressed optimism about the prospects for Israel's peace
plan, even though both Palestinians and right-wing Israelis have
criticized it.
   He said Ghali gave the plan a ``sympathetic hearing'' and noted
that 94 of the 100 U.S. senators endorsed it last week.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir proposes elections in which
Palestinians would choose representatives to negotiate with Israel
on an interim autonomy plan to last five years. The final status of
the occupied territories then would be discussed.
   ``The ... plan has some positive and some negative elements, and
these negative elements must be corrected if we wish to obtain the
support or participation by the Palestinians in this plan,'' Ghali
said before returning to Cairo from a two-day visit.
   Palestinians insist on withdrawal of Israeli soldiers from the
occupied lands, or at least from population centers, and on
international supervision of the elections. They also seek
assurances their demands for an independent state would be realized.
   Mansour Shawa, a Gaza Strip businessman, said the Israeli plan
``does not meet the minimum aspirations of the Palestinian people.''
   He praised as ``well-balanced'' a new peace program advanced by
Asad Siftawi, a prominent PLO supporter from Gaza who recently
served a six-month prison term without trial.
   Under Siftawi's plan, Palestinians would take part in elections
without an Israeli withdrawal and would accept a stage-by-stage
solution provided that its ultimate goal of statehood be determined
beforehand.
   Shawa said of the plan: ``These are really minimum requirements
that would be acceptable to the Palestinians.''
   Shawa spoke after a breakfast meeting between Ghali and 30
prominent Palestinians in Herzliya, a Tel Aviv suburb. He quoted
Ghali as saying he was ready to serve as a link between Palestinians
in the occupied territories and the PLO as well as between Israel
and the PLO.
   ``I am ready to be a good and active postman,'' participants
quoted Ghali as saying.
   Several Palestinians boycotted the meeting with Ghali, including
some prominent supporters of the PLO. Some felt the meeting should
have been held in Arab east Jerusalem and others said they were
threatened by PLO militants.
   Saeed Kanaan, a West Bank businessman who did not attend, quoted
a caller representing PLO faction based in Syria as saying: ``Anyone
who meets with him will be killed. ... It is very easy to get to
you.''
   Ghali advised the Palestinians not be affected by hard-line
rhetoric by Israel, noting that hawks like former Prime Minister
Menachem Begin took seemingly unchangeable positions during
negotiations that led to the peace treaty between Egypt and Israel.
   Israel radio quoted Shamir as telling an audience of farmers the
government would halt talks with the Palestinians if their
negotiators insisted on an independent state rather than limited
autonomy for the 1.7 million Palestinians in the occupied
territories.
</TEXT>
