<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 2020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Candidates-Pledge     06-12 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Candidates-Pledge,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayoral Candidates Pledge Clean Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch and the eight men seeking to
unseat him signed a pledge Monday to avoid any appeals to prejudice
or bigotry during their campaigns.
   But the candidates, meeting en masse for the first time, made
clear that the deal did not preclude old-fashioned, sharp-tongued
political rhetoric.
   ``This is not a campaign for president of the high school,'' Koch
reminded the group. ``This is a campaign for mayor, and I assume we
are going to be critical of one another.''
   Koch and some of his opponents already have swapped attacks.
   Republican Rudolph W. Giuliani wished out loud for a broader
truce, one barring all ``groundless and false charges'' among the
candidates.
   No one took him up on it, and Giuliani, a former federal
prosecutor, went on to defend a particularly pointed attack on one
of his opponents, cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder, by one of his
allies, local Liberal Party leader Raymond Harding.
   Harding last week called Lauder ``a man whose family business
would sell Israel out for a few riyals from Saudi Arabia.'' He based
that on a comment by Lauder's mother, Estee Lauder, that she
preferred not to sell in Israel.
   ``Fair comment on an issue that had been raised by someone
else,'' said Giuliani.
   But mostly, the candidates kept their comments good-natured.
   When Richard Ravitch came in late, he took fellow Democrat
Harrison J. Goldin's seat while Goldin spoke at the podium.
   ``That's not the seat I want, anyway,'' Goldin joked.
   Then Republican and Right-to-Life Party candidate Henry Hewes
took a seat vacated by Koch, and the mayor told Hewes: ``That's
probably the only time you'll have it.''
   ``That's a cheap shot,'' protested Hewes. ``I think I'll file a
complaint.''
   The candidates were convened by the Committee on Decent Unbiased
Campaign Tactics _ ``Conduct'' _ which said it would investigate
complaints of appeals to bigotry. If a transgression were confirmed,
the candidate would be asked to repudiate it.
   ``We don't seek to keep passion or pride out of these
campaigns,'' said Conduct's leader, R. Peter Straus. ``We embrace
pride and passion. But we reject _ we will not tolerate _ prejudice
or bigotry in this campaign.''
   Critics accused Koch of racial insensitivity during the
presidential campaign last year, when he said Jews ``have got to be
crazy'' to vote for Jesse Jackson because of Jackson's position on
Israel.
</TEXT>
