<FIRST>u i AM-Quayle     06-12 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,1st Ld-Writethru,a0628,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Warns of Cuba-Nicaragua-Panama Alliance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Quayle in Honduras, meeting with Honduran
president and candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede GUATEMALA CITY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle sought
help Monday from Latin American allies in pressuring Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega out of power in Panama and warned of the possibility
of an anti-democratic alliance among Cuba, Nicaragua and Panama.
   On the first full day of a three-day tour of Central America,
Quayle met with the presidents of Honduras and Guatemala and said he
discussed with them possible future measures against Noriega if an
Organization of American States initiative now under way fails to
remove him from power.
   ``If in fact he doesn't leave, we will have to pursue other
options,'' said Quayle. Without being specific, Quayle said the
options could include ``political and economic concerns Panama has
with other countries.''
   Quayle made those comments to reporters before traveling from
Guatemala to Honduras. He met with Guatemalan President Vinicia
Cerezo in Guatemala City and Honduran President Jose Azcona Hoya in
Tegucigalpa. Later, Quayle met with two candidates in that country's
November presidential election.
   The vice president, at all times protected by a large security
detail, also had lunch with U.S. troops at an Air Force base outside
the Honduran capital.
   The United States already has in place economic and trade
sanctions against Panama. President Bush recently strengthened the
U.S. troop presence there.
   Quayle would not discuss the new OAS initiative, other than to
say the United States supports it.
   But an official traveling with the vice president said in general
terms that the OAS plan would provide for deposing Noriega and for a
national dialogue leading to the installation of a democratically
elected government.
   That official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said
Quayle was interested in the OAS proposal but was insistent that
Noreiga must step down before such a dialogue is begun.
   Quayle, referring to recent reports that Nicaragua was planning
to send arms to Panama to help forces loyal to Noriega in the event
of a U.S. attack, said he was concerned about a possible
anti-democratic axis involving Panama, Cuba and Nicaragua, a
development he said ``would destabilize Central America.''
   Quayle said the leaders with whom he met were united in their
opposition to Noriega's staying in power.
   Cerezo, however, said that while he supports democracy in Panama,
its autonomy must also be respected.
   ``It is important to not confuse bilateral relations,'' between
the United States and Panama, ``with the concerns of the
hemisphere,'' Cerezo told reporters at the national palace.
   U.S. officials traveling with Quayle said Cerezo adopted a
harsher stance toward Noriega in the private meeting with the vice
president.
   Azcona told reporters that his position regarding Noriega
coincided with that of the United States.
   Latin nations have not shown much enthusiasm for interfering in
Panama beyond verbal condemnations of Noriega for invalidating the
results of the May 7 election, which independent observers said was
overwhlemingly won by his opposition.
   At one point while in Guatemala, Quayle stopped his motorcade on
a busy downtown street, drawing crowds of onlookers. He entered an
open-front store and purchased a soccer ball for his children,
tossing it with some bystanders before moving on.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
