<FIRST>u a AM-RockyFlatsCanal 1stLd-Writethru a0672 06-12 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats Canal, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0672,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Approves City's Ditch to Divert Water Near Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughtout to UPDATE with EPA giving go-ahead to dig
ditch, quotes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROOMFIELD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government Monday allowed
Broomfield to resume digging a ditch around its reservoir to divert
a stream allegedly contaminated by hazardous wastes from the Rocky
Flats nuclear weapons plant.
   ``The size of the stream and of the impacted area is not that
significant,'' said Max Dodson, director of water management for the
Environmental Protection Agency's Denver office. He said the EPA
would not require Broomfield to obtain a permit for the project.
   ``I'm elated,'' City Manager George DiCiero said after learning
of EPA's decision. ``We will resume digging tomorrow.''
   The Army Corps of Engineers will issue a letter of confirmation
allowing Broomfield to proceed.
   DiCiero said the city of 27,600 began digging a diversion ditch
and building an earthen dam to divert Walnut Creek following U.S.
Justice Department allegations that Rocky Flats nuclear weapons
plant dumped hazardous chemicals into the creek.
   Walnut Creek flows out of Rocky Flats into Great Western
Reservoir, which supplies half of Broomfield's drinking water. The
creek provides about 5 percent of the town's total water needs.
   The debate over the diversion canal was the latest development
involving federal and state investigations of illegal dumping and
burning at Rocky Flats, located 16 miles northwest of Denver. Last
Tuesday, 75 FBI agents and EPA investigators raided the plant. The
Department of Energy facility, operated by contractor Rockwell
International, makes plutonium detonators for nuclear bombs.
   Initially, the government said Broomfield needed a permit from
the EPA and Army Corps of Engineers to divert Walnut Creek, and work
on the ditch was stopped Monday pending the outcome of discussions.
   City officials met for much of the day with federal officials at
the EPA office in Denver and then toured the ditch and dam site.
After the on-site inspection, Dodson announced his decision.
   ``The flow in the river is an absolute trickle,'' Dodson said,
adding that the affected area was less than one acre. ``I respect
Broomfield's effort to develop a safety margin here.''
   The EPA decision was based on Broomfield's project falling into a
category of water diversion that only requires a letter of
confirmation from the Army Corps of Engineers, Dodson said.
   The diversion project is expected to cost about $50,000.
   DiCiero said Broomfield requested permission to divert the creek
two or three months ago but got no response from the EPA until
digging began Saturday.
   Broomfield officials said they wrote Rocky Flats operators last
week requesting no more water from the plant be discharged into the
creek.
   A spokesman for plant operator Rockwell International said
officials would consider the request.
   Gov. Roy Romer, meanwhile, in Washington, D.C., Monday to meet
with the head of the Department of Energy, said DOE chief Adm. James
D. Watkins pledged to immediately address the need for better
monitoring of hazardous wastes coming from Rocky Flats.
   The government charged in an affidavit made public last week that
Rocky Flats illegally dumped hazardous chemicals into the creek on
Nov. 15-16, 1988, and also that hazardous wastes were illegally
burned at the plant.
   Federal officials said then they didn't believe there was any
health hazard, and the state Health Department Monday said samples
taken over the weekend of drinking water in Broomfield and other
communities were not contaminated by any of 59 organic substances
typically analyzed in checking drinking water.
   However, the state still was testing for 13 other chemicals
specifically cited by federal investigators in their probe of Rocky
Flats. Results were expected later in the week, department assistant
director Tom Looby said.
   ``We are confident that these initial tests indicate that the
likelihood of any of the 13 chemicals being found in these drinking
water supplies is very, very small,'' Looby said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0167 </DOCNO>
