<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0716 06-12 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rakowski Abandons Bid for Parliament Seat</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eds: Leads grafs 1-8, more details on coundil ruling. Pickup 5th
graf pvs: Also Monday a judge...
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Council of State ruled Monday that the
33 top Communist Party and government officials who lost in the June
4 elections even though they ran unopposed cannot be candidates in
runoff elections.
   Only two candidates of the 35 on the ``national list'' received a
majority of votes in the elections and will take their seats in the
460-seat Sejm _ lower house of parliament.
   The other 33, including Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski,
failed to get the required 50 percent of the vote and the Council of
State said they could not be candidates in the runoff elections this
Sunday.
   It said that instead, competitive elections for the 33 vacant
seats will be held with two candidates running for each seat.
   Solidarity and other opposition groups will not be able to enter
candidates for those seats, however.
   The council said 66 new candidates will be selected by the
Communist Party and its allies _ the Peasants and Democratic parties
and several small pro-government Roman Catholic groups.
   After the ruling Rakowski announced he would not seek a seat in
the new parliament, but he did not rule out continuing to lead the
government.
   Others on the ``national list'' who lost when they failed to get
a majority in the June 4 balloting include Interior Minister Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak and six other members of the Communist Party
Politburo.
   Also Monday a judge registered a journalists' union banned in
1982, continuing the process of restoring legal status to
independent groups affiliated with the Solidarity union movement.
   ``We don't treat this day as a victory, merely a return to
normality,'' said Stefan Bratkowski, president of the Association of
Polish Journalists.
   The association had been replaced by a union of journalists that
was approved by the government after the 1981 martial law crackdown.
During the martial-law period Solidarity was outlawed and the
government purged 500 to 1,000 journalists from offical publications
for their political views.
   Solidarity was legalized again following an agreement with the
government in April that also prepared the way for the elections.
   Rakowski announced he would not run for the Sejm in a statement
to the state's PAP news agency. He said he wanted to ensure ``the
will of the electorate would not be offended.''
   But he left open the possibility of continuing as prime minister,
a post he assumed in September. Polish law does not require the
prime minister to be a member of parliament.
   ``I am not withdrawing from public life,'' Rakowski said.
   ``Just the opposite, with all my might I will serve my nation in
any posts my party and constitutional authorities of the state
entrust to me and which I consider possible to accept.''
   The June 4 elections were the freest in Poland in more than four
decades and Solidarity-supported candidates won 160 of the 161 seats
open to the opposition in the 460-seat Sejm. Opposition candidates
could run for all 100 seat in the new Senate and they won 92.
   In addition to the 33 ``national list'' vacancies, Sunday's
runoff elections are to decide 262 contested Sejm seats and eight
Senate seats for which no candidate got 50 percent of votes.
   The decision not to allow any of the defeated ``National List''
candidates to run again appeared aimed at heading off voters
claiming their June 4 decision was thwarted.
   After the elections the Sejm and Senate elect a president _
presumably Communist Party leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski by virtue
of the party's built-in majority in the Sejm.
   The new president names a prime minister to form a new government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
