<FIRST>r w AM-VenezuelaLoan     06-12 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela Loan,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Loan of $4.6 Billion Planned for Venezuela</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Monetary Fund may approve
this month a $4.6 billion loan to Venezuela, officials said Monday,
a move which would complete a process begun in February after riots
in Venezuela linked to government austerity measures.
   The riots, in which the government said 246 people were killed,
were triggered by increases in bus fares and gasoline prices as part
of a program to satisfy the IMF and other creditors.
   The day after the violence broke out in Caracas, Veneuzuelan
officials reached a tentative accord with the fund.
   The officials, who declined to be quoted by name, said Monday IMF
staff has completed work on the loan. It now has to be presented to
the fund's Board of Executive Directors, who represent the 151
member governments. The United States has about 19 percent of the
voting power.
   Part of the new loan could go to reduce Venezuela's existing debt
of more than $35 billion. Private bankers, to whom almost all the
money is owed, would be urged to reduce old debt in return for IMF
assurances that interest would be promptly paid on the remaining
debt.
</TEXT>
