<HEAD>Nominees For Ambassador Posts in New Zealand, Australia Testify</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nominee to be U.S. ambassador
to New Zealand expressed hope Monday that New Zealand would drop a
policy that bans warships carrying nuclear weapons from its
territorial waters.
   The nominee, Della M. Newman, a Seattle, Wash., real estate
broker who served as Washington state chairman of Bush's
presidential campaign, said opinion polls show most New Zealnders
oppose the breakup of the Anzus mutual defense treaty between
Australia, New Zealand and the United States.
   ``We can hope that as time goes by the preponderance of the
opinion'' will bring New Zealand's government to drop the ban, Ms.
Newman said.
   ``The task of improving relations between the United States and
New Zealand on security issues will not be easy,'' she said. ``It
will require a generous measure of commitment, patience and
sensitivity.''
   Also appearing before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee om
Monday was Mel Sembler, nominated by Bush to be U.S. ambassador to
Australia, who said he looks forward to enhancing the close ties
between the two nations.
   Sembler is a Florida businessman and founder of Straight, an
adolescent drug rehabilitation program. If confirmed, he will also
be ambassador to the tiny island nation of Nauru.
