<FIRST>r a AM-SouthernBaptists 1stLd-Writethru a0677 06-12 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southern Baptists, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0677,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moderates Admit Conservative Southern Baptists Winning Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead; SUBS 8th graf, `The president...,' with 7 grafs
to UPDATE with convention discarding plans for a conservative lobbying
group, background on Moral Majority, Bill Moyers canceling appearance.
Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Conservatives, who...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle for control of the nation's largest
Protestant denomination enters its 11th year Tuesday, with moderates
making an ``11th hour'' bid for the presidency of the Southern
Baptist Convention.
   ``I think the Southern Baptist Convention is in serious
condition, serious trouble,'' said Daniel Vestal, the moderate
candidate for the convention presidency. ``A lot of people are at
the point of dropping out.''
   Paul Pressler, a Houston judge who has helped rally conservatives
to 10 straight presidential victories in the convention since 1979,
said a win by moderates would result in ``confusion and turmoil''
for a few more years.
   ``The course correction has been made,'' Pressler said.
   Convention officials expect 15,000 messengers, or delegates, for
the three-day meeting that opens Tuesday morning.
   The focus of the convention is the presidential election Tuesday
afternoon, with the 44-year-old Vestal trying to unseat Jerry Vines,
51, Moyers withdrew a request to
appear before the Executive Committee to discuss its criticism of
his ``God and Politics'' documentary. The committee in February said
the documentary was biased in support of Southern Baptist moderates.
   Referring to Pressler, Moyers said in a letter to the committee,
``There is no way to get a fair hearing from an executive committee
that has become a rubber stamp for a secular politician who has
infected this Christian fellowship with the partisan tactics of
malice, manipulation and untruth.''
   Conservatives, who take the Bible as literal truth, accuse
moderates of being open to interpretations that challenge the
foundations of Southern Baptist faith.
   ``Beyond question, the central issue is theological,'' Vines
said. ``I believe that the Bible does not merely contain the word of
God, but that the Bible is the word of God.''
   If one questions part of the truth of the Bible, he said,
everything is open to question, including accounts of the
resurrection of Christ.
   But moderates charge conservatives with violating another central
belief of Southern Baptists _ that believers can interpret the Bible
for themselves.
   ``I think the issue is freedom: Are we going to be free or are we
going to be a controlled denomination?'' said Vestal, pastor of
Dunwoody Baptist Church in suburban Atlanta. ``Are we going to be
creedal or non-creedal?''
   Stan Hastey, executive director of the Southern Baptist Alliance
in Washington, said the dispute revisits the battleground of
American Protestantism in the early 20th century.
   ``The key questions are questions like `Were Adam and Eve real
people? Was the world created in six, 24-hour periods?''' he said.
``The moderates respond those questions are theologically
irrelevant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0178 </DOCNO>
