<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 2220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-JenretteConviction     06-12 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jenrette Conviction,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former South Carolina Congressman Convicted of Shoplifting Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE GINSBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. John Jenrette, D-S.C., on
probation from bribery and conspiracy convictions in a noted
congressional scandal of the 1970s, Monday was found guilty for the
second time of shoplifting shoes and clothes from a suburban
Washington department store.
   After deliberating for 35 minutes, the Fairfax County Circuit
Court jury found Jenrette guilty of petty larceny through switching
price tags at Marshall's discount department store in Tyson's Corner
on Dec. 7.
   The jury recommended a $1,000 fine and six months in jail for
each of the two misdemeanor charges. But the fact that Jenrette was
on probation could greatly lengthen that term.
   ``This could trigger three years extra in prison,'' said defense
attorney Steve Merril. ``It's a tremendous setback to his life.''
   Sentencing was set for Aug. 18.
   Upon hearing the verdict, Jenrette sat motionless and stared
straight ahead. He was whisked out a back door and did not speak
with reporters.
   Jenrette had been found guilty on both charges by Fairfax Circuit
County Circuit Judge Donald B. McDonough on Feb. 23. He appealed
that verdict in an attempt to bring his case before a jury where he
felt he could succeed in creating reasonable doubt.
   But the jury believed Marshall's store guards, who said they saw
Jenrette leave the store wearing stolen shoes and carrying a tie
that he had pocketed off a rack.
   Guard Heather McKeever said she also saw Jenrette remove the
price tags from a pair of pants and a shirt and replace them with
the tags from lower-priced merchandise.
   Ms. McKeever also said she saw Jenrette try on a pair of
Marshall's shoes and place his own in the bottom row of the store's
shoe rack.
   When Jenrette walked out of the store, he was apprehended by Ms.
McKeever and guard John Brown, who supported her testimony in court.
   Jenrette, testifying in his own behalf, said he ``flat forgot''
that he was wearing the new shoes.
   ``I had them on for 35-40 minutes and embarrasingly forgot I had
them on,'' he said. He denied switching price tags and claimed the
tie in his pocket was his own that he had brought into the store to
compare with a tie he was considering purchasing.
   Part of Merril's defense was the fact that Jenrette left behind a
$125 pair of shoes, and that the camera used by the security guards
didn't give an accurate depiction of events.
   Assistant Commonthwealth's Attorney William Pickett, in his
closing argument, called Jenrette's story ``totally fiction'' and
said the evidence against the former lawmaker was ``overwhelming.''
   Jenrette, who served in Congress from 1975 to 1980, was sentenced
to two years in prison and five years probation after being
convicted in the ABSCAM sting operation in which FBI agents posing
as Arab sheiks and businessmen offered bribes to lawmakers.
   Jenrette served 13 months in prison and is currently on probation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0180 </DOCNO>
