<FIRST>r a AM-NavigationSatellite     06-12 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navigation Satellite,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motor Firing Shifts Navigation Satellite's Orbit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Johnn' in penultimate graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The radio-commanded firing of an
onboard motor Monday shifted a new navigation satellite into a
circular orbit about 11,000 miles above the Earth, the Air Force
reported.
   The Navstar satellite was launched here Saturday into a
preliminary ellitical orbit ranging from about 100 to 11,000 miles
high.
   The new satellite is the second advanced model Navstar to be
launched. It is designed to tell U.S. and allied military forces
where they are within 50 feet anywhere in the world _ on land, sea
or in the air, and in any weather.
   Ground stations tracked the satellite for nearly two days to
accurately determine its orbital path, then sent a radio signal at
3:12 p.m. Monday to start the motor. On the new path, the
satellite's high and low points are both at about 11,000 miles.
   ``The burn was succesful and everything looks good,'' said Lt.
Johnn Kennedy, a spokesman for the Air Force Space Division in Los
Angeles.
   Officials said ground controllers would check out the payload's
systems for between 35 and 40 days before placing it on operational
patrol, joining eight other Navstar satellites already in orbit.
</TEXT>
