<DOCNO> AP890612-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 2236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Bishop     06-12 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bishop,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Designer of Famed Mosquito Aircraft is Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Bishop, who designed Britain's ``Wooden
Wonder'' Mosquito aircraft in World War II and the Comet jetliner
shortly after the war, has died, family death notices said Tuesday.
He was 86.
   After the war, Bishop designed other military and civil aircraft
and the world's first commercial jet airliner, the Comet, which fell
victim to the hitherto unknown phenomenon of metal fatigue.
   Bishop joined the De Havilland company when he was 18 and worked
his way through the metal, fitting and engine workshops before
entering the drawing office in 1923.
   The Air Ministry rejected his idea for a fast bomber built of
wood a year before the war began. But Bishop and the company built
it anyway and the DH-98 Mosquito became one of the most versatile
military planes ever built for day and night fighting, bombing and
photographic reconnaissance.
   It was made of two layers of plywood sandwiching a layer of balsa
wood. Twin Rolls-Royce Merlin engines powered the Mosquito to 380
mph, faster than any enemy fighter so it did not have to carry
defensive guns or armor. Later versions sped at 425 mph and doubled
the bomb load to 4,000 pounds.
   Mosquito night fighters destroyed 600 German planes over Germany,
a like number of German V-1 flying bombs over England, and marked
targets for night bombing of Germany by laying flares.
   The most spectacular Mosquito raids were the September 1942
attack that destroyed the headquarters of the Gestapo secret police
in Oslo, Norway, and the February 1944 attack on Amiens jail in
France which helped 258 French Resistance fighters escape.
   An obituary in London's Daily Telegraph said Bishop got the idea
for the Mosquito when he saw a stuffed pike in a glass case and
penciled a similar, streamlined outline on the back of an envelope.
   The fish had been caught before World War I by Sir Winston
Churchill, Britain's leader in World War II.
   Bishop lived at Harpenden, 25 miles northwest of London and is
survived by his wife, Nora, and two sons.
   Family notices said he died Sunday, but gave no cause or place of
death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0182 </DOCNO>
