<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 2241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Butter-Soviet     06-12 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Butter-Soviet,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets May Buy 75,000 Metric Tons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has been authorized to buy up
to 75,000 metric tons of surplus U.S. butter at prices to be
negotiated, Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter announced Monday.
   ``The United States has a large supply of surplus butter and we
can sell competitively on the world market,'' Yeutter said.
   An estimated 135,000 to 140,000 tons of butter will be in the
surplus inventory held by the Agriculture Department's Commodity
Credit Corp. by Sept. 30, up from 73,165 tons on Sept. 30, 1988, he
said.
   The 1985 farm law mandated sales of 150,000 tons of dairy
products annually through Sept. 30, 1990.
   Butter, cheese and non-fat dry milk are bought by the CCC to
support the price of milk paid to dairy farmers. Unless the products
are sold periodically, huge inventories can build up.
   Although no price level was mentioned in the announcement, recent
CCC report indicate that taxpayers have about $1.47 per pound
invested in the surplus butter, or around $3,241 per metric ton,
allowing for 2,205 pounds per ton.
   The administration has been under pressure from some members of
Congress and trade interests to sell soybean oil as well as butter
to the Soviets. Advocates want the vegetable oil to be included
under the Export Enhancement Program for sale to Moscow at
subsidized prices.
   However, no mention was made of possible soybean sales to the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
