<FIRST>a i PM-Euro-Parliament Adv15   06-12 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Euro-Parliament, Adv 15,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs June 15 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Europeans Electing Strongest Parliament Yet, but Interest Is Low</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note voting dates June 15 and June 18 in 3rd graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens in the 12 nations of the
European Economic Community are electing a new European Parliament
and for the first time the candidates they choose will have real
power.
   In the past few years, the Strasbourg-based parliament has been
rapidly shedding the image of an unwieldy, overfunded talking shop.
Now it will be an institution with more power and responsibility
than at any time in its 37-year history.
   The voting is today (June 15) in five countries and on Sunday,
June 18, in the remaining seven. Results are expected June 19.
   Yet old impressions die hard. Polls and other predictions in
several countries, including West Germany and France, indicate
little public interest in the ``European elections'' that seat a new
parliament every five years.
   In some countries, including Italy, France and Spain, what
interest the elections have generated is related more to the
ramifications for domestic politics of which candidates win.
   The danger for the parliament is that a low turnout among the 120
million eligible voters could undermine the legitimacy of the
institution just as it is gaining more power. Parliament members
have long asserted that they speak most directly for the 360 million
citizens of the European Economic Community, and therefore should be
a far more central element in community decision-making.
   Among the results likely are an increase in the number of Greens,
the environment-based political movements, in the parliament and a
falloff in members from extreme right-wing parties. These are likely
to have little overall effect, however, on the parliament, which has
traditionally been somewhat left of center and is already
sympathetic to environmental concerns.
   The elections will be the third time that voters have directly
elected the parliament's 518 members. Until the first elections in
June 1979, the deputies were appointed by the governments of the
member states.
   The number of members each nation can send to the parliament
depends on its population. Britain, France, Germany and Italy each
have 81 seats. Luxembourg has just 6. Spain has 60, the Netherlands
25, Portugal, Belgium and Greece have 24 each, Denmark has 16 and
Ireland, 15.
   Within the parliament's huge, modernistic chamber in Strasbourg,
however, members neither sit nor vote by nationality. Instead, they
work in eight political groupings, each with members from several
nations, that cover the West European ideological spectrum. There is
also a small group of independents.
   Those elected will have many powers to shape the legislation that
will rule the single European market the community plans to initiate
in 1992. The parliament's powers were significantly expanded in 1987.
   The parliament, however, is seeking an even bigger say in EEC
affairs. The most powerful body at present in the EEC is the Council
of Ministers, made up of delegates from each member government.
Advocates of more parliamentary power say the domination of
community decision-making by a handful of people responsible only to
their own governments is a disservice to the EEC's overall citizenry.
   This ``democratic gap'' will be a hot issue in the parliament's
next five-year term, says Gijs De Vries, a parliament member from
the Netherlands who has been particularly active in the body's
operations.
   Other key issues, he says, will include details of how the single
market will work, environmental, consumer and social issues and the
EEC's relationship with the rest of the world.
   The parliament has a crucial role in this last area because trade
cooperation agreements cannot take effect until a majority of the
parliament approves them. The parliament also must sign off on
applications from nations that want to join the community.
   The parliament also issues resolutions on current affairs, a
large number of which reflect concern with human rights abuses and
environmental issues.
   The voting begins June 15 in Britain, Denmark, Ireland, the
Netherlands and Spain. Belgium, France, Greece, Italy, Luxembourg,
Portugal and West Germany follow on Sunday, June 18.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs June 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
