<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv24   06-12 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv24,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Saturday, June 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, June 24, the 175th day of 1989. There are 190
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On June 24, 1948, Communist forces cut off all land and water
routes between West Germany and West Berlin, prompting the United
States to organize a massive airlift of supplies into the city's
western sector to counter the blockade.
   On this date:
   In 1314, the forces of Scotland's King Robert I defeated the
English in the Battle of Bannockburn.
   In 1497, the first recorded discovery of North America took place
as explorer John Cabot, on a voyage for England, sighted land,
probably in present-day Canada.
   In 1509, Henry VIII was crowned king of England.
   In 1647, Margaret Brent, a niece of Lord Baltimore, was ejected
from the Maryland Assembly after demanding a place and vote in that
governing body.
   In 1793, the first republican constitution in France was adopted.
   In 1842, author-journalist Ambrose Bierce was born in Meigs
County, Ohio.
   In 1908, the 22nd and 24th President of the United States, Grover
Cleveland, died in Princeton, N.J., at the age of 71.
   In 1915, more than 800 people died when the excursion steamer
Eastland capsized at Chicago's Clark Street dock.
   In 1940, France signed an armistice with Italy during World War
II.
   In 1947, Kenneth Arnold of Boise, Idaho, reported seeing flying
saucers over Mount Rainier, Wash.
   In 1948, the Republican National Convention, meeting in
Philadelphia, nominated New York Gov. Thomas E. Dewey for president.
   In 1968, ``Resurrection City,'' a shantytown constructed as part
of the Poor People's March on Washington D.C., was closed down by
authorities one day after the permit for the campsite expired.
   In 1975, 113 people were killed when an Eastern Airlines Boeing
727 crashed while attempting to land during a thunderstorm at New
York's John F. Kennedy International Airport.
   In 1982, proponents of the proposed Equal Rights Amendment to the
Constitution officially conceded defeat, but vowed to continue
efforts to fight for equal rights for women.
   In 1983, the space shuttle Challenger _ carrying America's first
woman in space, Sally K. Ride _ coasted to a safe landing at Edwards
Air Force Base in California.
   In 1987, comedian-actor Jackie Gleason, perhaps best known for
his TV series ``The Honeymooners,'' died at his home in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., at age 71.
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter arrived in Tokyo to begin a
12-day Asian tour that included a two-day summit conference in Tokyo.
   Five years ago: Black Muslim leader Louis Farrakhan delivered a
speech in Chicago in which he seemed to refer to Judaism as a
``gutter religion,'' although he later insisted he'd said ``dirty
religion.''
   One year ago: Pope John Paul II, on a visit to Austria, condemned
Nazism during a stopover at the Mauthausen death camp where 110,000
World War II prisoners died.
   Today's birthdays: Actor Al Molinaro is 70. Comedian Jack Carter
is 66. Movie director Claude Chabrol is 59. Actress Michele Lee is
47. Actress Nancy Allen is 39.
   Thought for today: ``There is nothing more frightful than
ignorance in action.'' _ Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, German poet,
dramatist and author (1749-1832).
</TEXT>
