<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Quinlan Adv13   06-12 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Quinlan, Adv 13,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, June 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kathleen Quinlan Is Star of Cable Movie `Trapped'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10 of June 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision to work late in her high-rise
office building put Kathleen Quinlan's character in the wrong place
at the wrong time.
   In the USA Network movie ``Trapped,'' Quinlan plays Marianne, the
building manager, who is caught inside the building, first with a
thief, then with a killer.
   ``What I like about it is that she's not a woman who thinks of
herself as a fighter,'' said Quinlan, ``but when she finds herself
in this situation she has to pull herself together and fight her way
through it.
   Quinlan calls ``Trapped'' a female version of ``Die Hard,'' the
feature film starring Bruce Willis, which was set in a Los Angeles
high-rise as the terrorists' robbery-hostage drama unfolded.
   ``This is about a man whose family has been killed by toxic waste
dumped by a huge corporation,'' she said. ``When he hits the
building, an industrial thief and myself are trapped in the
building. We become the target. So it becomes more one-on-one than
`Die Hard.'
   ``Usually this kind of movie is male-oriented. I loved doing all
the physical stuff. I did all the stunts except going off the
building. I'm a jock so if I get a role where I can act and do
something physical I'll take it. The character of Marianne wasn't
written in depth, so I put myself in her shoes and developed the
character myself. It was all taken very seriously, but it's really a
fun, entertainment piece.''
   The movie, which also stars Bruce Abbott as John, the thief, has
its premiere Wednesday on the USA Network. It was written by Fred
Walton, who directed it on location in Dallas.
   ``We filmed in Dallas because they have some incredible buildings
there,'' Quinlan said. ``We shot it indoors at night. I'm a very
outdoor person, and I'm not a night person. This girl likes to close
her eyes at 10:30. We worked from 6 at night until 6 in the morning.
It has a lot of action so you really had to be on your toes.
   ``I'm a former gymnast and so is Bruce Abbott and it really
helped. We did one stunt with an explosion. Trust me, if I'd known
it was going to explode so big I wouldn't have done it. Our stunt
people were very good, and they had to test me before letting me do
the stunts.''
   Quinlan recently completed a stage role in ``Les Liaisons
Dangereuse'' at the Ahmanson Theatre in Los Angeles.
   She has been in such movies as ``American Graffiti,''
``Lifeguard,'' ``I Never Promised You a Rose Garden,'' ``The
Promise,'' ``The Runner Stumbles,'' ``Sunday Lovers,'' ``Hanky
Panky'' and ``Sunset.'' Among her TV movies are ``She's in the Army
Now,'' ``When She Says No,'' ``Blackout'' and ``Children of the
Night.''
   Quinlan grew up in the San Francisco suburb of Mill Valley, where
she was a gymnast and diver. She made her film debut in ``One Is a
Lonely Number'' doubling for Trish Van Devere in a high dive
sequence.
   ``I was 17 at the time,'' she said. ``They came to our high
school and looked at the diving team. I did `American Graffiti'
because they had a cattle call audition at our school. I went in and
read for a part, never thinking in a million years I'd do any acting.
   ``I had a dream of going to the Olympics. It took me a long time
to get over it. But I got to keep my athletics to myself. In college
I was running back and forth between acting and athletic training.
My coach said I had to make a choice and get my priorities straight.
Finally, I chose acting.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television...
   BACK AT SEA: ``The Love Boat'' is setting sail again, this time
on CBS for a special two-hour movie about a Valentine's Day cruise.
Gavin McLeod, Bernie Kopell and Jill Whelan will return. Special
guest stars include Steve Bond, Tom Bosley, Julia Duffy, Joe
Regalbuto, Ted Shackelford and Shanna Reed. The ship will visit
Barbados, Antiqua, St. Thomas, St. Croix, and the Bahamas. The story
focuses on a group of jewel thieves, headed by Shackelford, who use
``The Love Boat'' as a means of getting their loot out of the
country.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, June 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:JazzFestival Adv16   06-12 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Jazz Festival, Adv 16,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, June 16 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>JVC Jazz Festival Already a Hit With Ticket Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz lovers have to move fast this year if they
want to see their favorite musicians at the JVC Jazz Festival.
Concerts, including Miles Davis and Ella Fitzgerald, are selling out
ahead of time.
   ``I guess interest in jazz must be growing. I don't know if it's
economic. There's interest in just about every concert we have,''
says festival promoter George Wein about the music fest that plays
New York's concert halls and other outdoors venues in the area from
June 23 to July 1.
   ``I don't know what's going on,'' he said in an interview.
``We're two times ahead of where we were last year (in ticket
sales). It looks like we're going to break all records this year. We
did break all records in the Jazz and Heritage Festival in New
Orleans.''
   First to approach sellout status were the earlier of two concerts
by trumpeters Miles Davis and Wynton Marsalis on opening night at
Avery Fisher Hall, and Ella Fitzgerald's concert with guitarist Joe
Pass as guest at Carnegie Hall on June 25.
   Last year's jazz festival tickets were about 10 percent above
sales from the previous year. The 1988 festival was under the
umbrella of the June 11 to July 11 First New York International
Festival of the Arts. Wein said he didn't know how much effect the
larger festival had on jazz-festival attendance.
   Other concerts this year in which tickets are selling early and
briskly include Lionel Hampton's and George Benson's tribute to
Benny Goodman at Carnegie on June 24; the first of two shows by Ray
Charles and the Temptations on June 28 at Avery Fisher; and ``An
Evening of Jazz and the American Song'' at Carnegie, a benefit for
the Duke Ellington Memorial Fund starring Rosemary Clooney, Dave
Brubeck, Marian McPartland, Phil Woods, Ruby Braff and Dave
Frishberg with Bobby Short as host.
   A children's program, ``Coolin' It With Snoopy,'' on the
afternoon of June 24, is also selling well, as is the final night's
``Clark Terry and Friends,'' with some 30 musicians including Oscar
Peterson.
   ``He called people and they came for him,'' Wein said. ``We never
could have afforded to get them all. It's going to be an exciting
evening.'' Both ``Snoopy'' and ``Friends'' will be at Town Hall.
   As for jazz musicians who are just beginning to establish
themselves, the JVC festival has something to offer.
   ``New people have never seemed to catch with the public in New
York. We're very concerned that that type of music have its place on
our festival,'' said Wein.
   This year Lincoln Center is helping Wein present avant-garde jazz
at five ``Knitting Factory Goes Uptown'' concerts in 1,096-seat
Alice Tully Hall. The Knitting Factory is a small club on Houston
Street showcasing the cutting edge in jazz. It has an even smaller
``Knot Room,'' seating 40, in what used to be a basement kitchen,
for even more far-out experimentation.
   Other concerts in this year's festival include Joe Williams
celebrating his 70th birthday, the Benny Carter Quartet with Art
Blakey and the Jazz Messengers, Dizzy Gillespie headlining a ``Bebop
Revisited'' concert, Spyro Gyra and Marcus Roberts, a 20th
anniversary tour performance by Gregg Allman with Dickey Betts, a
Latin Jazz Jam and a night of African jazz, which is a festival
first.
   The Japanese Victor Co., an electronics firm, is sponsoring the
festival for the third year.
   Wein is annually involved with some 30 jazz festivals. The
Newport Jazz Festival in Rhode Island, from which the New York
festival sprouted, began in 1954.
   ``I was playing seven nights a week while I was still going to
Boston University,'' said Wein, who started as a jazz pianist. ``I
knew I was going to do something with music, I didn't know what. I
found out I had a good head for promoting. That's how it all
developed.''
   At first, he didn't play piano at his festivals. ``I'm playing
more now than I ever played before. I'm playing better than I ever
played before. And I find my playing is more accepted now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, June 16</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
