<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Spotlight-Cambodia-Glance Adv18   06-12 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spotlight-Cambodia-Glance, Adv 18,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 18 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Camobodia-at-a-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One of a package of three stories.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Cambodia:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LAND AND PEOPLE _ About the size of Missouri, Cambodia is
bordered by Thailand, Laos and Vietnam. Its population of about 8
million people is made up largely of Cambodians _ or Khmers _ with
Vietnamese, Chinese, Moslem Chams and animist tribal groups forming
minority groups.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GOVERNMENT _ President Heng Samrin and Prime Minister Hun Sen
both defected from the Khmer Rouge, who were the victors in the
Indochina War in 1975, and sided with Vietnam, which invaded the
country in late 1978. A number of non-communists from earlier
governments occupy important positions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ECONOMY _ Although reliable statistics are unavailable, Cambodia
is widely regarded as one of the world's poorest nations. It
subsists largely on Soviet credit and barter trade in agricultural
products. The United Nations reports a very high infant mortality
rate, widespread malnutrition and an average life expectancy of 50
years.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RELIGION _ Buddhism remains a major force in everyday life
despite efforts by the Khmer Rouge to destroy it. The nominally
communist government recently declared Buddhism the state religion
and says 6,000 men have entered the monkhood.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Cambodia's golden age came between the 9th and 13th
centuries when its kings ruled much of peninsular Southeast Asia
from their magnificent capital of Angkor. Neighbors preyed on it in
later centuries and France colonized Cambodia in 1863. King Norodom
Sihanouk led the country to independence in 1953. After an interlude
of peace, Cambodia was plunged into the Indochina war in 1970 with
the U.S.-backed government fighting the Khmer Rouge. The latter won
in 1975 and instituted a reign of terror until Vietnam's invasion.
Since then Vietnamese and Cambodian government forces have been
battling a Sihanouk-led coalition of guerrillas who include the
Khmer Rouge and two non-communist groups.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FOREIGN RELATIONS _ The United Nations recognizes the Sihanouk
coalition as Cambodia's legitimate government, while the Soviet bloc
and India have ties with the pro-Vietnamese regime in Phnom Penh.
China and Thailand provide most of the aid to the coalition and the
United States is considering military assistance to its
non-communist components.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1401EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-MinamataLookback Adv18-2Takes   06-12 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Minamata Lookback, Adv 18-2 Takes,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 18 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Minamata Heals Slowly from Disease of the Same Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINAMATA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This is a town that surrendered its name
to a deadly disease and signaled to the world what unchecked
industrial waste can do to humans, wildlife and their surroundings.
   More than 800 of its citizens paid the price in death and
thousands more have been left painfully crippled.
   In the beginning, people were left puzzled by the scourge wrought
by a chemical company's indiscriminate dumping of mercury into
Minamata Bay.
   It was 1950 and they saw fish floating belly up, birds dropping
into the sea and cats ``dancing'' in wild death convulsions.
   Then in 1956, they themselves began to feel it _ hands and feet
going numb, tunnel vision, a loss of coordination and balance,
chronic pain, convulsions and, in many cases, death.
   Until then, Minamata had been a bustling fishing and factory town
nestled between lush green rice paddies and orange groves in far
southwestern Japan. The clear blue waters of its scenic harbor
yielded abundant seafood.
   Shinobu Sakamoto and her older sister, Mayumi, were among the
first to become victims of what much later would be called Minamata
disease.
   Mayumi died in 1956 at age 5.
   Shinobu, who was born in 1956, was poisoned while in her mother's
womb. She is one of some 60 ``second generation'' victims born with
severe defects.
   Some evenings Shinobu wanders into the Soushisha, a cooperative
set up to help poisoning victims, to visit, watch television and
sometimes to spend the night in the large straw-mat room where
visitors stay.
   She speaks and walks with difficulty but is cheerful.
   The poisoning in Minamata was caused by mercury-laden water
discharged by a factory owned by the chemical company Chisso Corp.
   The pollution devastated the town.
   Its population, which was 50,000 in 1956, has dropped to 36,000
and continues to fall while the number of poison-related deaths has
climbed to 871 by local count.
   All told, about 200,000 people in Minamata and its surrounding
villages on the southwestern island of Kyushu were affected in one
way or another by the poisoning.
   The factory that polluted Minamata's harbor once employed 5,000
people. It now hires only 700; many of its buldings stand empty in
the fenced Chisso compound _ grim monuments to a disaster.
   Minamata's victims and their supporters speak of their tragedy as
a classic case of the high cost of Japan's industrialization.
   ``People just care about money and what it buys,'' said Takanori
Goto, a Tokyo lawyer who has represented some of the victims in
court. ``They're not concerned about the victims created by
industrial prosperity. Minamata is a typical example.''
   Chisso Corp., whose acetaldehyde-processing factory began dumping
an estimated total of 27 tons of mercury into Minamata Bay in 1932,
denied responsibility for the pollution, which continued until 1968.
   Minamata and several other severe outbreaks of industrial
poisoning led the government to establish an Environment Agency in
1970, but the victims have faced lengthy court battles to gain
compensation for their suffering.
   As the victims grow older _ the average age of first generation
victims is 60 _ they continue their battles in court and also
negotiate with Chisso, which is has paid so much in compensation
that it is basically insolvent, Lawyer Goto said.
   Of the 12,296 people who have applied for official designation as
Minamata disease victims, the Health and Welfare Ministry has
granted only 2,210 the official recognition that would provide them
with compensation, welfare assistance and medical care.
   ``We believe at least 10 to 20 percent of the 200,000 people
living in the affected area have symptoms of the poisoning,'' said
Teruo Kawamoto, 57, a Minamata disease victim who has led battles
with Chisso for more than 20 years.
   ``In my case, I suffer from a bad heart, numb hands and feet. I
have liver trouble, headaches and back pain. I don't really expect
to win, but I'm determined to keep on trying to help those people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
