<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-MinamataLookback Adv18   06-12 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Minamata Lookback, Adv 18,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 18 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>MINAMATA: those people.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Kawamoto and other victims have asked the United Nations to
recognize violations of their human rights and to enforce a new
international standard for mercury pollution of 16 parts per million
in Japan, which still adheres to the previous standard of 25 parts
per million.
   Members of the Soushisha cooperative, which has a small
laboratory to test for mercury content, say the deadly metal has
drifted farther out to sea and continues to contaminate fish
officially considered safe.
   With government assistance, the company has been ordered to pay
more than $100 million to victims in compensation, in addition to
medical costs.
   It was also ordered in 1973 to clean up Minamata Bay. Chisso has
dredged much of the harbor. It is still in the process of filling in
the harbor at a cost of over more than $290 million.
   In 1987 a court found the government guilty of failing to prevent
the poisonings by allowing fishing to continue in the vicinity and
ordered it to pay 115 victims a total $4.6 million.
   In 1988, two former senior executives of Chisso were found guilty
of criminal negligence for failing to stop the pollution between
July, 1958, and June, 1968, despite Health and Welfare Ministry
warnings. The men, both elderly, received suspended jail sentences.
   Although people started falling ill in 1956, it wasn't until 1959
that it was determined that a diet heavy in mercury-contaminated
seafood caused the poisoning.
   But fishermen, dependent on the sea for their livelihood,
continued to take fish from the bay.
   The controversy over Chisso's responsibility created a deep
social rift in Minamata between families of victims and non-victims.
   Most, but not all, of the poisoning victims were families of
farmers or fishermen.
   Many of the non-victims were families of employees of Chisso
Corp., who feared for their jobs if they protested the mercury
dumping.
   In 1972, the photographer W. Eugene Smith was beaten by Chisso
employees as he took pictures of protests by victims. He later
published an award-winning photo essay and a book on the Minamata
tragedy.
   ``Twenty years ago, people told us to `get out,' and made fun of
victims,'' said Kawamoto. He added that he received hate mail from
people who called the victims ``cockroaches'' and said they should
``just die.''
   Said lawyer Goto: ``People thought it was a contagious epidemic,
or in typical Japanese fashion they blamed the victims for having
evil hearts or said they were suffering for their ancestors'
wrongdoing.''
   Cases continue to crop up, but many remain hidden because
symptoms can be light and because many people still fear the stigma
of Minamata disease. They don't tell their doctors what's really
wrong, said Ken Takakura, one of the 22 young activists in the
cooperative.
   For many Minamata residents, the question now is how to
revitalize the economy of a town notorious for pollution and ill
health, Takakura added.
   The cooperative has helped local residents shift from fishing to
growing oranges, and it markets the fruit in Tokyo. It also runs a
resource center, a farm and a museum to educate Japanese about the
Minamata tragedy.
   Town officials are promoting Minamata's tourism potential, and
people living here say the deep rift between families of victims and
non-victims has begun to heal.
   ``So many families have suffered that it's hard to be hateful
now,'' Takakura said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
