<FIRST>s i BC-Continent-Malaria Adv18   06-12 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent-Malaria, Adv 18,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday June 18 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Brazil _ Malaria Makes a Comeback</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Continent in Crisis-Health, b0635</HEAD>
<UNK>By JORGE MEDEROS ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uncontrolled settlement in Brazil's
Amazon rain forest has led to an alarming spread of a centuries-old
scourge of the tropics: malaria.
   As hundreds of thousands of prospectors, farmers and adventurers
poured into Brazil's vast northern wilderness in the past decade,
many fell victim to the mosquito-borne disease.
   Last year, the Health Ministry registered 560,000 cases of
malaria in Brazil, up from 500,000 a year before. The number is
expected to rise again this year.
   To control the outbreak, the Health Ministry plans a massive
spraying campaign with DDT, an insecticide banned in many countries.
   ``Only shock treatment can contain the spread of malaria in
Amazonia,'' Dr. Agostinho Cruz Marquez, head of the Health
Ministry's malaria division, said in an interview.
   Malaria is almost exclusively a problem of Amazonia, a 2 million
square-mile wilderness sprawled across northern and western Brazil.
Of the 560,000 cases last year, 97 percent were in the Amazon states
of Amazonas, Para, Rondonia and Acre.
   The worst affected is Rondonia, a state the size of Oregon on
Brazil's western border with Bolivia and notorious for the
destruction of its rain forest. Rondonia had 42 percent of the
country's malaria cases with 192 deaths in the first eight months of
1988.
   The gold-mining town of Ariquemes in Rondonia has become ``the
world capital of malaria,'' Cruz Marquez said.
   The military government that ruled from 1964 to 1985 urged poor
Brazilians to settle in the undeveloped Amazon, using slogans such
as ``The Brave March to the West.'' Since the drive began in the
1970s, the incidence of malaria has risen more than 500 percent.
   Malaria causes fever and chills and a gradual debilitation of the
body. It can be fatal if not treated. In Brazil, 1 to 2 percent of
those who get the disease die from it, Cruz Marquez said.
   Although quinine-based drugs can cure malaria in 24 hours, the
government cannot get the medicine to all who need it throughout the
vast and often inaccessible wilderness, he added.
   The Federation of Miners says an estimated 3,000 mining sites in
Amazonia have drawn untold thousands of prospectors, shopkeepers,
pilots and prostitutes to remote areas. Often the only access is by
helicopter or small planes, which land on dirt strips.
   To attend to this population, the government's Public Health
Campaign Department has just 300 laboratories, Cruz Marquez said,
adding that in some mining sites, a Swedish-made malaria drug called
Larian that enters the country as contraband is sold ``literally for
the price of gold.''
   Now, he said, the government plans to send 70,000 army soldiers
to the region to begin the anti-malaria campaign.
   Cruz Marquez said DDT would be used because of its low cost and
effectiveness against the marlaria-carrying anopheles mosquito.
   The insecticide will not be used indiscriminately, but only to
spray inside the huts and lean-tos used by miners and settlers, he
said.
   The five-year campaign will cost $198 million and will be paid
for in part with loans from the World Bank, Cruz Marquez said.
   ``Malaria is the only thing that scares a prospector,'' he said.
``In a way, it's a giant shield of defense for the Amazon.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
