<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Bowen Adv23-25   06-12 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Bowen, Adv 23-25,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 23-25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Jimmy Bowen's Juke Box Is Full</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Bowen doesn't sing well and can
barely read music.
   But in a career spanning four decades, the 51-year-old Bowen has
been a record producer for pop stars such as Frank Sinatra and Dean
Martin, and such country stars as Hank Williams Jr. and Reba
McEntire.
   In the past 12 years, he has headed four Nashville record
divisions at one time or another. Right now he heads MCA's Nashville
office and is president of the new Universal Records under the MCA
corporate umbrella.
   In the spacious den of his plantation-style home sits a brightly
colored juke box containing 100 carefully selected songs. They're
hits Bowen has been associated with in some fashion.
   ``I don't have time to play it a lot,'' says Bowen, who works an
average 90 hours a week.
   Even when not at work, he is consumed by music. The huge
television screen in his den is often playing MTV. He listens to a
radio or cassette player when he takes a bath. He listens to music
on the radio next to his bed and in his car on the way to his Music
Row office and recording studio.
   Much of his career has been in producing records: directing the
recording sessions, helping choose the songs and mixing the vocals
and instrumentation into the final product.
   In 1987 alone, Bowen was the record producer on 11 No. 1 hit
singles and three No. 1 albums. He has been the producer for
Williams for nine years covering 11 albums.
   ``I think I was born with a real good ear for music in general,''
he said in an interview. ``I like all kinds of music if it's done
well. I've worked in many different kinds of music and enjoyed it.''
   Thirty years ago, he used to play bass guitar, but today he says,
``all I can do is stay in (key of) A.'' As for his singing, Bowen
says, ``I'm about a quarter tone flat.''
   While working in Los Angeles in the mid-1960s, Bowen was the
record producer for Sinatra on hits such as ``Strangers in the
Night'' and ``That's Life.''
   ``I never worked with anyone who phrased better than Frank
Sinatra,'' he recalled. ``His breathing and phrasing were
incredible. He was an incredible professional. He was always
straight to the point, and he was a good human being. I really liked
him and liked working with him.''
   With Martin, Bowen was involved in two dozen hit singles and five
albums that sold at least 1 million copies each. One of the tunes
was ``Everybody Loves Somebody Sometime,'' Martin's signature song.
   ``He was the most unique, laid-back artist I ever worked with,''
he said.
   Bowen's comments on current singers under his direction:
   _ ``Reba McEntire with all those vocal gymnastics reminds me of
Ella Fitzgerald and Dinah Washington, people who did great vocal
gymnastics and still sold the message of the song.''
   _ ``Hank Williams Jr. is the best writer-artist I've ever worked
with. Twenty years from now, he will be known as a great writer like
his father is. Right now, he's such a great artist that people
aren't aware of what a great writer he is.''
   _ ``George Strait is so much like Dean Martin it's a time warp
for me. Everything is just so easy for them. There is no stress and
results just happen naturally. George could have been a big band
singer; if that's the era we were living in, that's what he would
have done.''
   Bowen, who was raised in Dumas, Texas, broke into the music
business by playing bass guitar in a band with rock 'n' roll pioneer
Buddy Knox. He co-wrote Knox's hit record in 1957, ``Party Doll.''
   He got into production work in Los Angeles in the '60s, then
moved to Nashville in the mid-'70s and concentrated his vast musical
talents on country artists.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 23-25</NOTE>
<TEXT>
