<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReview Adv00   06-12 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Review, Adv 00,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Big Daddy'' (PolyGram) _ John Cougar Mellencamp
   
   After taking giant steps forward with his last two albums, John
Cougar Mellencamp consolidates his success with the deceptively
impressive ``Big Daddy.''
   The once-ridiculed Johnny Cougar set aside the snickers with
1985's hard-rocking ``Scarecrow,'' blending party tunes with pointed
commentary about the American Midwest. ``The Lonesome Jubilee'' was
musically adventurous, with Mellencamp adding a fiddle, accordion
and female singers to his basic rock combo.
   ``Big Daddy'' sounds far less ambitious _ a collection of songs
rather than a statement. But in doing so, Mellencamp affirms his own
maturation and the strengths of the band he has assembled.
   Mellencamp and his band sing and play with an understated warmth.
At times, John's talking as much as singing, and he never finds it
necessary to shout. On songs such as ``Mansions in Heaven,'' his
band only hints at the power it can unleash. The players sound
confident in their abilities, not straightjacketed by the songs.
   Lately, he's taken Woody Guthrie and Bob Dylan as role models,
championing the causes of society's underdogs. ``Jackie Brown'' is
an elegant folk ballad about a poor man's life and death in the
countryside. In ``Martha Say,'' he sympathizes with a woman's
struggle for independence. ``Country Gentleman'' is a scorching
indictment of former President Reagan and his ``rich friends.''
   The singer's own aging is another constant theme _ Mellencamp
holds daughters Teddi Jo and Justice in album cover photos.
   About his only clear misstep is the single, ``Pop Singer,'' a
slight song in which Mellencamp insists he never wanted to be a pop
star. Well, why not? His own career contradicts that notion, as well
as the myth that a pop singer can't make real statements on causes
that mean something to him.
   With his work on ``Big Daddy,'' Mellencamp solidifies his
position alongside Bruce Springsteen and Tom Petty as one of the
three best American rock band leaders in the 1980s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
