<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Carmen Adv23-25   06-12 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Carmen, Adv 23-25,0816</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 23-25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Carmen Goes to Nimes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There will be gypsies and flamenco dancers but no
bullfight when Bizet's ``Carmen'' is staged next month in ancient
Nimes.
   The romantic opera starring mezzo-soprano Grace Bumbry is
expected to attract opera lovers, outdoor-theater lovers and lovers,
period, and promises to be the most exciting operatic event of
France's bicentennial year. Tenor Neil Shicoff co-stars as Don Jose,
and baritone Robert Hale will be Escamillo.
   Sets and costumes for the opera to be performed July 3, 5 and 7
are being designed by star couturier Christian Lacroix. Organizers
have not revealed the cost of the lavish production.
   The opera will be directed by Antoine Bourseiller who has been
director of the Opera-Theatre of Nancy since 1982, and an old hand
at ``Carmen'' with past productions in Nancy and Lausanne.
   The international production will also feature the Budapest
orchestra, the Bulgarian national choir, and a cast of over 100,
including 20 picadors on horseback to wind up the last act.
   ``But there will be no bull or corrida,'' Bourseiller said.
   Bullfights are still held twice a year in the well-preserved
Roman arena at Nimes, and a live bullfight following the opera had
been a Nimes tradition since the 19th century. In the years
following World War II, such great matadors as Ordonez, Nimeno, Paco
Camino and El Cordobes capped the musical performances with
bullfights.
   At times the spectaculars also included bands of gypsies,
flamenco dancers, circus numbers and ballet performances. But in
recent years the bullfight was dropped to focus on the opera
masterpiece itself, and as a concession to animal-rights advocates.
   ``As a boy I saw `Carmen' with bullfights,'' said Lacroix, who is
from nearby Arles. ``She was my first love, a very sexy lady.'' The
designer relishes the idea of dressing up Miss Bumbry to look far
more splendid than the down-and-out gypsy cigarette girl so often
seen in productions of the fiery opera.
   ``But it will not look like a fashion show,'' he said. Miss
Bumbry will be clad in colors to suit the drama: carnation pink for
the cabaret scenes; earth colors for the smugglers' scene; black and
silver for the death scene in the final act.
   He is currently working on designs for sets within the arena,
which will seat about 10,000 for the opera.
   ``The site itself is so spectacular you don't need much
scenery,'' Lacroix said. ``We'll be building simple elements to
suggest the mountains, soldiers' garrison, cabaret and so on.''
   Bourseiller said his production will be as true as possible to
the spirit of Bizet, who based his scenario on a tale by Prosper
Merimee. ``Merimee's Carmen was a 16-year-old,'' he said. ``But
obviously we don't want to show her as an adolescent.''
   Miss Bumbry, 52, has received rave reviews for her interpretation
of the sultry Gypsy courtesan in Paris, Rome and Dallas, and in a
screen version directed by Herbert von Karajan.
   ``I have not yet met Miss Bumbry,'' said Bourseiller, ``but
having seen her perform, I admire her and think she is perhaps the
only mezzo suited to both the drama and the difficult outdoor
singing.''
   Carmen has been mounted and acted in hundreds of versions,
including Peter Brook's iconoclastic ``The Tragedy of Carmen,'' a
stark production with a pared-down cast of seven in a dilapidated
setting. This style raised both critical protest and praise when it
came out in Paris and New York in the early 1980s, and last month in
Glasgow.
   ``Brook's version is wonderful in a special setting, such as an
old warehouse,'' said Bourseiller. But his favorite is the steamy
1983 film version by Francesco Rosi starring Julia Migenes-Johnson
and Placido Domingo.
   A part of the Nimes summer festival, ``Carmen'' promises to be
the most spectacular of the operas mounted since 1983, when musical
activities in the arena were resumed after a hiatus of more than 15
years.
   The impressive amphitheater was built by the Romans in the first
century B.C.
   Bourseiller says he can offer has no details yet on what sort of
Carmen character will result from his collaboration with Grace
Bumbry. Rehearsals started June 16.
   ``Our only problem may be the weather. It can get very hot down
there, but we'll begin after sunset, which should help,'' he said.
   ``And then, there's the Mistral,'' he added, referring to the
mighty wind that sometimes comes howling down the Rhone Valley,
bringing blue skies but sometimes hot tempers as well.
   ``The acoustics are excellent in the arena. But the wind creates
a terrible handicap for singers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 23-25</NOTE>
