<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Proclaimers Adv23-25   06-12 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Proclaimers, Adv 23-25,0894</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 23-25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Rock With a Scottish Twist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While growing up in the Scottish village of
Auchtermuchty, Craig and Charlie Reid listened to Frank Sinatra, Ray
Charles and Jim Reeves.
   With their close-cropped hair and horned-rimmed glasses, the Reid
twins could pass for a new-age version of the 1960s English pop duo,
Peter and Gordon. But as The Proclaimers, the brothers erase all
doubts about their Scottish roots.
   ``I think our strength is in being ourselves and not
compromising,'' said Charlie Reid, the guitarist and backing
vocalist for the folk-rock duo. The group has released its second
album, ``Sunshine on Leith.''
   ``In England, which I felt would be the hardest, the album's gone
platinum. We've done it through working and performances. It may
take longer but the process will be worth it. We'll find out a lot
about America and ourselves.''
   The Reids have been best friends all their lives and took pains
in a recent interview to single each other out for priase. As
children, they dreamed of performing together and finally took the
step at 16 when Craig acquired a drum kit and Charlie learned to
play guitar.
   ``It was natural for us that we'd be in the same band,'' said
Charlie, who deferred to his brother as the superior singer. ``I've
got a harsher style; Craig's is better. To some extent the voices
have been shaped that way because I tend to do the backup and the
high harmonies while Craig sings lead.''
   Craig remembered their first time on stage, playing at a local
village hall.
   ``I think one of our songs was by John Lee Hooker, `Boom, Boom.'
We did a Clash song and we may have done soemthing else,'' he said.
``We were very scared. People knew you very well, and they don't
think you can play music. It was very noisy, but it was great.''
   The Reids fronted a punk-rock group before deciding in 1983 to
form an act of their own, naming themselves The Proclaimers and
playing acoustic sets. They headed for London, hoping for a
contract, but were not well received by the English record companies.
   ``They were hinting that if we sang in our own accents, it may be
difficult for people to understand what we were writing about,''
Craig said. ``They said they couldn't sign us because of that.''
   But in 1986, The Housemartins, a popular British band, heard a
tape of The Proclaimers and made them the opening act on their next
tour. The Reids were eventually signed by Chrysalis Records.
   Their first record, ``This Is the Story,'' came out the following
year and featured the single, ``Letter From America,'' a hit in
England. The Reids also celebrated their native accent in ``Throw
the `R' Away.''
   ``A lot of Scots try to get their children's voices to be very
proper, not have them use Scot words,'' Craig said. ``They said you
wouldn't be able to work in England if you do that.''
   The Reids did not use a backing band for their debut album, but
have a wide range of musicians on ``Sunshine on Leith,'' which
features guitars, drums, bass, keyboards, mandolin, fiddle, melodeon
and penny whistle.
   ``We've always liked different sounds,'' Craig said. ``We've
always considered a record where you could do something a bit
different. The music could be anything we wanted. Having a joke,
having a laugh, not taking it too seriously.''
   Gerry Hogan's steel guitar is featured on ``My Old Friend the
Blues,'' a country weeper written by Steve Earle. The Proclaimers
also covered an Earle song on their first album and count themselves
as major country music fans.
   ``I think that any real interest in Scotch and Irish music comes
through our interest in country music,'' Craig said. ``A real thread
of Appalachian and bluegrass music runs through Scotch music. It
awakens your own identity.''
   Craig also praised folk and country lyrics, insisting that they
cover a broader range of subjects.
   ``Basically in rock 'n' roll you write about love and sex and
maybe a couple of political songs, and that is the limit. You don't
write about children, family, places.''
   The remaining 11 songs on ``Sunshine on Leith,'' all written by
the Reids, are a mixture of love, politics and family. ``Sean'' is
about Charlie's baby son. ``What Do You Do'' and ``Cap in Hand''
criticize Scotland's bleak economic condition.
   ``Oh Jean,'' written for a friend of Craig's, closes their live
shows, with the Reids chanting ``I Love Her, I Love Her,'' working
themselves and the audience into a frenzy.
   ``We did a double bill once and we went on and we weren't getting
much of a reaction until we did that one,'' Craig recalled. ``We
tore the place apart.''
   ``You can go as long as you want,'' Charlie said. ``You know the
feeling when it's reached the end. You go into another frame of
mind, not like a trance, but you do try to summon up a primal
energy.''
</TEXT>
