<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--RadiationStudies Adv15   06-12 1059</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Radiation Studies, Adv 15,1085</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, June 15, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gov't Plans First Study Of Hanford Releases' Health Effects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the nation rushed to build atomic
bombs during World War II and the Cold War, few thought the work
might eventually prove more dangerous to the U.S. citizens living
near the weapons factories.
   As the Hanford nuclear reservation produced much of the plutonium
for the nuclear arsenal, radioactive wastes escaped into the air
from smokestacks or were dumped into the adjacent Columbia River.
   ``In the early history of Hanford, there were exposures to the
public. Nobody argues with that,'' said Jim Ruttenber of the U.S.
Centers for Disease Control. Forty-five years after the first
emissions, the government is making its first attempt to learn if
they hurt people in Washington, Oregon and Idaho.
   The Department of Energy's Hanford Environmental Dose
Reconstruction Project is under way to estimate the possible
radiation doses residents might have received, and similar studies
are being done at the Nevada Test Site, the uranium processing plant
at Fernald, Ohio, and other sites. The CDC is about to launch a
study of thyroid disease rates, a $1.5 project that will focus on a
group of 300 people at greatest risk from exposure to radioactive
iodine.
   For the scientists, the issues include dose reconstruction,
environmental transport, source terms, uncertainty analyses and
other jargon.
   But for Hanford's ``downwinders,'' the issue is damaged lives.
   ``Myself and five other members of my family all have
hypothyroidism,'' said Judith Jurji, whose father and two uncles
were Hanford welders from 1949 to 1956. Ms. Jurji, 43, believes the
disease, which slows the body's metabolism and robs a person of
vigor, was caused by Hanford emissions.
   Only the branch of her family that moved to eastern Washington,
around Hanford, has any trace of thyroid disease, Ms. Jurji said.
   The downwinders are prohibited by law from suing the federal
government or its contractors, and even if they could sue it would
be extremely difficult to prove a long-term illness was caused by
radiation exposure 40 years ago, said Jim Thomas of the Hanford
Education Action League, a citizens watchdog group.
   The first step in trying to link health problems to emissions is
dose reconstruction, an elaborate attempt to estimate how much
radiation might have reached people, mostly during the 1940s. The
federal government has estimated over 435,000 curies of radioactive
material was released into the atmosphere over Hanford in 1945-1947.
Three Mile Island released just 15 to 24 curies.
   But dose reconstruction isn't concerned with individual illness.
The $15 million, 5-year DOE study will estimate possible radiation
doses to the public. That will be done by meticulous examination of
such things as milk production, because radioactive iodine-131
settled on grass eaten by cows; weather, because radioactive
material was scattered for hundreds of miles by wind; and outdoor
recreation patterns, because exposure is greatest outdoors.
   The study has been attacked as not credible by some downwinders
because it is being done by Battelle Pacific Northwest Laboratory, a
major DOE contractor.
   Ms. Jurji said she is also dissatisfied by how long the work will
take, and what she perceives as the wrong attitude of the
scientists, who she said were too dispassionate at a recent
downwinder conference in Spokane.
   ``Not one person said one word of sympathy or indicated any sort
of compassion,'' she said. ``They were looking like the kind of
scientists who might have given us the problems in the first place.''
   The CDC study will try to determine if there are higher rates of
thyroid disease in the region, and whether that is caused by
iodine-131, which attacks the thyroid. But even that won't yield
conclusive answers in individual cases.
   ``There is no way of measuring or detecting how somebody got
cancer,'' Thomas said. ``A lot of health effects are separated from
the exposure by 20 to 40 years.''
   Delbert Barth of the University of Nevada-Las Vegas, a member of
an independent panel overseeing the dose reconstruction project,
said at a recent meeting that it is wrong to think the study will
produce a firm number for radiation exposure the public received.
   There will only be estimates, with wide margins of error,
scientists say.
   Hanford was built in south central Washington in 1943 during the
Manhattan Project. The world's first full-sized nuclear plant, B
Reactor, was erected in a frenzied 15 months, and produced plutonium
for the Nagasaki bomb. Seven other plutonium reactors built along
the Columbia in the 1940s and '50s, all are shut permanently. A
ninth reactor, the N Reactor, was built in 1963 and is closed
because of a plutonium surplus.
   The releases were revealed when the Energy Department released
19,000 pages of previously classified documents in 1986.
   Most of the early releases were deliberate, from normal nuclear
operations for the time. But one release, the 1949 ``Green Run,'' is
notorious because an unknown amount of radioactivity was released so
its path could be charted.
   The term ``Green Run'' refers to faster processing of irradiated
nuclear fuel into plutonium. It was processed after just 16 days of
cooling, instead of the normal 40. The exact mission of the research
is unknown, though scientists have said it was to aid in monitoring
nuclear production in the Soviet Union.
   No one knows exactly how much was released, although recent
estimates are about 8,000 curies, twice what experimenters
originally planned.
   Much of the ``Green Run'' report remains classified.
   ``The main answer we are still looking for is why the Green Run
was done, who authorized it and how could it happen in a democratic
society,'' Thomas said. He wonders why the public wasn't told to
take precautions _ like staying indoors and evacuating pregnant
women _ during the December 1949 experiment.
   The dose reconstruction project's initial report is due early
next year and will deal with 10 counties in eastern Washington and
northeastern Oregon, said John Till, head of the oversight panel. It
will cover 1944-49 releases into the air, and 1963-64 releases of
cooling water into the Columbia River.
   Radiation releases aren't a thing of the past at the
560-square-mile site. While off-site radiation is negligible, 50
million gallons of radioactive and hazardous waste from plutonium
processing is still dumped each day.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 15</NOTE>
