<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--School:ClassroomTV     06-12 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Classroom TV,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: Classroom TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Couch potatoes in the classroom?
   It's a likely scenario this fall as more and more cable networks
tout educational offerings specifically designed as teaching aids.
   The competition took off in controversy with the debut of Channel
One, a flashy 12-minute newscast with two commercials. Cable News
Network soon weighed in with a news program minus the ads, followed
by the Discovery Channel with a five-day-a-week documentary package
available for taping.
   And that doesn't include other school-oriented programs from
C-SPAN, The Learning Channel and the Arts and Entertainment network.
   The offerings range from live public events and congressional
coverage on C-SPAN to nature films and historical documentaries on
Discovery. The Learning Channel featured vintage films like ``Oliver
Twist'' and ``A Farewell to Arms'' on a program designed to
encourage reading of the classics.
   And then there are the rival news programs from CNN and Whittle
Communications, producer of Channel One.
   Whittle conducted a $5 million, seven-week test run in six
schools last spring, with candy bars, shampoo and jeans among the
products advertised. Company officials are determining whether to
launch the program in 8,000 schools in 1990 _ a $100 million project.
   The trial run drew fire for a number of reasons. Educators
objected to inflicting ads on a captive audience. They also
complained that the program, heavy on graphics and hip teen-age
anchors, was superficial.
   ``Channel One is social studies by 90-second sound bites,''
charged Scott Thomson, executive director of the National
Association of Secondary School Principals. Furthermore, he said,
the program ``allows special interests to reach kids through
television commercials which they are forced to watch.''
   Christopher Whittle, chairman of Whittle Communications, says the
ads are necessary to finance the $50,000 in satellite dishes, TVs
and VCRs given to schools that promise to show his program daily.
   ``Were this a perfect world, we would agree that the government,
not commercials, should provide this technology and programming,''
Whittle wrote in a New York Times op-ed piece. ``But in today's real
world of $20 textbook budgets and tough fiscal constraints, two
minutes of appropriate advertising is not a bad solution.''
   Whittle suffered a blow in May when the California department of
education said the state could not be billed for education funds for
time students spent watching commercials in class. ``Such time will
be deleted from the certification,'' the department said in a legal
opinion.
   The department also said that ``the imposition of forced
commercial advertising'' on schoolchildren may violate the state
constitution.
   Educators and TV watchdogs are reacting more favorably to the
daily ``CNN Newsroom,'' due to start Aug. 14 in time for the fall
school term _ a full year before Channel One would be available in
classrooms across the country.
   They note that CNN is a legitimate news operation, the 15-minute
program would feature adult anchors, and use of it in the classroom
would be voluntary and at the teacher's discretion. Perhaps most
important of all, CNN founder Ted Turner decided at the last minute
to ditch the commercials initially planned for the package.
   Turner says ``CNN Newsroom'' will cost millions of dollars but
CNN is profitable enough to absorb the expense. Whittle's venture
would be a money-maker, while Discovery _ with its daily, hour-long
``Assignment: Discovery'' _ expects to break even by enlisting
corporate and foundation underwriters.
   The Discovery underwriters will be identified onscreen, but their
names will never interrupt either of the two educational segments
planned for each hour. Thus students will never have to see the
sponsorship billboards.
   The education community has reserved its highest praise for the
Discovery series, which starts Sept. 18. For one thing, it is
divided into systematic, teacher-friendly curriculum blocks. Social
studies teachers, for example, will know that documentaries in their
field are shown on Tuesdays.
   Furthermore, the network is getting educational rights to each
program so teachers can tape segments at their convenience and use
them if and when they want. Teachers consequently remain in control
of what happens in their classrooms, rather than being forced to
show a daily program _ such as Channel One _ that may or may not be
the best use of time that day.
   ``If there are ways to provide this technology when, where and
how the teacher feels it best enhances instruction, discussion and
comprehension, then it is to be applauded,'' said Manya Ungar,
president of the National PTA. ``If it doesn't, it's a detriment.''
</TEXT>
