<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Evaluation,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: Evaluating a College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   With an investment of four years and probably more than $50,000,
choosing the right college is far from a trivial decision.
   Alice Ilchman, president of Sarah Lawrence College in Bronxville,
N.Y., has this advice for parents and aspiring collegians:
   _ Sit in on a class or two. Are the students involved? Are you?
Is there opportunity to participate?
   _ Speak with the faculty. Look for faculty office hours or ask
the admissions office to make an appointment for you. Ask why they
chose to teach at this college and what they find rewarding about it.
   _ Wander around the campus. Are the buildings well-maintained?
Are they open and available to students? What is on the notice
boards?
   _ Check out the bookstore. Does it emphasize books, or just
sweatshirts and beer mugs?
   _ Look at the library. Are students using it? Are they awake?
   _ Learn about the students. What are they talking and thinking
about? Do they like being there? What percentage of students
graduate?
   _ Talk with your child. Listen to his view of himself and how he
thinks a particular college will let or help him develop.
   ``One thing I've learned as a parent and educator is that our
children probably know more than we think they do,'' says Miss
Ilchman. ``Guide, discuss, question, but trust the final judgment of
that budding student.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
