<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--School:Motivation     06-12 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Motivation,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: ^Motivating Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE FOREST, ILL. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some teen-age achievers say motivation
and care are needed to help their less brilliant classmates learn
more and prepare for life.
   Class size and individual attention are seen as important, and
the teens think that while more money for schools is needed, it's
not as important as the other factors.
   These attitudes were revealed by a poll of students listed in
``Who's Who Among American High School Students'' organized by its
publishers.
   ``A lot of students in my school aren't motivated to learn,''
reports Matt Henry of Florissant, Mo., one of the students. Henry
says motivating students is a shared responsibility of students,
teachers and parents. ``It's up to students to make an effort, but
it's also up to teachers to present material in a way that's
interesting and relevant to today's world.''
   Colleen Boyle of Twinsburg, Ohio, also thinks parental
involvement is important. ``My parents have always shown a lot of
interest in my academic progress as well as my extracurricular
activities, and it's been a big boost in helping me go forward. Some
students aren't so lucky.''
   Large class size got poor marks from the students. ``In a large
school like mine, many students seem to graduate without the basic
knowledge needed to succeed,'' says Lindsey Taucher of Plano, Texas.
Adds Claudine Cangiano from Plandome, N.Y.: ``In a large high school
environment like mine, a student may feel like a number.''
   She also thinks schools rely too much on computers. ``They can
enhance the learning process, but they cannot replace teachers.
Individual attention is still important.''
   Todd DiSimone from Lockport, Ill., says that money spent on
higher teacher salaries will draw more and better candidates. ``Then
the overall quality of teaching might be higher.''
   But Ms. Cangiano disagrees, saying she thinks more money won't
make that much difference. ``Good teachers are those who love what
they do and will give it their all, regardless of how much they are
paid.''
</TEXT>
