<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--School:Dropouts     06-12 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Dropouts,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: Dropout Signs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A potential school dropout exhibits early warning signals that
can help his parents head off the problem.
   Unfortunately, many parents miss the signals and find themselves
surprised when the adolescent decides to drop out of school without
a diploma, says Glenn Hogen, vice president of Sylvan Learning
Corporation, a supplemental learning service.
   ``Children exhibit symptoms, even as early as first or second
grade, that signal trouble ahead and indicate the potential for a
dropout situation,'' he says.
   He advises parents to be alert to these warning signals and
intervene early with help from teachers, lay or religious
counselors, or medical authorities. ``Counselors can act as
intermediaries between parent and child and can accurately analyze
the extent of the problem,'' says Hogen.
   Some of signs he cites:
   A new pattern of dropping grades after a record of good grades.
   Teacher comments like ``not working up to potential,'' or ``does
not pay attention in class.'' The comment, ``is well-mannered in the
classroom,'' may be a euphemism for disinterest.
   Failure to complete homework.
   Lack of interest in sports or classroom activities.
   Behavioral problems such as fighting with other students or other
attempts to provoke expulsion.
   Negative comments about teachers.
   Blaming others.
   Becoming either passive or noisy.
   Hogen says the problem often develops after the student has
missed learning and finds he can't overcome the gap. As he falls
further behind, he gives up in frustration and anger.
   Positive things parents can do include reading and discussing
report cards in a non-judgmental way with the child; praising his
successes; communicating with teachers; asking the child for his
feelings and opinions and how he thinks he can improve; encouraging
him to develop realistic but challenging goals to improve study
habits; providing guidance and ground rules; and discussing _ not
grilling him _ about his progress and school activities weekly.
   ``Active listening is crucial. That means going beneath the words
to the meanings and emotions, or what children are not saying,''
Hogen says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--School:Summer     06-12 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Summer,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: Summer Vacation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The idea of summer vacation for children
should be re-examined, with summer activities _ whether school, a
job or camp _ arranged to fit the individual child, says a Los
Angeles psychologist.
   A whole summer of inactivity breaks the study chain, says Dr.
Robert R. Butterworth, a specialist in youth psychology. An
integrated program of work, study and leisure can be designed so
that what the child learns in the longer term doesn't get lost in a
summer dropoff.
   ``I'm not saying that kids shouldn't have a vacation. But for two
months and two weeks?''
   The problem is that many parents can't cope with deciding what
kind of plans to make for their children, he says. And the choices
they make often backfire, he adds.
   ``They don't know how to approach it directly. It's an emotional
situation,'' he says.
   For one thing, he says, there's no evidence that summer jobs will
help underachievers or problem children. The discretionary income
often distorts teens' focus, and often that income goes for drugs.
``Summer jobs won't turn them around.''
   And high achievers, the ones who usually go to summer school,
really don't need it, he says. ``Often the achievers need a break.''
   Good students need little or no supervision but need to be
encouraged to find a creative, change-of-pace summer activity,
including volunteer work.
   Average achievers also may benefit from volunteering, attending
academic camp, reading, or learning a new academic skill. The low
achiever _ usually a child who simply doesn't work up to his
capabilities _ should be steered to summer school and encouraged to
develop good study and work habits.
   Low achievers who also have drug, alcohol, or behavioral problems
need a very structured summer job or school program, according to
Butterworth. They need strict curfews, high supervision and perhaps
group treatment for their problems. ``For this group, too much free
time can be dangerous and can lead to trouble.''
   Unfortunately, youngsters who need the most help are the ones
least likely to get it, he says.
</TEXT>
