<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--School:Lunches     06-12 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Lunches,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: Lunches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Moderation in all things, including your kid's school lunch.
   Yes, be concerned about nutrition, but don't worry too much if he
pigs out occasionally.
   Obviously, you can exercise greater control over what he eats if
he's a brown bagger, but accept that his social needs are going to
take him now and then to fast food establishments whose menus
include high-fat items like hamburgers and thick milkshakes.
   There's no firm agreement among pediatricians and other health
care professionals about how much fat is too much, though they do
agree that children need fat for growth. About 30 to 40 percent of a
child's calories should come from fat, recommends the American
Academy of Pediatrics. That's close to the 34-39 percent spread
shown in a federal survey of the current diets of American children.
   ``I think run-of-the-mill parents should be aware that a high-fat
diet is not good,'' advises the academy's nutrition committee
chairman, Dr. Laurence Finberg. ``You don't need to say it any more
stringently than that.''
   Cholesterol levels in children now average about 160 milligrams
per deciliter of blood. Many doctors think a child would benefit
from a lower average; the target would be a level of 200 or lower by
the time the child reaches adulthood. ``We believe that the ideal
level of cholesterol in the blood would be between 110 and 140 for
children,'' says Dr. Curtis Ellison , a cardiologist at Boston
University Medical School.
   ``It's normal for kids to go through periods in which they eat
the same foods day in and day out,'' says David Mintz, whose
company, Tofutti Brands Inc., makes cholesterol-free foods. ``It
reflects emerging independent behavior and developing tastebuds.''
   He suggests offsetting these temporary ``food jags'' by making
sure that a variety of grains, fruits, vegetables, and protein foods
_ meats, poultry, fish and legumes _ are available at home meals.
And using the leftovers will enable parents to vary the contents of
the lunch bag.
   He also suggests preparing low-fat meals prepared at home on days
when the child has pizza at the school cafeteria or hamburgers at
the neighborhood hangout. And providing nutritional snack food to
substitute for the high-calorie, high-fat versions will encourage
children to eat sensibly. Some examples he cites include yogurt with
fresh fruit or cholesterol-free frozen desserts for sweets;
pretzels, popcorn or dry unsweetened cereal for munching; and
unsweetened fruit juices for beverages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0244 </DOCNO>
