<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--School:Writing     06-12 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Writing,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: Writing Magnet School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the belief that writing is the key to all
learning, the Crestview Elementary School teaches writing as its
main course from kindergarten to the fifth grade.
   Crestview students prefer writing to toys, says one of the
kindergarten teachers at this public magnet school. ``You give them
word games and a chance to write, and they get really into it.''
   The school calls itself the Center for Learning Through Writing,
and the principal, Jill Witlin, says that the intensified writing
program helps the students move ahead quickly. ``By writing,
children learn more and become more literate.''
   All subjects are taught within the context of writing. Children
are introduced to vocabulary relevant to the subject and encouraged
to form sentences with these words. Spelling and grammar are
fine-tuned later.
   ``When you know how to write, you get to learn all the other
aspects of literacy,'' says Dr. Evelyn Rothstein, who with Dr. Diane
Gess created the Write Track program the school uses.
   Based in Nyack, N.Y., both these experienced educators visit
schools with the Write Track system, training teachers how to use
it. They also provide complementary classroom materials.
   Programs are in place in schools especially committed to
improving literacy skills _ such as public schools in Clovis, N.M.,
Moss Point, Miss., and New York City. Crestview is unusual in that
it uses the program as the key part of its magnet school approach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
