<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--School:Mathematics     06-12 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Mathematics,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: Math Literacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   America's widespread math illiteracy might be less of a problem
if parents became more involved in their children's math education,
according to a Chicago learning authority.
   ``Many theories have been propounded on why U.S. youngsters
appear to have problems coping with math,'' says Robert Baseman,
president of the American Learning Corp., a division of
Encyclopaedia Britannica, Inc.
   ``What it comes down to, however, is the need for parents to be
more directly involved in their children's math training. We think
there is reason for optimism if youth and parents work together.''
   Baseman's optimism is based on observations in other countries
where parents frequently become deeply involved in their children's
math education.
   In these situations, he explains, if a child faces problems his
parents are then in a better position to detect the whys and
wherefores needed to solve the problems.
   The shortcomings of U.S. mathematics standards have been
underscored in recent reports finding American students being
outperformed by their counterparts in four other countries _ South
Korea, Spain, Ireland and the United Kingdom _ and four Canadian
provinces.
   One way to apply parent power to the math illiteracy problem is
to incorporate a sense of fun into the process, says Baseman.
   When you take a child shopping, he suggests, let him help weigh
produce, count change and price the best buy.
   If a child has missed school, try to learn what math concepts
were taught when he or she was absent, Baseman adds, because failure
to learn a concept when it is taught can hamper future performance.
   Baseman also suggests:
   _ When planning a long-distance vacation or other trip by car,
have your child use road maps to determine the number of miles to
your destination.
   _ When baking or cooking, have your child help by reading
directions on packages and measuring incredients into bowls. Let
them become familiar with measuring spoons and cups.
   _ Have your child log how his or her allowance money is spent
during a particular period _ say, vacation time or over the summer
months. Based on money received, and money spent, your child should
be able to determine the percentage of money saved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
