<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--School:Spending     06-12 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--School: Spending,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More public school funding does not necessarily mean improved
student performance, says a University of Rochester (N.Y.) economist.
   ``There is little if any relationship between differences in
spending and the quality of schooling,'' says Professor Eric
Hanushek in a recent issue of Educational Researcher magazine.
   ``It's tempting to believe that the amount of money spent on
education will determine how well students will perform,'' he says.
``The logic is compelling: We figure that with more money, we can
attract better teachers, create superior programs, and reduce
classroom overcrowding so that students can get more individualized
instruction.
   ``Unfortunately, this strategy by itself has not led to
significant improvements in students' achievements.''
   Family background, he says, has a major influence on students, as
does the skill of their teachers.
   ``There is no substitute for good teachers,'' he says, but
``differences in teacher skill are not strongly related to
educational backgrounds, amount of teaching experience, or teaching
in small classes.''
   Hanushek says schools should direct their attention to the actual
performance of teachers through such incentives as merit pay.
   Hanushek, former deputy director of the Congressional Budget
Office, analyzed 187 separate studies of students' performance at
primary and secondary schools during the past 20 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
