<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Schools: Briefs</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP LaserPhotos NY703, NY704</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't stress your child by arranging too many after-school
activities, advises a child psychiatrist.
   ``Time to play and to relax is important. Without constant
pressure to succeed, eventually a child may even hook into genuine
interests,'' says Dr. Richard Oberfield, clinical associate
professor of psychiatry at New York University Medical Center.
   Parents should ask themselves if they are providing lessons and
activities for themselves instead of the child, he advises. ``If you
always wanted to play three musical instruments, but couldn't, don't
force that dream on your children. It's one thing to introduce them
to opportunities to learn and quite another to make them mandatory.''
   It's important for parents to spend unstructured time with their
children, he adds. ``This gives them the feeling of being cared
about for themselves, not just for their performance, which is
integral to their self-esteem.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elementary school children in Cincinnati, Chicago, Atlanta,
Dallas and Kansas City will be learning some basics about weather
reporting and forecasting when tags are returned from finders of a
series of balloons they released in May.
   The science project, the Lucky Charms Red Balloon School Science
Project, is sponsored by the manufacturer of Lucky Charms cereal,
who recruited meteorologist Jon Lehuta to talk to children at each
launch site in May. Children were able to view the balloons in
flight with a theodolite telescope. Tags returned from finders of
the balloons will tell how far the balloons traveled and who found
them.
   Lehuta says that the project will help children learn basic
weather skills. ``They also can learn how to ask meaningful
questions, collect data accurately, organize information, use
observations to answer questions _ and have fun doing it.''
</TEXT>
