   The omnibus title, ``World Politics of Peace and War,'' covers
the study regimen for this fall's International Honors Program,
based in Boston.
   Thirty students will tackle this issue, under the leadership of
Johan Galtung, during an eight-month tour to meet experts in foreign
countries, including the Soviet Union, Germany, Israel, Egypt,
India, Thailand and Japan. In the process, they will earn 36 credits
from Bard College, with which IHP is affiliated.
   Joan Tiffany, director of IHP, says research and study areas also
include human needs; human rights and the environment; culture,
peace and war; theories of peace; theories of conflict; and
Ghandism. The IHP is in its 35th year and is open to students from
all colleges.
