<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Back to School: 1st add Briefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The average annual income for college students in the United
States is more than $6,000, according to a nationwide survey based
on syndicated research and interviews with 1,200 full-time students
at 30 colleges and universities.
   The study was conducted for American Express by CollegeTrack, a
market research and consulting firm.
   The survey indicated the average student had $155 in monthly
discretionary spending, with 65 percent having savings accounts, 19
percent owning stocks, 19 percent owning bonds and 14 percent with
certificates of deposit.
   Fifty-one percent of all students had a credit or charge card.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Ballet star Mikhail Baryshnikov is launching a new line of
bodywear for children called ``Baryshnikov for Kids.''
   ``Children are the future of dance,'' Baryshnikov says, ``whether
they grow up to be great professionals or enthusiastic amateurs.
Bodywear that fits like a second skin and athletic-inspired fabrics
that don't restrict movement are important elements in this new
line.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   According to the Washington-based American Institutes for
Research (AIR), the best way to get ready for a test is to study
from the beginning of the course, preparing for a test gradually _
which lets the student absorb the material, make connections between
concepts and draw conclusions.
   ``Studying each subject every night will save the agony of having
to cram on the night before a test,'' advises AIR, which operates a
bibliographic data base on tests, measurement and evaluation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   What a teacher wears in the classroom affects the response of her
students, but the result may not be as expected.
   A Miami University study shows that most students prefer a
teacher who wears jeans over the one who wears a suit.
   ``You might anticipate that a female teacher in a suit would get
the most respect, but my research doesn't show that,'' says Dr. Sara
Butler, associate professor of home economics and consumer sciences
at Miami's Oxford, Ohio, campus. Butler and a graduate student,
Kathy Roesel, surveyed 201 students at two northern Kentucky high
schools to find out how female teachers' clothes affect them. There
were 157 girls and 44 boys in the study.
   ``The teacher in jeans was generally viewed as fun, approachable,
not especially knowledgeable, not looking like a teacher and
generally preferable,'' says Butler. Curiously, that teacher was
seen as least fair when it came to grades.
   ``In contrast, the suited teacher was seen as possessing the
image of a teacher but was the teacher students preferred not to
have. This teacher was seen as unapproachable, not especially fun
and an authority figure who assigns homework.''
</TEXT>
