<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 0931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UndergroundAtlanta 1stLd-Writethru f0019 06-12 1100</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Underground Atlanta, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0019,1126</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Lot's On The Line As Underground Atlanta Opens _ Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS led to CORRECT to next month sted this week. A version
moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Often derided as ``a nice place to live, but you
wouldn't want to visit,'' Atlanta tries one more time this week to
amuse conventioneers and capture its soul as Underground Atlanta
opens for business _ again.
   Seven years after the lights went out, ostensibly for good, the
entertainment and shopping playground beneath downtown is set to
open Thursday after a three-year overhaul under the auspices of The
Rouse Co., the wizards of American urban reclamation.
   In its prime, Underground Atlanta was Atlanta's answer to the
French Quarter, created in old storefronts that were the city's
heart before a network of bridges over railroad tracks literally
raised downtown one level.
   Underground had swinging Dixieland, loud rock 'n' roll, cool
jazz, fine eateries, chic watering holes _ even a shop where
segregationist restaurateur-turned-governor Lester Maddox signed
autographs and sold souvenirs.
   Underground opened in 1969, peaked in 1972, was struggling by
1975, and was gone by 1982. It was eulogized as the victim of crime
_ or a perception thereof _ derelicts, subway construction, ripoff
merchants and changing times. There were dozens of theories about
what went wrong, but seemingly no answers.
   Without it, downtown Atlanta has acquired the reputation of a
ghost town after dark, which has been an albatross around the neck
of the city's thriving convention industry. While conventioneers sit
in gleaming downtown hotels, real Atlantans are miles away in the
biracial city's largely white suburbs.
   In 1985, the city signed the deal for a $142 million
rerevitalization. It turned to Rouse, the people responsible for
Boston's Faneuil Hall Market Place, Baltimore's Harborplace, New
York's South Street Seaport, among other projects.
   ``We're trying to create a town center for metropolitan Atlanta,
back to the birthplace of Atlanta,'' said Joseph G. Martin Jr.,
president of the Underground Atlanta development company. ``We want
it to be a place ... where visitors will come to find out about what
Atlanta has to offer, but where also the hometown crowd can feel
some sense of identity.''
   Mayor Andrew Young sees the new Underground as ``one of the most
significant accomplishments'' of two terms in office. ``This
represents a new heart for Atlanta. It represents a gathering place
for the entire metro area.''
   The new Underground is on and around the original site, on
downtown's south side, just blocks from the high-rise hotel
district. It's three times the size of the old Underground; visitors
will find 22 restaurants and nightclubs and nearly 100 retailers.
While the emphasis on retailing marks a change for Underground, the
entertainment focus is something new for Rouse.
   ``We've never done this strong an entertainment aspect to any of
our urban places,'' said William M. Coleman, vice president and
general manager of Rouse-Atlanta, the Rouse affiliate created to run
the project.
   ``Some of that is due to the name,'' he said. ``Underground
Atlanta has probably the highest name recognition of any project
we've ever touched ... and what Underground Atlanta was known for
was entertainment.''
   Rouse officials anticipate 10 million to 11 million visitors a
year, half of them out-of-towners. They say there are enough office
workers and convention-goers downtown to meet three-fourths of
Underground's needs.
   Even so, Martin said, ``The real test of whether the project
succeeds ... is whether the project appeals to residents. The
obvious concern _ what a lot of people talk about around here _ is
security.''
   That's because the old Underground came to be regarded as
dangerous.
   Dante Stephensen, whose Dante's Down The Hatch jazz club and
restaurant anchored the old Underground, said, ``At its worst,
Underground had a lower crime rate than Lenox Square (a popular
mall). But downtown areas can't protect themselves from bad
publicity.''
   Clearly, this time around Underground must be perceived as safe.
   ``We've taken a common-sense approach,'' Martin said. A squad of
some 30 private guards will patrol, accompanied by Atlanta police,
who are building a 34-officer substation there. Planners have made
sure there are no blind alleys, and lighting designers have made it
bright enough to read at midnight.
   Martin admits to being irked that he is repeatedly asked what
Underground will do to keep out ``undesirables.'' ``First, tell me
who the `undesirables' are. This is a town center. It's open to
everyone. If a person comes to Underground and happens to look
different, that's fine. If a person starts to infringe on somebody
else's rights, that's not fine.''
   A no-nonsense security policy seems to have wide public appeal.
Where city officials triggered a storm of criticism with a plan to
run vagrants out before last year's Democratic National Convention,
hardly anything has been heard from anyone concerned about
loiterers' civil rights in Underground.
   ``I don't see it as a problem,'' Coleman said. ``The biggest
problem is in perception, and that perception problem goes away as
people come here and have a good time and find out they aren't
hassled.''
   ``I would be surprised,'' Martin said, ``if Underground is not
the safest place in the whole Atlanta area.''
   It had better be. The city has sunk more than $80 million in
revenue bonds, as well as other public funding, into Underground. If
it flops, the city could be forced to cough up some $3 million a
year for 30 years.
   ``Underground is important symbolically, and it is a test of
whether a town center can work here, whether we have enough
cohesiveness,'' Martin said. ``Because if we continue to drift
apart, as we've been doing, there could be all sorts of consequences
_ economic, political, social and otherwise.''
   And although Rouse has relatively little capital invested, the
company's track record is on the line. ``It seems that each year,
the expectations get higher, as they see what's happened in other
cities,'' Coleman said.
   ``Rouse has taken slums and turned them into landmarks,'' said
Stephenson, who is reopening Dante's. ``And Underground Atlanta was
never as bad, at its worst, as any of those other areas were.''
   Project officials maintain there's virtually no way Underground
will fail.
   ``I'm convinced Underground is going to be a great success,''
Martin said, pointing out that while two developers put together the
first Underground on a shoestring, this time the city is landlord,
partner and major investor.
   ``The city leaders recognize how important it is, and they're not
going to let it fail,'' he said. ``They just can't.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
