<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UMWRally 3rdLd-Writethru f0014 06-12 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UMW Rally, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0014,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildcat Strikes Reported After UMW Head Announces Plans To Expand
Walkout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with number of affected miners
put in the thousands, quote from industry group, other detail. Picks up
8th graf pvs, We're here ... SUBS 13th graf pvs, Trumka had ..., to delete
extraneous word `expanded.' A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN GILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of coal miners refused to show
up for work today across southern West Virginia, after the head of
the United Mine Workers told cheering supporters that ``it's time
for labor to rise up and fight back.''
   A rally Sunday drew 12,000 people outside the state Capitol to
call attention to UMW's 2-month-old strike against the Pittston Coal
Group. This morning, several other mining companies reported
walkouts.
   Gary White, president of the West Virginia Coal Association, an
industry group, estimated that a third of the state's 30,000 miners
stayed home today, most of them in the southern part of the state.
There was no evidence the walkouts affected operations in other
states.
   In his speech to the rally Sunday, UMW President Richard Trumka
had pledged to widen the UMW's strike against Pittston, but there
was no answer early this morning at the UMW's headquarters in
Washington, or at the home of union spokesman Joe Corcoran.
   ``It's time for labor to rise up and fight bak,'' Trumka told
protesters. ``The 1990s will see us resisting like we did in the
'60s, in the streets, in the hallways, in the corridors of power.''
   David Todd, a spokesman for Hobet Mining in Madison, said union
miners did not report for work beginning with the midnight shift.
The walkout at Hobet probably is related to the Pittston strike, he
said, because his company has no pending disputes with the union.
Hobet employs nearly 500 miners.
   ``We have no picketers and no direct communications,'' Todd said.
``Beyond that, they have given us no notice that this is a memorial
period.''
   Miners are allowed a 10-day ``memorial period'' to stop work and
air grievances under the 1988 Bituminous Coal Operators Agreement,
which covers Hobet and most other coal companies, but not Pittston.
   Among the mines reporting no workers this morning were Omar
Mining in Laurel Creek, where 100 miners are employed, and Kess
Coals in Whitesville, which reported 55 miners out.
   ``We're here available for work whenever the men come out,'' said
Troy Wills, a supervisor at Kess.
   About 1,600 Pittston miners in Virginia and West Virginia walked
off the job in April over wage, benefit and rule disputes after
working for more than a year without a contract.
   The strike has slowed Pittston's production in Virginia, and all
but halted Pittston mining in West Virginia.
   Miners blocking roads at Virginia picket sites have landed more
than 2,000 union members and supporters in jail, and resulted in
millions of dollars in court-ordered fines against the union, whose
strike fund and liquid assets are dwindling.
   The rally culminated a six-day march by miners through southern
West Virginia.
   Trumka had refused to elaborate Sunday on his threat to expand
the strike, but left open the possibility of taking the walkout to
other parts of the country, including Kentucky, where about 200
Pittston miners remain on the job.
   ``Our government stands up and fights for freedom in Poland and
China,'' said Trumka, who led supporters to the Capitol in the final
leg of the march.
   ``Where are the cries of protest when it's an American worker
having his or her rights trampled?''
   West Virginia Gov. Gaston Caperton made an unscheduled appearance
at the rally, urging a compromise solution to the strike.
   ``The question before us is not who will win, but how all can
win,'' said Caperton, who was endorsed by the United Mine Workers in
last year's election.
   The rally included appearances by leaders of striking Eastern
Airlines employees and more than a dozen other local and national
unions. The grounds of the Capitol were turned into a sea of
camouflage green, the color of the uniform adopted by strikers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
