<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-China-Economy     06-12 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Economy,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Banker Says Unrest Will Damage Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BASEL, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Chinese banker said Monday that
China wanted to continue with its recent economic reforms despite
the bloody crackdown on pro-democracy protesters.
   ``We want to push our economic reforms forward,'' Chen Yuan,
deputy governor of the Bank of China, said at a meeting of the Bank
of International Settlements.
   ``It is a very urgent task for us that we see the economic and
political situation stabilize.''
   Chen said it would take several months before the full economic
impact of the strife becomes known.
   However, he acknowledged that the the civil unrest in Beijing and
other major Chinese cities already has caused widespread work and
transportation disruptions, increased food prices and led to anxiety
among Western investors and creditors about the prospects for future
investment in the country.
   Chen repeated assurances already made by other Chinese officials
that the country intends to honor all its obligations to foreign
creditors.
   ``I think there is absolutely not a problem in this field. We are
confident. The Bank of China has a very good reputation (with
foreign creditors),'' he said.
   Chen said that the cost of servicing China's estimated $30
billion foreign debt amounted to about 11 percent of China's foreign
income.
   He said inflation remained China's biggest economic problem, and
he estimated that retail prices in the first quarter of this year
rose at an annual rate of more than 20 percent.
</TEXT>
