<FIRST>r f PM-TennecoRestructuring     06-12 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tenneco Restructuring,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tenneco Announces Restructuring in Automotive Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc. today announced a restructuring of
its automotive parts unit, including the sale of its automotive
retail division and the acquisition of a Georgia brake manufacturing
plant.
   The transactions were designed to strengthen Tenneco's market
position in the automotive parts business and generate an estimated
$46 million in available cash, the company said in a statement.
   Under the plan, Tenneco Automotive agreed to sell its
Toronto-based retail division for more than $100 million to a group
of Canadian investors led by Stanley Goldfarb and Fred Karp,
chairman of Speedy Muffler King.
   The retail unit, which accounted for $260 million of the
automotive division's $1.7 billion in 1988 revenue, operates 709
muffler shops under the Speedy Muffler King, Car-X and Pit-Stop
names in five countries.
   In a related move, Tenneco said the automotive division also
completed the acquisition of a non-asbestos brake manufacturing
facility in Cartersville, Ga., from Interfriction USA and Friction
Materials Corp. of America for an undisclosed sum.
   The transactions follow the recently announced $100 million
acquisition of the suspension division of Armstrong Equipment PLC of
the United Kingdom, a manufacturer of ride control systems.
   ``To strategically position Tenneco Automotive for the
competitive decade ahead, we are initiating aggressive actions to
redeploy capital,'' said Tenneco Chairman James L. Ketelsen said in
a statement.
   Tenneco, a diversified manufacturer based in Houston, has
business interests in natural gas pipelines, farm and construction
equipment, shipbuilding, chemicals and minerals.
</TEXT>
