<HEAD>Grain Higher, Corn and Soybeans Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices were mostly higher, but corn
and soybeans mostly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Weather, specifically the rain over the weekend, was responsible
for both trends.
   The heavy rain in Texas, Oklahoma and the lower Midwest delayed
harvest of the winter wheat crop and helped support prices. But the
same storms reached into the corn and soybean belt of the upper
Midwest and nourished the still-developing crops in Iowa, Illinois
and Indiana.
   Hanging over the markets' head today is a winter wheat production
report scheduled for release after the close of trading. That
estimate is expected to show this year's crop declined by about 8
percent from last year.
   On the open, wheat was 1 cent lower to 2} cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.89\ a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 1} cents lower, with July at $2.50 a bushel; oats were 2} cents
to 3{ cents lower, with July at $1.59 cents a bushel; and soybeans
were 6{ cents to 9{ cents lower, with July at $6.96 a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures prices were mostly higher on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .5 cent lower to .33 cent higher, with June at
70.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .33 cent
higher, with August at 80.20 cents a pound; live hogs were .18 cent
lower to .13 cent higher, with June at 47.75 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent lower to .43 cent higher, with
July at 32.37 cents a pound.
