<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-IronWorkers     06-12 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Iron Workers,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeals By Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected appeals by an
international iron workers union and a local affiliate found to have
discriminated against black construction workers.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that a union
training program for granting journeyman status to workers was
biased against blacks.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled last April that the
International Association of Bridge, Structural and Ornamental Iron
Workers and Local 201 in the District of Columbia area practiced
illegal bias.
   Eight black rodmen _ construction workers who position steel rods
to reinforce building materials _ sued the union in 1975. Ten years
passed before a federal judge issued a ruling that found
discrimination.
   The appeals court upheld key portions of the judge's decision,
finding that blacks were victimized by a program that trained
apprentice workers to become journeymen.
   Qualifying as a journeyman was crucial for getting work,
particularly in the mid-1970s when commercial construction slumped
in the capital city area.
   The appeals court based its finding of discrimination largely on
statistical evidence that showed the training program had a
disproportionate impact in denying union admission to blacks.
   The black workers said the program created unnecessary barriers
that delayed or barred them from becoming journeymen even though
they were qualified.
   The parent union and its local argued that the real source of the
disparity was the higher percentage of blacks who dropped out of the
training program. But the appeals court said union officials failed
to meet their burden of disproving bias.
   ``Absent rebuttal, the fact of disproportionately high minority
dropouts demonstrates the effectiveness of the barrier to (union)
membership represented by Local 201's educational requirements,
particularly the training program,'' the appeals court said.
   It added that the union failed to explain why classroom training
is essential for becoming a journeyman for those arleady experienced
and able.
   The appeals court noted that for a brief period in 1971 workers
were allowed to take an exam to qualify as journeymen without
completing a training program.
   That proves that work experience alone can qualify one to be a
joureyman rodman, the appeals court said.
   The appeals court ruled that workers with 3,000 hours of
experience may take an exam to become journeymen without undergoing
any classroom instruction.
   The cases are International Association of Iron Workers vs.
Berger, 88-699, and Iron Workers Reinforced Rodmen vs. Berger,
88-820.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-USX     06-12 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-USX,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Sets Aside Discrimination Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today set aside a federal
appeals court ruling that USX Corp. illegally discriminated against
blacks at a Fairless Hills, Pa., steel mill.
   The justices told the Philadelphia-based 3rd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals to restudy the USX case in light of their decision last
week making it far more difficult for workers to win some job-bias
lawsuits.
   The appeals court had ruled that USX, formerly known as U.S.
Steel Corp., discriminated against blacks who applied for
non-skilled production and maintenance jobs at the steel mill.
   A federal judge in 1983 ordered USX to end all discrimination in
the hiring of production and maintenance employees at the Fairless
Hills mill, and awarded more than $12.3 million to those represented
by a class action suit.
   The judge ruled that statistics showing the disparity between the
percentages of black applicants and black hires proved that USX
violated a federal anti-bias law, known as Title VII of the Civil
Rights Act of 1964. But the judge said intentional discrimination
had not been proved.
   The 3rd Circuit court, in considering the ensuing cross-appeals,
ruled that both a Title VII violation and intentional discrimination
had been proved.
   The appeals court also ordered the trial judge to reconsider the
monetary award in a way USX lawyers said could raise the award to
``the range of $30 million.''
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for USX said the 3rd
Circuit court ruling means ``an employer's only protection against
Title VII liability is to adopt a quota system.''
   A very similar rationale was cited by the Supreme Court last week
when the justices, in a major civil rights decision, split 5-4 in
strengthening employers' defenses against charges of bias.
   The Fairless Hills mill, where 7,000 to 10,000 workers are
employed at a given time, hired 5,516 people _ including 977 blacks
_ to production and maintenance jobs in the years 1971-82.
   In those years, blacks represented 25.9 percent of the applicants
and 17.6 percent of the hires. Hiring was based on many subjective
criteria.
   The appeals court said statistical studies showed ``that USX's
hiring practice had a statistically significant adverse impact upon
blacks.''
   After finding that USX had no valid reason for the statistical
disparity, the appeals court ruled that the corporation also had
practiced intentional discrimination.
   The case is USX vs. Green, 88-141.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
