<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shares fell in London on Monday on news of a
faster-than-expected gain in British retail sales in May, which
fueled fears that British interest rates may be headed higher.
   But trading activity was light, as players were reluctant to
sell. Dealers said the market was gaining support from a recent
spurt of takeover speculation.
   Many players also were awaiting the U.S. trade report and British
inflation figure later this week.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 3.8
points, or 0.2 percent, to 2,138.3.
   Volume was 381.1 million shares, down from Friday's 528.2 million
shares.
   The retail sales figures showed volume up 2.5 percent in May from
April and up 4.1 percent from May 1988. That compared with market
expectations for a month-on-month rise of 0.8 percent and a
2.4-percent gain for the year.
</TEXT>
