<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-EEC-Soviet     06-12 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-Soviet,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Foreign Ministers OK Soviet Trade Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European foreign ministers Monday approved the
start of talks that could lead to increased trade and economic
cooperation between the European Economic Community and the Soviet
Union.
   Nico Wegter, spokesman for the 12-nation trading bloc, said the
foreign ministers gave a mandate for the talks to the European
Commission, the community's executive body.
   The talks will center on a number of areas, including science and
technology, economic, monetary and banking questions, environmental
protection and agriculture.
   Wegter said the EEC would be prepared to discuss cooperation in
nuclear research, including the safety aspects of nuclear energy.
   No specific timetable was set for the talks.
   In advance of the negotiations, the community and the Soviet
Union have held a series of meetings, described as exploratory
talks, designed to determine what each side would want in a trade
agreement.
   EEC officials said the Soviets indicated they would be interested
in an accord with the richer European countries in various areas,
including high technology. Transferring sensitive technology to
Moscow is restricted.
   The community, excluding Greece, imported nearly $13 billion
worth of goods from the Soviet Union last year and exported products
worth about $10 billion. The EEC had a 1988 trade deficit with
Moscow of nearly $3 billion.
   The trading bloc has been negotiating trade agreements with East
European countries.
   Last June, it established official relations with the Soviet-led
socialist economic bloc, known as the Council for Mutual Economic
Assistance, ending three decades of estrangement between Europe's
economic halves.
   Moscow's partners in Comecon are East Germany, Poland,
Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Bulgaria and Romania, plus Vietnam, Cuba
and Mongolia.
   Since then, the community has signed a trade and cooperation
agreement with Hungary and a trade accord in manufactured goods with
Czechoslovakia. Talks on trade pacts also have been held with
Poland, Bulgaria and East Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
