<FIRST>r f AM-Norway-Oil     06-12 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Oil,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Statoil To Sall Share in Norwegian Fields</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway's state oil company Statoil A-S
announced plans Monday to sell part of its holdings in an offshore
oil field for the first time.
   Statoil said it signed a letter of intent with Japan's Idemitsu
Oil Exploration to sell a 9.6 percent interest in two offshore
blocks covering parts of the Snorre and Statfjord East fields.
   The sale price of up to $214 million is linked to future oil
prices. The deal must be approved by Japan and Norway, which could
take up to four months, the company said in a statement.
   The sale would reduce Statoil's Snorre offshore field share to
41.8 percent, its lowest interest in any license awarded since 1973.
   Parliament in March said Statoil could reduce its stake from a
normal minimum of 50 percent to 35 percent in some cases. Reducing
its Snorre share could save Statoil about $270 million in field
development costs, officials siad.
   Statoil has cut costs and investments to improve its capital
base, which was reduced by low oil prices, high operating costs and
cost overruns at a refinery project.
</TEXT>
