<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-12 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Mostly Higher; Soybeans Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices were mostly higher, while
corn and soybeans were mixed to mostly lower Monday on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Weather, the dominant feature in the market, was behind both
trends. But the U.S. Agriculture Department's monthly crop estimate
on winter wheat production also had some effect.
   The report, scheduled for release after the close of trading, was
expected to show this year's crop declined by about 8 percent from
last year.
   ``Nobody figured the change would be a major one, but it still
made people want to square up their positions before it came out,''
said Ted Mao, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New
York.
   Heavy rain in Texas, Oklahoma and the lower Midwest delayed
harvest of the winter wheat crop and helped support prices
throughout the day.
   But the same storms reached into the corn and soybean belt of the
upper Midwest and nourished the still-developing crops in Iowa,
Illinois and Indiana. And with prices sliding for nearly four weeks,
several of the old-crop months in beans touched new contract lows.
   On the close, wheat was 1{ cents lower to 2\ cents higher, with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.88\ a bushel; corn was 2\
cents lower to 4 cents higher, with July at $2.49{ a bushel; oats
were 3{ cents to 4{ cents lower, with July at $1.58 cents a bushel;
and soybeans were 8{ cents to 11} cents lower, with July at $6.94 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
