<FIRST>r f AM-WPPSS-ChinaSale     06-12 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WPPSS-China Sale,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glenn Questions Possible Sale Of WPPSS Equipment To China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Glenn has warned the Bush
administration that the possible sale to China of millions of
dollars worth of surplus equipment from a closed nuclear plant could
violate a congressional resolution.
   Glenn, D-Ohio, said the sale even without the actual reactor from
the Washington Public Power Supply System plant would be worth $500
million.
   He warned that such a deal would violate a 1985 resolution
barring the sale of U.S. reactors or fuel to China until the
president had certified that China would abide by various nuclear
non-proliferation pacts.
   Glenn, in a letter to Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher
obtained Monday, said if such a deal was approved it would
``represent an extremely inauspicious beginning for the new
administration in the field of nuclear non-proliferation.''
   A staff member of the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
which Glenn chairs, said the Commerce Department subsequently told
the senator it would not issue any export licenses for the sale
until after consulting with the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   ``We have been told by Commerce they would withhold any further
action until they hear from the NRC,'' said the staffer, who asked
not to be named.
   A spokesman for the Commerce Department's Bureau of Export
Administration declined immediate comment.
   A spokesman for the supply system at its Richland, Wash.,
headquarters said WPPSS has been trying for several years to sell
equipment from its terminated No. 5 plant to the Chinese, but export
licenses from the federal government had to be secured first.
   Spokesman Gary Petersen said the supply system would like export
licenses to sell the plant's actual reactor, 250,000 pounds of
nuclear fuel and what is called the ``balance of the plant''
including its turbines.
   Both plants, beset with enormous cost overruns and years behind
schedule, were terminated in the early 1980s when new forecasts
showed the power they would produce wouldn't be needed.
   Petersen declined to comment on Glenn's $500 million pricetag for
the sale.
   Glenn wrote Mosbacher early last month before the Chinese
government cracked down on student protesters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
