<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PrimeComputer     06-12 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Decision on Prime Computer Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge reserved decision Monday on a
motion to force Prime Computer Inc. to hold its annual meeting this
month so shareholders can vote on a challenge from hostile bidder
MAI Basic Four Inc.
   MAI Basic argued in Chancery Court that Prime violated state law
by delaying the annual meeting.
   Prime, based in Natick, Mass., originally scheduled the meeting
for May 12, but postponed it until June 14 and again until July 26.
Tustin, Calif.-based MAI Basic is seeking an injunction to force the
Wednesday meeting.
   Both companies are incorporated in Delaware.
   MAI Basic, which originally offered $20 per share for Prime,
lowered its offer June 1 to $19.50 per share. The new offer values
Prime at about $975 million, down from $1.3 billion in cash.
   MAI Basic attorney Michael Goldman said postponement of the
annual meeting violated corporate law that requires an annual
meeting to be held within 13 months of the previous meeting. Prime's
last annual meeting was May 1988.
   Goldman argued the delay prohibits shareholders from voting on a
new board of directors and on whether to accept MAI Basic's offer.
   Prime attorney Paul K. Rowe said the meeting was changed because
of MAI Basic's revised offer, adding that the company wanted about a
month ``to develop new alternatives'' to ward off a takeover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
