<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 1720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Northwest     06-12 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Pilots Threaten Strike Amid Takeover Offers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union pilots at Northwest Airlines on Monday
threatened to strike if its parent company, NWA Inc., is taken over
by a buyer who would saddle the carrier with debt.
   ``This letter is to serve notice that our concern for the
long-term survival and success of Northwest Airlines must be the
cornerstone of any new contract,'' leaders of the 5,000-member Air
Line Pilots Association said in the letter addressed to all bidders
and the company's board of directors.
   ``Excessive debt incurred in connection with any transaction
involving Northwest Airlines or NWA Inc. is something we simply will
not accept,'' the pilots said in the letter, published as an ad in
the Wall Street Journal. ``We may have no choice except to take
whatever action we can to ensure the continued growth and prosperity
of'' the carrier.
   H.T. Dodge and Kirk Faupel, co-chairman of the union, said ``a
pilot strike will be inevitable'' if their concerns are not resolved.
   The pilots are the only union at Northwest with an open contract.
About half of the pilots are working under a three-year agreement
signed with the old Northwest Orient in 1983.
   The other half are working under terms of a 1984 contract signed
with Republic Airlines, which Northwest acquired in the fall of
1986. The old Republic contract ran out in 1987.
   The letter said too much debt would render Northwest Airlines a
``financially crippled second-tier carrier, ill equipped to meet the
challenges of business cycles, the economic and safety demands of
fleet replacement, and the global competitive threat of
government-subsidized foreign mega-carriers.''
   A message to pilots recorded on Friday said mediated talks with
Northwest management are scheduled to resume Tuesday. The message
said significant progress has been made on a variety of contract
issues since May.
   A second round of bidding for Northwest Airlines comes to a close
Friday. Seven bidders representing a range of interests have already
submitted bids but other offers are possible.
   NWA should fetch in excess of $3.3 billion and perhaps more than
$3.6 billion, based on details of the offers made during the first
round. NWA's board has said it may decide to reject all offers.
</TEXT>
