<FIRST>r f AM-Farley-Cluett     06-12 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farley-Cluett,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Threatens `War' In Bid For Apparel Maker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A textile union said Monday it plans a joint bid
with a Tennessee businessman for apparel maker Cluett, Peabody &amp; Co.
and threatened that another buyer would ``risk being at war with
their own employees.''
   The Amalgamated Clothing &amp; Textile Workers Union said workers
would not cooperate with another buyer of the company that makes
Arrow shirts now owned by Farley Inc.
   ``We're here to put on notice other potential bidders, and the
lenders for these bidders, that we are unequivocally opposed to any
bids other than by the employees,'' said Garry Ferraris, an ACTWU
vice president.
   He said the union has joined with Nashville, Tenn., businessman
Spencer Hays, a publisher who owns several clothing businesses, to
prepare an offer for Cluett.
   Preliminary plans call for a leveraged buyout with Hays putting
up most of the cash and employees retaining about 30 percent of the
stock and a voice in major decisions affecting the compan, he said.
   Chicago-based Farley reportedly want to sells Cluett to help
erase some of the debt associated with its $3 billion acquisition of
West Point, Ga.-based WestPoint Pepperell Inc. earlier this year.
   Farley spokesman Jack Albertine was traveling Monday and could
not be reached for comment.
   Jay Meltzer, a textile industry analyst with Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.
in New York, said the union's action was unusual but should not
deter other potential bidders.
   Ferraris said employees are opposed to other bidders because
Cluett has changed hands twice in the last four years. It was
acquired by WestPoint Pepperell in 1985 and switched again in the
Farley deal.
   Ferraris said employees do not feel secure and a new owner could
shift Cluett jobs overseas. Ferraris said about five potential
bidders exist for Cluett, including the shirt manufacturer
Phillips-Van Heusen.
   The value of a union offer has not been determined, Ferraris
said. Dale Allen, an ACTWU leader, said the company has been valued
as high as $800 million.
   Ferraris said union leaders discussed their plans with Farley
Chairman William Farley. He said Farley indicated he wanted to allow
several parties to bid on Cluett.
   Cluett also manufactures Gold Toe socks and J. Schoeneman suits.
Its factories in Georgia, Alabama, Maryland, North Carolina,
Pennsylvania and Delaware employ more than 8,000 people.
</TEXT>
