<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold Bjt   06-12 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, Bjt,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Higher; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traders in Asia and Europe drove the dollar to
long-time highs against major foreign currencies on Monday,
increasing American buying power but further jeopardizing progress
on cutting the U.S. trade deficit.
   The dollar reached a 22-month high against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo and a 30-month high against the West German mark in Europe
before retreating slightly in U.S. trading.
   Gold prices recovered somewhat in U.S. trading after Friday's
steep plunge, which knocked prices down as much as $15 a troy ounce.
   Dealers cited several factors in the dollar rally, including the
image of the United States as a safe haven from political
uncertainty, but said market sentiment was the main force.
   ``This is not all psychological, although a good chunk of it is
psychological,'' said Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase
Manhattan Bank.
   The dollar rally could harm the U.S. economy as soon as the end
of the year by prompting companies to cut back on their spending on
new plants and equipment, Fine said.
   The companies would cut back, he said, out of a belief that the
strength of the dollar would reduce their ability to compete with
foreign manufacturers, although it is too soon to see such effects
yet.
   There were rumors that the Federal Reserve sold dollars in New
York trading in an attempt to restrain the U.S. currency, but the
supposed action had little effect.
   The Bank of Canada intervened in Europe, but no other central
banks were sighted, dealers there said.
   The latest phase of the dollar's climb gained strength Friday on
news of an unexpectedly large 0.9 percent increase in U.S. producer
prices in May. That strengthened expectations U.S. monetary policy
would remain tight for some time, sustaining high interest rates
that support demand for dollars.
   ``As far as I'm concerned this dollar is in a definite uptrend
and it's a question of the market looking around for the
fundamentals to explain it,'' said Susan Babcock, a chief corporate
foreign-exchange dealer at Marine Midland Bank.
   In London, the British pound tumbled nearly 3 cents, falling to
$1.5250 from $1.5545 late Friday. In New York, sterling fell to
$1.5285 from $1.5485 on Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 148.40 yen, up 4.90 yen from Friday and the
highest there since it closed at 148.55 yen on Aug. 18, 1987.
   Later, in London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 148.76 yen.
In New York the dollar closed at 148.46 yen, up from 146.49 on
Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 2.0195 West German marks, up from 2.0100; 1.7470
Swiss francs, down from 1.7475; 1.2011 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2015; 6.8420 French francs, up from 6.7987; and 1,460.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,457.80.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday:
2.0250 West German marks, up from 2.0025; 1.7550 Swiss francs, up
from 1.7402; 6.8620 French francs, up from 6.7810; 2.2835 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.2510; 1,463.50 Italian lire, up from 1,450.50;
and 1.2024 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1999.
   The mark closing in Europe was the highest since the dollar
closed at 2.0255 on Dec. 12, 1986.
   Gold prices fell in Asia and Europe, catching up with the drop
late Friday in New York. But they rose in New York from Friday's
lows.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell $1.47 a troy ounce to a bid of $359.03.
   Gold fell in London to $359.95 from late Friday's $363.25. In
Zurich, gold fell to a bid $359.00 from $368.05.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $361.90 a troy ounce from $358.10 on Friday.
   Later Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at
$360.70 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $357 on Friday.
   Silver bullion prices fell in London to a late bid of $5.20 a
troy ounce from Friday's $5.27. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.202 an ounce from $5.162.
</TEXT>
