<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market managed a mixed performance
Monday, benefiting from an afternoon comeback led by the blue chips.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed with a gain of
5.42, at 2,518.84 after trading in negative territory for much of
the session.
   Declining issues narrowly outnumbered advances in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 772 down, 714
up and 512 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 151.46 million
shares, down from 173.24 million in the previous session.
   Wall Street market watchers attributed the early setback to sales
aimed at collecting profits amassed during the recent advance
inspired by takeover speculation. Some of the early selling also was
due to trading maneuvers associated with stock index futures.
   Michael Metz, an analyst at Oppenheimer &amp; Co., said when the
market suffered its sinking spell early in the day, would-be buyers
were standing on the sidelines watching how far share prices would
fall.
   Before long, these hesistant investors began nibbling again at
stocks they considered attractive buys, said Metz.
   Analysts say the sentiment seems very positive toward stocks,
particularly because the dollar's surge has started drawing in
investment money from abroad. Declining interest rates also have
steered investors to equities.
   Much of the impetus for the rebound in the Dow Jones industrial
average came from a jump in Procter &amp; Gamble shares to a 52-week
high. The stock, driven higher by report of a favorable revision in
an analyst's earnings estimate, closed at 110|, up 5}.
   Takeover stocks also figured in the renewed buying. Time gained
4} to 175 as rumors of a new bid for the communications giant
rippled through the market. Paramount Communications, whose $10.7
billion-bid for Time has left Time's planned merger with Warner
Communications in limbo, fell 1~ to 57. Warner fell 1] to 54}.
   Burlington Resources topped the list of actively traded issues on
the Big Board, with more than 9.2 million shares changing hands.
Burlington Resources sported a gain of 1 at 44~; the company
confirmed that it has been buying back its shares in recent days.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business Machines
rose { to 108~, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was off [ at 36[ and
Eastman Kodak lost |, closing at 49}.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 178.22 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market was off $3.98 billion, or 0.12
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks ended
at 182.14, down 0.23.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 0.32 to 373.21, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index finished with a decline of 0.45 at 326.24.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
0.26 to 453.39. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 365.89, down 0.27.
