<FIRST>r f AM-Tenneco     06-12 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tenneco,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tenneco Announces Restructuring in Automotive Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc. said Monday it is selling its
Toronto-based automotive parts retail division for more than $100
million to a group of Canadian investors including the chairman of
Speedy Muffler King.
   Tenneco also also announced acquisition of an non-asbestos brake
manufacturing operation in Georgia as part of an automotive parts
division restructuring.
   Under the plan, Tenneco Automotive has agreed to sell its retail
division for more than $100 million to Canadian investors led by
Fred Karp, chairman of Speedy Muffler King.
   The retail unit, which accounted for $260 million of the
automotive division's $1.7 billion in 1988 revenue, operates 709
muffler shops under the Speedy Muffler King, Car-X and Pit-Stop
names in five countries.
   In a related move, Tenneco said the automotive division also
completed acquisition of a non-asbestos brake manufacturing facility
in Cartersville, Ga., from Interfriction USA and Friction Materials
Corp. of America for an undisclosed sum.
   Tenneco recently paid $100 million for the suspension division of
Armstrong Equipment PLC of Britain, which makes ride control systems.
   Tenneco said the transactions were designed to strengthen its
market position in the automotive parts business and generate an
estimated $46 million in available cash.
   Tenneco, a diversified manufacturer based in Houston, has
business interests in natural gas pipelines, farm and construction
equipment, shipbuilding, chemicals and minerals.
</TEXT>
