<FIRST>r f BC-PanAm-Security     06-12 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pan Am-Security,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Fires Frankfurt Airport Security Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am has fired its security chief at the
Frankfurt, West Germany, airport, but the airline said Monday the
action was unrelated to Flight 103, which crashed over Lockerbie,
Scotland, after a bomb smuggled aboard the plane exploded.
   The bomb, hidden in a radio-cassette player, exploded in midair
on Dec. 21, killing all 259 passengers and crew aboard the Pan Am
jumbo jet and 11 people on the ground. The flight originated in
Franfurt.
   Security chief Ulrick Weber was fired June 4 after anonymous
letters sent to Pan Am management accused him of misusing funds,
said Jeff Kriendler, a spokesman for Pan American World Airways at
its New York headquarters.
   ``We have indeed terminated his services,'' he said. ``It had to
do with the improper use of company funds for personal expenses.
   ``Some irregularities were brought to management's attention,''
Kriendler continued. `The company investigation revealed no evidence
that security was compromised by his personal misconduct.''
