<FIRST>r f AM-NorthrupInvestigation     06-12 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northrup Investigation,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northrop Corp. Division Under Investigation Over Defense Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents are investigating
Northrop Corp.'s Defense Systems Division here for possible
overcharging on military contracts, according to a published report.
   Company spokeswoman Maria Oharenko acknowledged the probe but
would not reveal its focus.
   ``We are aware of a government investigation and company
documents were subpoenaed,'' she said. ``We are working with the
government on the document request.''
   Agents from the U.S. Attorney's office visited the Defense
Systems Division in this Chicago suburb last week seeking documents
related to the probe, she told the Daily Herald in Arlington Heights.
   The newspaper reported last weekend that the probe involves
accusations that Northrop improperly billed the government for
defense work.
   Unidentified sources within the Defense Systems Division told the
paper they believe the probe centers on allegations that the
government was overcharged for labor and materials under certain
contracts.
   The investigation comes as parent Northrop Corp. in Los Angeles
faces a 167-count criminal indictment charging it supplied defective
parts and falsified test results on critical components of Air Force
cruise missles and Navy AV-8B Harrier jets.
   Ms. Oharenko said the local investigation is not related to that
criminal indictment.
   The Defense Systems Division, which makes radar-jamming equipment
for military aircraft, employs about 4,000 people at its
headquarters in Rolling Meadows and two other facilities in nearby
Arlington Heights and Elk Grove Village.
   The division produces systems to shield B-52 and B1-B bombers and
F-15 fighter jets from detection by enemy radar. It has suffered
from cutbacks in military spending and over the past year, and has
reduced its work force by more than 1,000 people through layoffs and
attrition.
</TEXT>
