<FILEID>AP-NR-06-12-89 2039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CleanAir-Autos     06-12 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air-Autos,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carmakers Say They Can Meet Pollution Curbs With New Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers said Monday they could develop
methanol-fueled vehicles to meet President Bush's clean-air
proposals but wonder if people are likely to buy them.
   Some practical hurdles the Big Three automakers cited including
making the fuel available, making methanol-powered engines start
better in cold weather and cutting their formaldehyde emissions.
   The cars can be made, said Kelly Brown, Ford Motor Co.'s
executive engineer in charge of fuel economy and emissions, but
``it's another thing to sell them.''
   ``Some people, when new technology comes out, want to be first on
board, and some want to sit back and wait and see how everyone else
does with it. Those are the ones we're worried about.''
   Bush called on Congress in a White House speech Monday to require
automakers to put 500,000 alternative-fuel vehicles in operation in
nine high-smog urban areas by 1996, and 1 million such vehicles a
year after that.
   Unlike gasoline, methanol does not produce the hydrocarbons and
nitrogen oxides that are an ingredient in the ozone that causes smog
problems in nearly 100 metropolitan areas.
   Bush also proposed cutting tailpipe emissions from automobiles by
40 percent and curbing other automobile fuel-related pollutants.
   Environmental Protection Agency Administrator William K. Reilly
said Bush's proposals to cut acid rain and industrial and automotive
smog would let all but the most severely polluted areas _ Los
Angeles, Houston and New York City _ meet federal air quality
standards by the year 2000.
   ``It is a tough proposal, but it does take into account some of
the technical difficulties we would face in meeting it,'' said
Harold A. Poling, Ford's vice chairman and chief operating officer.
   Any tighter standards probably would be unattainable and would
bring little improvement in air quality, Poling said.
   Ford favors a pilot program to resolve technical questions before
trying to switch to alternative fuel vehicles, he said.
   William H. Noack, a General Motors Corp. spokesman in Washington,
said GM also favors a pilot program.
   Noack said details will have to be fleshed out in ensuing
legislation and regulations. ``Just generally speaking, as you look
at the proposal, there is a good deal of flexibility in there,'' he
said.
   At Ford, Brown said engineers are trying to improve cold starting
of methanol engines and cut formaldehyde emissions, which are about
four times as high as from a gasoline engine.
   Chrysler Corp. questioned the speed of the program in a statement
issued by spokeswoman Karen Stewart. ``For example, it is not clear
how an abundant supply of alternate fuels will be produced and
distributed at prices attractive to the consumer,'' she said.
   Chrysler spokesman Ben Dunn said his company will deliver 10
vehicles fueled by an 85-percent methanol, 15-percent gasoline mix
to Southern California later this year for two years of tests in
fleet use.
   Dunn said methanol vehicles need larger tanks for the same travel
range as gasoline vehicles, and it remains unclear if methanol will
have corrosive effects on fuel system components in the long run.
</TEXT>
